<HEADLINE> Airlines Warned on Y2K Exclusions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. airlines are being warned against seeking  
exclusions that would prevent their insurance policies from 
covering claims passengers may file due to problems stemming from 
the Year 2000 computer glitch. 
</P>
<P>
	The Transportation Department, in a statement issued Tuesday,  
also urged airlines to ensure that their computers and planes will 
not be affected by Y2K problems on New Year's Eve. 
</P>
<P>
	The department said it had warned airlines that ``some aviation  
insurers wish to write into insurance policies a clause that would 
exclude liability for all damages related to Y2K problems, and that 
some carriers already may have had similar exclusions written into 
their policies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It added: ``The department has not approved any Y2K insurance  
exclusion.'' It said it approves exclusions only in rare cases, 
such as for war risk. 
</P>
<P>
	The Year 2000 problems stems from a common programming practice  
in which computer software recognizes dates in a two-digit format, 
such as ``99'' for the year 1999. There is widespread concern that 
unless computers are repaired, some will malfunction at the end of 
this year when the century changes, since they may interpret the 
new year as 1900 instead of 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Aviation administration recently tested its  
computers and radar systems to ensure that they will not 
malfunction. The Boeing Co. also issued a statement recently 
repeating that its planes will not be affected. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. airlines have given reassurances that passenger flights  
will not be affected. 
</P>
<P>
	Under federal law, all U.S. and foreign air carriers -- including  
commuter airlines and air taxis -- are required to carry minimum 
aircraft accident liability insurance coverage for bodily injury to 
or death of aircraft passengers or other people and for property 
damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Minimum coverage amounts depend on the class of the carrier and  
the size of its aircraft. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
