<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Delicate Diplomacy at NATO Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Details, details: For the State Department's  
office of protocol, taking proper care of the leaders of 42 foreign 
countries at this week's NATO summit is a logistical nightmare of 
motorcades, seating assignments, flags and music. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest headaches: Who should sit next to President Clinton  
at dinner? (Still unclear). And how to hang the flags? 
(Alphabetically.) 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to try to stay calm. It works better that way,''  
said Chief of Protocol Mary Mel French, her laugh masking the hours 
of frenzied planning her office is doing for Washington's 
largest-ever gathering of heads of state. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. French's staff must make sure that the limousines run on  
time, that guests are property attired, that cultural barriers are 
bridged and visitors not offended. 
</P>
<P>
	They know, for instance, that the flags of the 19 NATO countries  
are displayed alphabetically -- according to the English language -- 
with NATO's in the middle. 
</P>
<P>
	They know that NATO newcomer Vaclav Havel, president of the  
Czech Republic since 1989, ranks No. 1 on the seating hierarchy for 
one dinner the White House is holding for members of the alliance. 
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, his country's leader for just 
six months, ranks last. 
</P>
<P>
	But even that doesn't clear up who will sit next to Clinton: It  
also depends on how the tables are arranged, whether there will be 
other special guests and if seating is arranged male/female. 
</P>
<P>
	And the ranking will be different at a second White House  
dinner, for both NATO members and the 25 eastern and central 
European countries that are NATO partners. 
</P>
<P>
	``That changes the protocol order,'' Ms. French said.  
</P>
<P>
	It sounds complicated, yet protocol makes seating at official  
dinners manageable, says Selwa ``Lucky'' Roosevelt, chief of 
protocol from 1982 to 1989, under President Reagan. 
</P>
<P>
	``If somebody says `Why does the person from that unimportant  
little country of Lower Slobovia get to sit next to the president, 
and my country doesn't?' You can say `We just followed protocol,''' 
Mrs. Roosevelt said. ``That gives you an out. Everybody observes 
the same protocol.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Does anybody really fuss over seating?  
</P>
<P>
	``Oh, my dear, do they!'' Mrs. Roosevelt said. An Italian  
foreign minister once threatened to leave the White House unless 
seating assignments were changed. ``They take it not only as a 
personal affront, but as an affront to their country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign leaders are regulars at official events so their  
``antennae wiggle'' if seats are not properly assigned, said John 
Gifford Weinmann, a chief of protocol under President Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Weinmann says there are two rules governing protocol: Common  
sense and good manners. If someone breaks with protocol, it's best 
to overlook the gaffe, he says. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they're really fouling things up, you play it by ear and  
try not to throw a hissy fit,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	To avoid glitches, protocol employees will handhold members of  
each foreign delegation from the time they're greeted at airports 
until they leave American soil. 
</P>
<P>
	``If everyone doesn't get where they have to be, then it's a  
problem,'' said Ms. French, who calls arrivals, departures and 
motorcades one of the most complex arrangements. 
</P>
<P>
	She's been working 17-hour days the past three weeks to help  
finalize details -- down to what music to play. 
</P>
<P>
	The tunes played at the signing of the North Atlantic Treaty in  
1949 seem a bit carefree for an event that, in hindsight, marked 
the beginning of a weighty alliance that has stood firm for 50 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	To the wry amusement of then-Secretary of State Dean Acheson,  
the U.S. Marine Band launched into a medley from ``Porgy and 
Bess,'' including ``I Got Plenty of Nothin''' and ``Bess, You Is My 
Woman Now,'' presumably for first lady Bess Truman, who was sitting 
in the front row, writes author Don Cook in a book on those early 
NATO days. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, planners are aware that the conflict in Yugoslavia  
has dampened the festive air surrounding NATO's 50th birthday 
commemoration, says Ms. French, who has been protocol chief since 
November 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the music that we use is going to be a little more  
somber,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
