<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Hits Communications Sites  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO blasted communications sites  
and military garrisons today as U.S. helicopters and troops headed 
toward Albania to bolster the alliance's ability to destroy 
Yugoslav ground forces. NATO also sought a new promise of 
cooperation from Bulgaria, hoping to use its airspace in the 
campaign to force Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to sign a 
peace plan for Kosovo. The Bulgarian premier was traveling to NATO 
headquarters tomorrow to work out a deal. In Washington, Secretary 
of State Madeleine Albright moved to act against Yugoslav forces, 
trying to persuade her fellow foreign ministers to cut off 
shipments of refined oil to Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	Ebb of Refugees Flow Mystifies  
</P>
<P>
	KUKES, Albania (AP) -- Aid officials puzzled today over the  
sudden drying up of the stream of refugees out of Kosovo, uncertain 
whether border fighting had stopped the flow or Serbs had blocked 
it. Refugees reported thousands still on the move within Kosovo. 
But fewer than 150 made it across yesterday. After a weekend in 
which tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians poured out of the 
southern Serbian province, the only to cross into Albania yesterday 
were a few cars and trucks full of people and an old man on foot. 
In Macedonia, only 30 made it. The U.N. refugee agency spokesman in 
Kukes said it was unclear if the Serbs were preventing people from 
reaching the border. 

</P>
<P>
	Security High for NATO's 50th  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The city is taking unprecedented steps to  
protect leaders of about 40 countries meeting for NATO's 50th 
anniversary. Bomb squads, SWAT teams and other federal and local 
police units and personnel are throwing a smothering security 
blanket over America's capital. The cloak of protection, 
intensified because of the NATO bombing campaign, includes the 
first-ever closing of several Smithsonian museums. Police are 
virtually shutting down more than two dozen blocks in the busy 
heart of the city. Yet organizers continue to scale back public 
aspects of the gathering, turning it solely toward serious business 
topped by talk on NATO's conflict with Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	Fires May Burn 40,000 More Acres  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- An erratic 130,000-acre wildfire that has roared  
through the Everglades could devour another 40,000 acres before it 
is contained, officials warned. Firefighters were monitoring the 
blaze early today while hoping that barriers created with 
controlled burns would stop its progress. Late yesterday, the 
flames reached the Miccosukee Indian Reservation, threatening 
several hunting camps and shacks, said John Fish of the state 
Division of Forestry. No injuries were reported. Just to the north, 
the blaze was about two miles east of the Big Cypress Seminole 
Indian Reservation. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Tours Ohio Tornado Damage  
</P>
<P>
	MONTGOMERY, Ohio (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore commiserated with  
those who lost their homes and businesses when a killer tornado 
tore through suburban Cincinnati earlier this month. ``I was truly 
inspired by the way everybody pulled together, neighbors helping 
neighbors,'' Gore said yesterday. The vice president visited the 
areas worst hit when a pre-dawn twister with 200-mph winds carved a 
narrow path through affluent subdivisions in Montgomery, Blue Ash 
and other communities on April 9. Four people died. 

</P>
<P>
	DiCaprio Safe After Boat Capsizes  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- The hero of ``Titanic'' survived a  
real-life boat sinking in Thailand -- but despite some local media 
reports, his producer insisted today there were no sharks in sight. 
DiCaprio and co-star Tilda Swinton were riding in a long tail boat 
when it went down Friday in heavy seas during a sudden storm. The 
two were filming ``The Beach'' off Phi Island in the Andaman Sea. 
Santa Pestanij, the Thai coordinator for the 20th Century Fox film, 
said DiCaprio remained calm for the five to ten minutes he was in 
the water and helped soothe crew members who feared drowning. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Close Mixed  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices closed mixed today after  
languishing in negative territory for most of the session. The 
Nikkei Stock Average rose 22.90 points to close the day at 
16,697.11. 

</P>
<P>
	Giants' Bonds To Have Surgery  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Barry Bonds will undergo surgery today to  
repair a bone spur in his left elbow and a damaged triceps tendon, 
San Francisco Giants manager Dusty Baker said last night. The 
All-Star left fielder was placed on the 15-day disabled list. There 
was no indication of how long Bonds would be out of the lineup, and 
the length of his recovery would depend on what the surgeons found, 
general manager Brian Sabean said. Bonds, batting .366 with four 
home runs and 12 RBIs, had an MRI yesterday that revealed the bone 
spur. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
</P>
