<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NYC May Limit Skyscrapers' Height </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The city that is home to some of the world's  
most famous skyscrapers is considering its first broad limits on 
the height of new buildings under a proposal announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not trying to turn Manhattan into a little village,''  
said Joseph Rose, chairman of the City Planning Commission. 
``There's no reason we can't create a lot of new housing with 
acceptable heights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sky would still be the limit for towers in midtown Manhattan  
and the downtown financial district, Rose said. Elsewhere, maximum 
heights would vary from neighborhood to neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	The current zoning rules, enacted in 1961, require developers to  
provide public space on the ground if they want to build high into 
the sky. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rose said that system had failed, creating useless concrete  
plazas around buildings that were often out-of-sync with their 
neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	And the incredible complexity of the regulations often let  
builders with clever lawyers do whatever they wanted, Rose said. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents of Manhattan's East Side were shocked to realize  
Donald Trump would be allowed to put up a 90-story tower -- now in 
the planning stages -- in their neighborhood of mostly much smaller 
buildings near the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Conn Nugent, executive director of the non-partisan  
good-government group Citzens Union, applauded a simplification of 
the zoning rules and said height restrictions could help make the 
city friendlier to residents and pedestrians. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Rudolph Giuliani emphasized that the proposal would go  
through a lengthy process of public review before adoption. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a proposal. It isn't necessarily going to happen that  
way,'' he told reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
