<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clouds, cool temperatures and rain hung over the nation's  
northern tier early today, while humid air and the potential for 
thunderstorms threatened the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Low pressure and a trailing cold front was expected to bring wet  
weather to the Eastern part of the country, with the steadiest rain 
falling in the major metropolitan area of the Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	An area of high pressure over the Gulf of Mexico was forecast to  
continue providing the Southeast, southern Plains and desert 
Southwest with partly cloudy skies, breezy conditions and dry 
weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Parched and fire ravaged Florida wasn't expected to have rain.  
</P>
<P>
	Showers and thunderstorms were expected to dampen parts of the  
Mississippi and Tennessee Valleys. Areas from western Missouri, 
east into Tennessee and Kentucky also could see a rain, hail and 
thunderstorms. 
</P>
<P>
	To the north, a trough of low pressure was forecast to bring  
rain showers to the Great Lakes and northern Plains. Areas of the 
high Plains may see partly cloudy skies and dry weather. 
</P>
<P>
	The northern Rockies also could be wet, particularly parts of  
Colorado and Utah. Thunderstorms were forecast in the plains of 
Montana and Wyoming. 
</P>
<P>
	To the west, another cold front was expected to bring the chance  
of rain over the Pacific Northwest by afternoon. Otherwise, the 
rest of the West coast was forecast to see partly cloudy skies and 
dry weather. 
</P>
<P>
	The afternoon high Monday in the lower 48 states was 102 degrees  
in Thermal, Calif. The low was 21 degrees in Gallup, N.M. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were expected to range from the 50s and 60s across  
the Northeast, Northwest, northern Plains, the Rockies, Great 
Lakes, mid-Atlantic states and the Carolina; the 70s and lower 80s 
in the Southeast, California, central Plains and the Ohio, 
Mississippi and Tennessee Valleys; and the mid-80s and 90s in the 
Southwest and southern Plains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
