<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Tens of thousands of students shut down  
Mexico's main university -- one of the largest in the world -- with 
an indefinite strike Tuesday to protest a tuition hike that has 
ended the state-run school's virtually free status. 
</P>
<P>
	The students walked out on most campuses of the National  
Autonomous University, effectively blocking classes and research 
activities. They vowed to strike until college officials revoke 
last month's hike, which raised annual fees from 2 cents to about 
$145. 
</P>
<P>
	University President Francisco Barnes de Castro said Monday that  
his administration would not back down over the hike, which 
officials say is necessary due to steadily decreasing government 
funding. He called for further negotiations with student leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	The university, known as UNAM, has some 268,000 students at 42  
campuses throughout the Mexico City metropolitan area. Students 
have long fought against any increase in fees, which have been 
frozen since 1948 due to constitutional guarantees of free 
education in state-run schools. 
</P>
<P>
	UNAM officials have promised students whose families make less  
than four times the national minimum wage, about $3.50 a day, would 
be exempt. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Supporters of Gen. Augusto Pinochet  
launched a new campaign Tuesday to raise $2 million for his defense 
over the next two years, convinced the former dictator faces a long 
legal battle in Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	Announcing the campaign, retired Gen. Luis Cortez, director of  
the Pinochet Foundation, said Pinochet would never be ``left 
alone.'' Pinochet, under arrest in Britain since October, is 
battling extradition to Spain, where a judge wants to try him for 
human rights violations stemming from his 1973-90 rule. 
</P>
<P>
	The new fundraising includes the restoration of five hot lines  
where people can donate the equivalent to $5 to $30. Two bank 
accounts also are to receive donations. 
</P>
<P>
	Cortez said the foundation, a private group of Pinochet  
supporters and former aides, has already paid $1.5 million for his 
legal defense. That money came from private donations. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Federal police seized 77 pounds of  
cocaine aboard a Brazilian Air Force cargo plane and are 
investigating possible links between military personnel and drug 
traffickers, the Air Force Ministry said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The drugs were found Monday on a Hercules C-130 bound for Palma  
de Mallorca, Spain, where it was scheduled to pick up spare parts 
for Brazilian military aircraft, the ministry press office said. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane departed from the Rio de Janeiro air base Sunday and  
made a refueling stop in the northeastern city of Recife, where the 
drugs were detected by drug-sniffing dogs. The pilot and eight crew 
members were detained pending further investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The drugs were found in two suitcases, which the pilot told  
investigators he had received from a fellow officer based in 
Manaus, capital of the jungle state of Amazonas, according to an O 
Globo newspaper report. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilot was asked to deliver the suitcases to an unidentified  
individual in Spain, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A majority of Mexicans approve of the way  
President Ernesto Zedillo is leading the government, according to 
an opinion poll made public Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll by the University of Guadalajara's Center for Opinion  
Studies showed that 80.2 percent of 2,202 people polled nationwide 
March 25-27 approved of Zedillo's performance. Another 17.3 percent 
disapproved, and 2.5 percent refused to answer. 
</P>
<P>
	The polls had a margin of error of 4 percentage points.  
</P>
<P>
	Zedillo is now in his fifth year of a six-year term, with  
presidential elections scheduled for July 2000. Three major parties 
and two smaller ones are scheduled to choose their candidates to 
succeed him this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 42.4 percent said they would vote for the candidate of the  
Zedillo's Institutional Revolutionary Party, in power since 1929, 
if elections were held today. 
</P>
<P>
	Another 25 percent said they would vote for the conservative  
National Action Party, and 19.6 percent for the leftist Democratic 
Revolution Party. The rest supported smaller parties or declined to 
respond. 
</P>
</TEXT>
