<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Gives Broadcasters Verbal Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- With increased competition from cable TV,  
satellite TV and the Internet, broadcasters should be given some 
leeway to own more TV and radio stations, the nation's top airwaves 
regulator said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think that we can afford to keep broadcasters in the  
Dark Ages of black-and-white era rules because the world has 
changed,'' Bill Kennard, chairman of the Federal Communications 
Commission, told broadcasters at the industry's annual convention. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the changing realities of today's marketplace, you do  
need the flexibility to seize these opportunities so you can be a 
player in the information age,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadcasters say they need regulatory relief to better compete  
against other cable TV, satellite TV, Internet and other media and 
entertainment providers, which aren't subject to the same ownership 
restrictions. Owning more local TV and radio stations in the same 
market would produce business efficiencies that would allow 
broadcasters to offer new programs and services, they contend. 
</P>
<P>
	Deregulation opponents say allowing companies to own more local  
stations would threaten editorial diversity. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennard asked the industry to work with the FCC to come up with  
a plan to ease rules limiting the number of local TV and radio 
stations that a single company can control. 
</P>
<P>
	That plan, he said, must balance broadcasters' needs with the  
commission's desire to make sure listeners and viewers continue to 
have diverse sources of news and entertainment. The industry and 
the FCC have been at loggerheads on the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	``My challenge this year is for you to join with me in crafting  
common-sense ownership rule relief,'' Kennard said. ``First and 
foremost, we've got to get this behind us. We've got to bring these 
ownership rule proceedings to a close. They have been pending for 
far too long. There's too much uncertainty in the marketplace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC wants to produce a final plan in a couple of months, an  
agency official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennard didn't specify what such a plan would do or whether it  
would resemble a proposal offered by commission staff last year. 
</P>
<P>
	That proposal would have made it easier for some broadcasters to  
own more media properties but also would have required others to 
divest some stations. Many broadcasters and key Republican 
lawmakers in Congress opposed the plan, saying it doesn't give 
broadcasters enough regulatory relief. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1996 telecommunications law eased some restrictions but  
required the commission to consider changing, or even eliminating, 
other limits because of competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Those rules prohibit a single company from owning more than one  
local TV station in a given market or from owning a TV station and 
a radio station in the same market unless the FCC grants a waiver. 
</P>
<P>
	The major broadcast networks, meanwhile, want the FCC to  
eliminate or loosen a rule limiting them from owning stations that 
reach more than 35 percent of all TV viewers -- something their 
affiliates oppose. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some say we should just eliminate all of these rules, just  
sweep them away, get rid of everything,'' Kennard said. ``I don't 
think that's the right answer, frankly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another crucial matter for broadcasters is whether the FCC will  
continue to let companies enter into local marketing agreements, or 
LMAs. They allow one TV station to operate another TV station in 
the same market, but not own it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
