<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Atheist Doesn't Have To Go to AA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An appeals court said an atheist cannot be  
forced to attend Alcoholics Anonymous meetings. But the court also 
noted that his $1 award for damages was ``just about right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling came Monday in the case of Robert Warner, who had  
argued that the Orange County Department of Probation ignored his 
constitutional rights when it required him to attend AA meetings as 
part of his probation following an impaired-driving conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	Warner argued that the order meant he would be forced to  
participate in religious exercises in violation of his First 
Amendment rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, siding with a lower court  
judge, agreed in a split ruling. It also said U.S. District Court 
Judge Gerard Goettel was right to find no substantial damages and 
to award Warner only a nominal $1. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney Richard Golden, representing Orange County, said he  
planned to appeal the case to the Supreme Court. He said any 
religious aspect to AA meetings did not rise to the level of an 
establishment of a religion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
