<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Radcliffe College, Harvard To Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- When Radcliffe College opened its doors  
to women in 1879, it did so out of necessity: nearby Harvard 
University was only for men. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't until 1943 -- with Harvard's undergraduates off  
fighting in World War II -- that Radcliffe's women were first 
allowed to take classes at Harvard. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty-four years later, Radcliffe ceased to be an independent  
undergraduate institution. Though it still admitted female 
students, they studied at Harvard. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, its mission fulfilled, Radcliffe plans to close its doors  
forever -- fully merging with Harvard and ending its role as a 
separate college after 120 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The former women's college will become the Radcliffe Institute  
for Advanced Study, which will offer graduate students instruction 
on women, gender and society. 
</P>
<P>
	That puts Radcliffe in the same league as Harvard's business,  
law, divinity and education graduate schools, with one major 
exception: Radcliffe will not grant degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are creating something that will have extraordinary  
intellectual power and visibility,'' Harvard University President 
Neil L. Rudenstine said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's long-rumored announcement is as much an end of an era  
as a beginning of a new one, said Mary Maples Dunn, director of 
Radcliffe's Schlesinger Library. She will become the institute's 
interim leader. 
</P>
<P>
	``This Institute for Advanced Study is going to become probably  
the best such institute in the country and the only one with a 
strong emphasis on women,'' said Maples Dunn, former president of 
Smith College. 
</P>
<P>
	Tensions between Radcliffe and Harvard had been mounting over  
concurrent fund-raising campaigns and disputes over Cambridge 
property that the one-time women's college occupies. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new merger, Radcliffe, as well as its prime Cambridge  
real estate, will be subsumed under Harvard's enormous umbrella. 
Beginning next year, women applicants will apply only to Harvard, 
just as men do. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger brought mixed reaction from undergraduates.  
</P>
<P>
	``I may have been educated academically at Harvard, but  
Radcliffe gave me so many things that Harvard couldn't,'' said a 
disappointed Mia Bagneris, a 21-year-old senior from New Orleans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really think it's the way to go,'' said Miriam Pachacki of  
Mountain View, Calif., Radcliffe Class of 1938. ``I think it's 
going to be a good thing for the women of Harvard not to have this 
sketchiness between the two colleges.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Radcliffe College was established in 1879 under the name the  
``Harvard Annex'' as an alternative to women who were denied access 
to the all-male Harvard. Fifteen years later came the name honoring 
Ann Radcliffe, who established Harvard's first scholarship in 1643. 
</P>
<P>
	Radcliffe seniors began receiving Harvard diplomas signed by the  
presidents of both colleges in 1963. Twelve years later, a joint 
admissions office opened. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the merger -- which still needs final approval from  
Radcliffe's Board of Trustees and Harvard's equivalent oversight 
board -- Harvard will actually boost the Radcliffe endowment by 
about $150 million, bringing the total to $300 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Radcliffe becomes just the latest women's school to merge with  
its one-time brother institution. The partnership between New 
York's Columbia University and all-female Barnard College is one of 
the few that still exist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 17:23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Reacts to School Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A somber President Clinton, recalling his own  
travels to the suburban Denver community rocked by a shooting 
rampage through Columbine High, asked the nation to ``wake up'' to 
school violence today. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said a team of grief counselors has been mobilized and  
will head to Littleton, Colo., where the death toll -- which police 
estimated at 25 -- was still being confirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it can happen here, then surely people will recognize that  
they have to be alive to the possibility that it can occur in any 
community in America and maybe that will help us to keep it from 
happening again,'' Clinton said from the White House press briefing 
room. 
</P>
<P>
	The president, his face red and eyes mostly downcast, addressed  
the nation after an afternoon of updates from his aides and phone 
calls to state and local officials on the scene in Littleton. 
</P>
<P>
	Pressed by reporters to say what the government might do to stop  
such school violence, Clinton said he wanted to give the Colorado 
community -- ``an open wound'' -- time to grieve. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tonight, I think the American people ought to be thinking  
about those folks in Littleton,'' he said. ``Tomorrow and in the 
days ahead, we'll have a little more time to kind of gather 
ourselves and our determination and go back at this again.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 18:12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Reacts to School Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A somber President Clinton, recalling his own  
travels to the suburban Denver community rocked by a shooting 
rampage through Columbine High School, asked the nation Tuesday to 
``wake up'' to school violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Out of respect for Colorado's grief, Clinton canceled a  
political trip Wednesday to Texas. He said a team of counselors has 
been mobilized and will head to Littleton, Colo., where the death 
toll -- which police estimated at 25 -- was still being confirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it can happen here, then surely people will recognize that  
they have to be alive to the possibility that it can occur in any 
community in America, and maybe that will help us to keep it from 
happening again,'' Clinton said from the White House press briefing 
room. 
</P>
<P>
	The president, his face red and eyes mostly downcast, addressed  
the nation after an afternoon of updates from his aides, phone 
calls to state and local officials in Littleton, and what he said 
were constantly changing numbers of injuries and fatalities. 
</P>
<P>
	Quoting from a conversation he said he had with County  
Commission Chairwoman Patricia Holloway, Clinton said: ``Perhaps 
now America would wake up to the dimensions of this challenge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pressed by reporters to say what the government might do to stop  
such school violence, Clinton said he wanted to give the Colorado 
community -- ``an open wound'' -- time to grieve. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tonight, I think the American people ought to be thinking  
about those folks in Littleton,'' he said. ``Tomorrow and in the 
days ahead, we'll have a little more time to kind of gather 
ourselves and our determination and go back at this again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton had been scheduled to celebrate Texas' new  
Austin-Bergstrom International Airport on Wednesday and to star at 
political fund-raisers in Austin and Houston. The president ``felt 
it was best to remain here in Washington,'' press secretary Joe 
Lockhart said Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	It was six months ago that Clinton -- together with Vice  
President Al Gore, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and close to 
800 educators and law-enforcement officials -- held a splashy White 
House conference on school violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday night, after hours of nonstop television coverage of the  
dramatic events in suburban Denver, Clinton acknowledged the nation 
has made little progress. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know there are a lot of kids out there who have access to  
weapons -- and apparently more than guns, here -- and who build up 
these grievances in their own mind and who are not being reached,'' 
Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``And it's not just Littleton.''  
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Tuesday at an economic announcement, Clinton offered  
prayers to the students, parents and faculty of Columbine High but 
said he would not comment extensively until after officials were 
certain they'd heard the last of the gunshots inside the school. 
</P>
<P>
	Police at the scene said two gunmen on a ``suicide mission''  
shot and killed as many as 25 people inside the school and then 
themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	The president called attention to a spate of school shootings a  
year ago when he traveled last summer to Springfield, Ore., and 
visited the Thurston High School cafeteria. There, police said, a 
15-year-old pupil opened fire, killing two classmates and wounding 
22 others. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton followed up that emotional visit with the White House  
conference in October. 
</P>
<P>
	He ordered Education Secretary Richard Riley and Attorney  
General Janet Reno then to work with school officials and law 
enforcement authorities on developing an ``early warning guide'' 
that might help prevent the kind of youth rage that erupted in 
deadly -- and high-profile -- school gunfire in Springfield, West 
Paducah, Ky.; Edinboro, Pa.; Jonesboro Ark.; and Pearl, Miss. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Clinton recalled those tragedies as he tried to  
console Littleton. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rest of us have a responsibility to do everything we can  
to make sure this doesn't make 1999 a year like last year, that we 
don't have another rash of this, that we really can be more 
effective in preventing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was asked if he stood by his administration's contention  
last October that students are still safer sitting in a classroom 
than they are walking down the street. 
</P>
<P>
	``Statistically, for all the whole 53 million kids in our  
schools it's true,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	But at Columbine High, where the attackers were apparently armed  
with hand grenades, explosives, and high-powered weapons, ``it 
obviously wasn't true there. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was obviously the most dangerous place in Colorado  
today.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
