<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mystery Surrounds Ng's Nature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) -- The same jurors who concluded that  
Charles Ng was a vicious serial killer are now being asked to view 
him as a gentle philosopher and caring friend who deserves to 
escape execution. 
</P>
<P>
	In the final days of the penalty phase, Ng's lawyers have  
presented a litany of testimonials to his good character from a 
parade of witnesses, some of whose roles have bordered on the 
downright bizarre. 
</P>
<P>
	It's no surprise that family members would talk of Ng's abused  
childhood in Hong Kong. But more than a dozen other witnesses 
called by Deputy Public Defender William Kelley threw yet another 
twist in a trial that has become one of California's longest and 
most expensive. 
</P>
<P>
	Some were upstanding citizens: tough former Marines, brawny  
prison guards and a 66-year-old woman who was briefly Ng's lover. 
Together, they spoke of the 38-year-old defendant in almost 
reverential tones. 
</P>
<P>
	None seemed more a surprise than Betty Kirkendall, a  
well-dressed, well-spoken woman who traveled from Cleveland, Okla., 
with her daughter. She told of forming a friendship with Ng through 
her efforts at prison ministry in 1983, a year before the killings 
began. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Kirkendall said her son was murdered, she was having  
marital problems, had been raped and had no one to communicate with 
when she began writing letters to Ng, who was imprisoned at 
Leavenworth, Kan., for weapons theft while serving in the Marine 
Corps. 
</P>
<P>
	To her surprise, she said, Ng wrote supportive letters and sent  
gifts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Did he make you feel loved?'' asked defense attorney Lewis  
Clapp. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes,'' she replied.  
</P>
<P>
	When Ng was released, they decided to meet, she recalled. He  
came to the home of a friend in Shawnee, Okla.; they met and the 
next day she picked him up in her car and drove to a motel. After 
they had sex, Mrs. Kirkendall said she never saw him again. 
</P>
<P>
	Another supporter who testified was Chuck Farnham of San Jose,  
Calif., who wrote to Ng a year ago about their common hobby of 
origami, the Japanese art of paper folding. He said they began 
talking by phone and Ng comforted him over the death of his father. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of all the people I know I was surprised that with all his  
problems he had this genuine concern about what I was going 
through,'' Farnham said. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel, which convicted him Feb. 24 of killing six men, three  
women and two baby boys, also has seen Ng's darker side. 
Prosecutors showed them videotapes of Ng and his co-conspirator, 
survivalist Leonard Lake, tormenting bound, terrified women who 
were later murdered. 
</P>
<P>
	They saw, as well, cartoons drawn by Ng in prison -- crude  
pictures of babies being smashed, drowned, fried in a wok or put in 
a microwave oven. 
</P>
<P>
	These were in contrast to sweet, carefully drawn greeting cards  
shown by his friends -- valentines and images of angels and animals. 
</P>
<P>
	No witness was more effusive in his praise of Ng than convicted  
rapist and murderer Lance Blanchard who said Ng's counseling in the 
philosophy of Taoism turned him away from violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will not harm another human being,'' Blanchard said in  
videotaped testimony, telling how Ng guided him through the 
principles of Taoism in prison. ``I have learned to, no matter 
what, give respect to everybody.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
