<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 17:33:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Boxer Ayala Released From Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- ``The Little Bull'' is a distant memory,  
even for Tony Ayala. 
</P>
<P>
	He once seemed destined for superstardom, but his promising  
boxing career crashed in a night of madness. Images of his 
flamboyance and devastating speed stayed locked behind bars with 
him, along with thoughts of a terrible crime he can never forget. 
</P>
<P>
	Ayala walked out of a New Jersey prison Tuesday after serving 16  
years for rape. As he ventured into daylight and freedom, Ayala was 
bombarded by thoughts of a comeback and overwhelmed by disbelief. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kept expecting an officer to come to me and say they made a  
mistake,'' said Ayala, spending his first hours of freedom with his 
wife at the Pennsylvania home of his adviser, Brian Raditz. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's almost like a dream. I've said that to her a number of  
times: `We made it. We got through this.' It's like a long 
struggle, a struggle to keep going. Sometimes it seemed like the 
end would never come, and when it happens it's hard to believe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ayala, now 36, hasn't fought since he was a 19-year-old junior  
middleweight with a 22-0 record with 19 knockouts. But his chance 
to be the Oscar De La Hoya of his day was ruined by drugs and 
alcohol. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early morning hours of New Year's Day 1983, Ayala  
returned to his Paterson, N.J., home after a night out with his 
wife, Lisa Paez. She went to bed. He said he was going to watch 
television. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, stoked by heroin and booze, he went to the home of a  
female neighbor and raped her. At the time, he was on probation for 
beating a woman in the restroom of a San Antonio drive-in theater 
in 1980, and for breaking into a San Antonio home in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	``My whole focus was finding out what it was that caused me to  
behave in the manner that I did and fix myself,'' said Ayala, who 
was released for good behavior less than half way through his 
35-year sentence. ``The fact that I committed this crime is 
something I will have to live with the rest of my life. It's not 
ever going to be forgotten.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ayala spent much of his sentence attacking the demons that  
nearly ruined his life and that of his victim, training his mind 
and soul with the intensity that once honed his body for the ring. 
</P>
<P>
	With the counseling and friendship of Raditz, Ayala finally was  
ready to begin training his body again. He says he weighs 175 
pounds -- 21 pounds over the junior middleweight limit -- and can do 
300 pullups, 300 pushups, 300 dips, 2,000 crunches and run eight 
miles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Physically, he looks phenomenal,'' Raditz said. ``He's  
probably in better shape now than he was when he was fighting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paez struggled with her husband's crime and absence, leaving him  
several years ago. But she was there to lead him out of Bayside 
State Prison in Leesburg, N.J. The couple are planning to remarry 
and perhaps have children. 
</P>
<P>
	``He took a deep breath, let it out and said, `Let's go,''' Paez  
said. ``We walked through the doors hand-in-hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a new beginning. It was a very hard walk. But I've always  
been in love with Tony, and I was always trying to replace him with 
someone else. It just wasn't happening. I wasn't running from him, 
because I loved him. I was running from a situation that was just 
unbearable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ayala's parents and two older brothers also were there to escort  
him out of prison. His father, also Tony, will train him again if 
he makes it back into the ring. 
</P>
<P>
	Financially, Ayala needs to work. As with many troubled  
fighters, boxing probably will give him a few easy pay days. If he 
is going to make it, Ayala will have to avoid the problems former 
heavyweight champion Mike Tyson has had since he got out of prison 
for rape. 
</P>
<P>
	``Boxing is a way I could give to my family what I always wanted  
to give to them, but unfortunately was too stupid when I was young 
to give them,'' Ayala said. ``I want to finish some unfinished 
business with boxing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Ayala tended to the unfinished business of his life.  
Laughter, chatter and a dog's barking could be heard in the 
background as he talked on the phone at Raditz's home in the 
Philadelphia suburb of Huntingdon Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	The sounds of a speedbag could be next.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's already succeeded,'' Raditz said. ``He's dealt with his  
horrible, horrible conflicts. He's very remorseful about how he 
behaved. He is a winner already, whether he goes back to fighting 
or, honestly, whatever he sets his mind to.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
