<HEADLINE> Lockheed Martin Loses $87M in 1Q </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- Lockheed Martin Corp. lost $87 million or  
23 cents a share in the first quarter as a $355 million accounting 
charge dragged down earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Without the charge, which the company attributed to start-up  
costs for business activities, and a $74 million gain on the sale 
of stock, the company would have earned $194 million, or 51 cents 
per share, in line with Wall Street expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	In the same period last year, Lockheed earned $269 million, or  
71 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	First-quarter revenues edged lower to $6.19 billion from $6.22  
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although this quarter's results were on plan, they were not as  
good as we'd like them to be, and we remain focused on the 
operational and performance issues that create uncertainty for our 
customers and shareholders,'' said Vance Coffman, chairman and 
chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockheed Martin is one of the nation's largest defense  
contractors. It is engaged in the research, design, development, 
manufacture and integration of advanced-technology systems, 
products and services. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Lockheed Martin closed down 75 cents to $39 in trading  
on the New York Stock Exchange. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
