<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Importer Goes Bankrupt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- Tamexco, an import-export company that was  
at the center of Vietnam's biggest corruption trial, has been 
declared bankrupt effective May 1, a court official said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's creditors have 30 days to appeal the decision,  
which was made on March 31, the official said. There was no 
explanation why announcement of the decision was delayed. 
</P>
<P>
	The bankruptcy is the latest chapter in a scandal in which 20  
people, including business executives, bankers and government 
officials, were charged. 
</P>
<P>
	Four were sentenced to death at a trial in January 1997, and  
three of them were executed by firing squad a year later. The 
fourth was pardoned for contributions his family has made to the 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	Tamexco, the commercial arm of the Communist Party of Tan Binh  
District in Ho Chi Minh City, initially filed for bankruptcy in 
March 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The bankruptcy petition was approved because Tamexco suffered  
from ``serious losses'' and ``is unable to pay its debts,'' the 
court official said. He spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Tamexco's former director allegedly spent some $27 million on  
bribery, embezzlement and gambling, then covered the losses with 
loans from state-owned banks on overvalued collateral. He was 
brought to trial as part of a government crackdown on corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 10:08:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nine-Year-Old Loves Trash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SIERRA MADRE, Calif. (AP) -- Trash talk hasn't been a waste of  
time for Kevin Inciyaki. At age 9, it's landed him notice and a 
job. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin likes garbage and garbage containers and garbage trucks  
and garbage books and garbage videos. Early photos of him in the 
family scrapbook show him inspecting trash cans at Sea World. 
</P>
<P>
	He has a photo collection of ``garbage trucks of the world''  
taken for him by family friends on trips abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been garbage since he was 2-years-old -- you have no idea  
what it's like having a child who has a passion for trash,'' said 
Kevin's mother, Marsha Inciyaki. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin doesn't know what got his interested in the dirty side of  
life. Classmates at Bethany Christian School ``think it's kinda 
weird,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hawaii, his brother wanted to go snorkeling, and when we  
asked Kevin what he wanted to do, he said, 'Follow the garbage 
trucks,''' Mrs. Inciyaki said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sierra Madre public works officials who knew how much Kevin  
likes trash recommended him for a job with the University of 
California, Los Angeles. Now he's running a worm farm and 
collecting worm information as part of a waste management survey in 
Sierra Madre and Monrovia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 14:35:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Eyes Coliseum for LA Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The NFL wants to put its 32nd franchise in  
the Los Angeles Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	That does not guarantee, however, that pro football will return  
to Los Angeles. Still to be determined is an ownership group for 
the new team, which must satisfy other NFL owners with its stadium 
and financing plans. 
</P>
<P>
	NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue announced the league's  
intentions today at a news conference in front of the Coliseum. 
Eleven team owners, members of the league's expansion committee, 
were on hand. 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles area has not had a pro football team since the  
Rams, who played at the Coliseum before moving to Anaheim, left for 
St. Louis and the Raiders returned to Oakland, both after the 1994 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Some NFL owners who have opposed putting a team back in the Los  
Angeles Coliseum apparently have unpleasant memories of their teams 
playing the Raiders there. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there were owners who had their teams play against the  
Raiders here a few years ago who felt that there was a safety 
issue, a rowdiness issue,'' Mayor Richard Riordan said after he and 
other civic and business leaders met Monday with the expansion 
committee. ``Those are the ones who have changed their minds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the Raiders played at the Coliseum before moving back to  
Oakland, their crowds tended to be rougher than those at most other 
NFL games. 
</P>
<P>
	``The owners were very, very positive about Los Angeles,''  
Riordan said. ``A couple of them mentioned that they were negative 
until they visited our city recently. I feel very confident we'll 
get a team, and I feel very confident we'll get a team at the 
Coliseum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Coliseum, which would be gutted inside and rebuilt, became  
the only viable choice in Los Angeles after Michael Ovitz bowed out 
of the Carson proposal last week to endorse the Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	Riordan said that, among other subjects discussed at Monday's  
meeting, were parking -- ``They require 20,000 parking spaces'' -- 
and TV blackouts -- ``It's very, very important to the league that 
there are no blackouts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Who will own the new team remains a large question.  
</P>
<P>
	Carolina Panthers owner Jerry Richardson, chairman of the  
expansion committee, spoke glowingly of Ovitz, although Richardson 
did not rule out Ed Roski, who headed the drive to get an NFL team 
for the Coliseum, and partner Eli Broad as team owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Roski, a developer, holds exclusive rights to any NFL deal with  
the Coliseum, but said he won't stand in the way if the league 
wants to hold an auction for the new team. 
</P>
<P>
	His exclusive rights would be relinquished if he were reimbursed  
for his expenses -- capped at $5 million -- incurred while seeking 
the league's franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've told them (the NFL) all along that we're not going to  
stand in the way of football in LA,'' Roski said. ``We would 
suggest a couple of things, local ownership, and reimburse us. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole purpose was to bring NFL football back to LA, and  
the Coliseum and we would like to be a bidder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roski spearheaded the building of the new Staples Center  
downtown, and also gave the New Coliseum proposal life. Broad, who 
could provide solid financial backing for an NFL team, joined the 
Coliseum efforts later. 
</P>
<P>
	NFL owners have seemed interested in having Ovitz involved in  
any deal with the Coliseum. Tagliabue called the Hollywood 
deal-maker a ``visionary,'' and implied the league could benefit 
from Ovitz's experience in the entertainment industry. 
</P>
<P>
	There is no guarantee that Los Angeles will even get a team. The  
owners, well aware that the area represents the nation's 
second-largest TV market, voted 29-2 last month to spurn Robert 
McNair's Houston bid and award the franchise to the Los Angeles 
area on a conditional basis. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, suburban Carson also was in the running.  
</P>
<P>
	The NFL gave Los Angeles until Sept. 15 to put together an  
ownership and stadium package. If a deal can't be reached, the new 
team, which would begin play in 2002, probably will go to Houston. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 15:25:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Must Solve the Hasek Puzzle / Hockey Game Story  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANATA, Ontario (AP) -- The Ottawa Senators reward for winning  
the Northeast Divison and the No. 2 seed in the Eastern Conference: 
A first-round matchup with all-world goalie Dominik Hasek. 
</P>
<P>
	Goals will be at a premium when Ottawa faces Hasek's Buffalo  
Sabres in Game 1 of their quarterfinal series Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Senators have the only goaltender with a better  
goals-against average than Hasek -- Ron Tugnutt. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've played a lot against Dominik Hasek,'' said Senators  
winger Shawn McEachern. ``We aren't expecting any high-scoring 
games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All five games between the teams went into overtime this season,  
with the Senators winning 3-2 on Dec. 30 in Buffalo and the other 
four ending in ties. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3-2 win was also the only time one team managed to score  
three goals. Only 15 total goals were scored by both teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a battle,'' said Senators defenseman Wade  
Redden. ``But that's the price we have to pay to advance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two clubs are meeting in the playoffs for the second time in  
three years, with Buffalo eliminating Ottawa from its first-ever 
modern-day playoff appearance two seasons ago on Derek Plante's 
Game 7 overtime goal against Tugnutt. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always been a great intensity against them,'' said  
Senators wing Daniel Alfredsson. ``We can't just focus on their 
goaltending. They have a good team in front of him as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alfredsson says there is a way to beat the Dominator.  
</P>
<P>
	``You have to make it tough for him to see the puck,'' said  
Alfredsson. ``We know we have to shoot a lot and be there for the 
rebounds. The main thing is you can't think he'll be there to stop 
everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek played all five games against Ottawa during the regular  
season, surrendering eight goals and three in the final three 
meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's their best player,'' Alfredsson said. ``But he's not  
their only player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tugnutt, who had a GAA of 1.79 this season, doesn't think his  
club should be too focused on Hasek. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to be concerned with the way, the style of hockey that  
they play,'' he said, adding that both teams play a tight, 
defensive style of hockey. ``It's not just Dominik Hasek we have to 
beat, although he is a major part of that team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the Senators were just 3-2-5 in their final 10  
regular season games, coach Jacques Martin isn't worried about his 
club's lack of intensity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're well prepared,'' Martin said. ``We're a team  
looking forward to starting the playoffs, we're anxious.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
