<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Rebounding From Poor Day / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, with technology stocks  
showing signs of recovery from Monday's rout but blue chips losing 
more ground. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 34.93 at 10,405.60 after having fallen 53 points on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq composite index was up 32.02 at 2,377.63 after  
plunging 5.6 percent Monday amid a sharp selloff in 
Internet-related shares. 
</P>
<P>
	High-profile technology stocks that took big hits Monday were  
mostly higher. Microsoft led the Nasdaq trading in volume and was 
up 1 33/64 at 82 33/64. Dell, Intel and Cisco were all higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet shares, which were pounded sharply lower on Monday,  
were recovering too, with Amazon.com up 9 1/16 at 168. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think the tech group will stay down. This is just a  
normal pause to refresh,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, chief market 
strategist, A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc., St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Belski, chief investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP;  
Co., in Kansas City, Mo., said he was encouraged at signs of gentle 
recovery in tech stocks after Monday's debacle. Investors embarked 
on the day expecting a recovery in tech shares, so they placed some 
bets in that stock sector. 
</P>
<P>
	``When tech stocks cratered yesterday, investors in general had  
someplace else to go,'' Belski said. ``While the vim and vigor is 
not present on this upside bounce that was there in other 
recoveries in the tech sector, it's good that people have 
alternatives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While technology stocks recovered, industrial shares, which have  
been popular purchases for more than a week, were lower today. One 
of the biggest decliners was United Technologies, which fell 4 1/4 to 
140 3/4 despite reporting better-than-expected earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Ricky Harrington, a technical analyst at Wachovia Securities in  
Charlotte, N.C., said attributed some of the blue-chip decline to 
profit taking. 
</P>
<P>
	``But there is also a little bit of apprehension out there,'' he  
said. ``The fall in technology stocks over the last few sessions 
has created caution elsewhere in the market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are in a transition period and no one is sure what is  
coming next,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by 4-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 477 million shares, 
down from 462 million shares on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 10.94 at 1,300.42, the  
NYSE composite index was up 3.55 at 619.43, and the Amex composite 
index was unchanged at 735.11. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 17:13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cowboys' Newton May Be Gone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Guard Nate Newton has beaten the odds for 13 years  
but recent developments at Valley Ranch suggest he has seen his 
last days with the Dallas Cowboys. 
</P>
<P>
	Newton has been plagued by injury the past several seasons, a  
reason why Dallas drafted two more offensive lineman and signed 
free agent center Mark Stepnoski recently. 
</P>
<P>
	This would leave only about $400,000 for Newton who made  
$700,000 last year. His agent, Jim Neader, has suggested Newton 
will shop his wares to other teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not closing the door to his coming back,'' Neader said,  
``but he may be forced to go elsewhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cowboys won't say if big Nate is in their plans.  
</P>
<P>
	``We'll be making that announcement in a couple of weeks,''  
Dallas coach Chan Gailey said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest NFL draft, the Cowboys took tight end Mike Lucky  
of Arizona and offensive guard Kelvin Garmon of Baylor with their 
two seventh-round picks. The additional help for the offensive 
line, which was targeted with Saturday's second-round selection of 
West Virginia's Solomon Page, could have made Newton expendable. 
</P>
<P>
	Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said earlier this year he wasn't sure  
Newton can be a starter in his 13th season, even though the 
37-year-old offensive lineman was just voted to the Pro Bowl for 
the sixth time. 
</P>
<P>
	A fixture in the Cowboys' offensive line since 1986, Newton has  
spent the past 12 years as a starter after one year as a reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	``At some point we will sit down with Nate and talk,'' Jones  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas coaches have discussed putting Flozell Adams at left  
tackle and moving Larry Allen back to guard, where he would join 
Everett McIver. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 22:24:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Waitress Must Share $10M Lottery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOBILE, Ala. (AP) -- A former waitress who won a $10 million  
jackpot with a lottery ticket left as a tip has been ordered to 
share the money with four co-workers. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury on Tuesday decided against Tonda Dickerson, 28, who  
denied that she had agreed to split any winnings with her Waffle 
House co-workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The co-workers had also received lottery tickets as tips and  
testified that they and Mrs. Dickerson had a share-the-wealth plan. 
A couple who regularly dine at the Waffle House in Grand Bay 
testified that Mrs. Dickerson told them of the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dickerson, who had turned down a settlement offer that  
would have given her $3 million of the Florida jackpot, left court 
without comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Her former co-workers were jubilant.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have a 5-year-old girl and she's going to get a new  
collection of toys,'' said Jackie Fairley, 21. ``I want a new 
wardrobe and a new car.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A beaming Sandra Deno, 45, said: ``I might work two days a week.  
I don't really have any hard feelings toward Tonda.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Robert Kendall said he will decide how the money will be  
divided after consulting with attorneys and Florida lottery 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dickerson's attorney, Dwight Reid, said he expects the five  
will share equally. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dickerson was given the lottery ticket on March 7 by a  
breakfast regular at the Waffle House, Edward Seward Jr., who said 
he wanted only a new pickup truck if the ticket won. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
