<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Open Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures advanced early today on  
the Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts for rains that will delay 
spring plantings. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans found the most support on continuing rains in  
the Midwest, which have increasingly stalled fieldwork and could 
lead to smaller acreage planted. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans also were supported by a lack of selling by farmers in  
Brazil and the United States, which boosted cash market prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures rose after the U.S. Agriculture Department  
reported Monday that winter wheat crop conditions had declined, 
although most of the gains came largely on the strength of the corn 
and soybean markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 3 cents to $2.66 1/4 a bushel; May  
corn rose 2 1/2 cents to $2.23 a bushel; May oats rose 1 1/4 cents to 
$1.22 a bushel; May soybeans rose 3 1/2 cents to $4.91 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and lean hogs were mostly higher on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while pork bellies retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .45 cent to 62.47 cents a pound; May  
feeder cattle rose .37 cent to 71.67 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
rose .30 cent to 55.52 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell .75 
cent to 55.17 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
