<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 15:27:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Eyes Coliseum for LA Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The NFL wants to put its 32nd franchise in  
the Los Angeles Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	That does not guarantee, however, that pro football will return  
to Los Angeles. Still to be determined is an ownership group for 
the new team, which must satisfy other NFL owners with its stadium 
and financing plans. 
</P>
<P>
	NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue announced the league's  
intentions today at a news conference in front of the Coliseum. 
Eleven team owners, members of the league's expansion committee, 
were on hand. 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles area has not had a pro football team since the  
Rams, who played at the Coliseum before moving to Anaheim, left for 
St. Louis and the Raiders returned to Oakland, both after the 1994 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Some NFL owners who have opposed putting a team back in the Los  
Angeles Coliseum apparently have unpleasant memories of their teams 
playing the Raiders there. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there were owners who had their teams play against the  
Raiders here a few years ago who felt that there was a safety 
issue, a rowdiness issue,'' Mayor Richard Riordan said after he and 
other civic and business leaders met Monday with the expansion 
committee. ``Those are the ones who have changed their minds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the Raiders played at the Coliseum before moving back to  
Oakland, their crowds tended to be rougher than those at most other 
NFL games. 
</P>
<P>
	``The owners were very, very positive about Los Angeles,''  
Riordan said. ``A couple of them mentioned that they were negative 
until they visited our city recently. I feel very confident we'll 
get a team, and I feel very confident we'll get a team at the 
Coliseum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Coliseum, which would be gutted inside and rebuilt, became  
the only viable choice in Los Angeles after Michael Ovitz bowed out 
of the Carson proposal last week to endorse the Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	Riordan said that, among other subjects discussed at Monday's  
meeting, were parking -- ``They require 20,000 parking spaces'' -- 
and TV blackouts -- ``It's very, very important to the league that 
there are no blackouts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Who will own the new team remains a large question.  
</P>
<P>
	Carolina Panthers owner Jerry Richardson, chairman of the  
expansion committee, spoke glowingly of Ovitz, although Richardson 
did not rule out Ed Roski, who headed the drive to get an NFL team 
for the Coliseum, and partner Eli Broad as team owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Roski, a developer, holds exclusive rights to any NFL deal with  
the Coliseum, but said he won't stand in the way if the league 
wants to hold an auction for the new team. 
</P>
<P>
	His exclusive rights would be relinquished if he were reimbursed  
for his expenses -- capped at $5 million -- incurred while seeking 
the league's franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've told them (the NFL) all along that we're not going to  
stand in the way of football in LA,'' Roski said. ``We would 
suggest a couple of things, local ownership, and reimburse us. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole purpose was to bring NFL football back to LA, and  
the Coliseum and we would like to be a bidder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roski spearheaded the building of the new Staples Center  
downtown, and also gave the New Coliseum proposal life. Broad, who 
could provide solid financial backing for an NFL team, joined the 
Coliseum efforts later. 
</P>
<P>
	NFL owners have seemed interested in having Ovitz involved in  
any deal with the Coliseum. Tagliabue called the Hollywood 
deal-maker a ``visionary,'' and implied the league could benefit 
from Ovitz's experience in the entertainment industry. 
</P>
<P>
	There is no guarantee that Los Angeles will even get a team. The  
owners, well aware that the area represents the nation's 
second-largest TV market, voted 29-2 last month to spurn Robert 
McNair's Houston bid and award the franchise to the Los Angeles 
area on a conditional basis. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, suburban Carson also was in the running.  
</P>
<P>
	The NFL gave Los Angeles until Sept. 15 to put together an  
ownership and stadium package. If a deal can't be reached, the new 
team, which would begin play in 2002, probably will go to Houston. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
