<DOCNO> APW19990420.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 18:23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Otis Thorpe Grabs 10,000th Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Otis Thorpe grabbed his 10,000th rebound Tuesday  
night, becoming the 16th player in NBA history to score at least 
15,000 points and get 10,000 rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Wizards forward entered the game against the  
Chicago Bulls needing just two rebounds to reach 10,000. Thorpe, 
36, got his first with 5:50 left in the first quarter, when he 
grabbed an offensive rebound and put it back for a basket. 
</P>
<P>
	The 10,000th came on a defensive board with 2:39 left in the  
first. The game wasn't stopped. 
</P>
<P>
	The others in the 15,000-10,000 club are: Kareem Abdul-Jabbar,  
Wilt Chamberlain, Karl Malone, Moses Malone, Elvin Hayes, Hakeem 
Olajuwon, Robert Parish, Elgin Baylor, Charles Barkley, Walt 
Bellamy, Bob Pettit, Dolph Schayes, Jack Sikma, Buck Williams and 
Patrick Ewing. Of the 15, 12 are on the NBA's list of 50 Greatest 
Players. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing got his 10,000th rebound earlier this season.  
</P>
<P>
	Thorpe, in his 15th NBA season, entered the game with 17,042  
points. He was the 55th player -- and 12th active player -- to break 
the 17,000 mark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 15:45:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Indoor Football League Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- The Extreme Football League, scheduled  
to begin play in April 2000, Tuesday announced nine cities that 
will field teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Art Clarkson, acting commissioner of the newly formed Extreme  
Football League, said teams will play a 16-game schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	Teams will have 22-man rosters, with eight players per team on  
the 50-yard field at one time. The rest of the rules are still 
being worked out. 
</P>
<P>
	Clarkson said the league will definitely have three teams in  
Florida; Tallahassee, Jacksonville and Pensacola. It also plans to 
have teams in Huntsville and Birmingham, Ala., Norfolk and 
Richmond, Va., and Greenville, S.C. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said five other cities were in ``serious discussion'' to  
join the league. 
</P>
<P>
	``We aren't going to be like the Arena League, mainly because we  
won't use the nets that they do,'' Clarkson said. ``We're going to 
try to bring the outdoor game indoors, with a lot of offense and 
defense, but make it a little more extreme.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The nine current teams will be owned in whole or part by  
existing East Coast Hockey League owners. That would allow them to 
use the hockey teams' existing support staffs and arenas during 
hockey's offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	Clarkson, who said he will own the Huntsville franchise once a  
permanent commissioner is named, said it will be some time before 
his league can compete with the Arena League. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Arena League has teams in Chicago and New York, tier one  
markets, so I don't see them as competition,'' Clarkson said. ``But 
I still think we are on the right track. We have laid the cement, 
it's not exactly solid, but it's becoming stronger every day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bruce Burge, part of the group that will own franchises in  
Birmingham, Jacksonville and Pensacola, said the teams will be 
competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't a minor league,'' Burge said. ``We're not taking a  
back seat to the Arena League. We're going for the best available 
players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The league plans to hold a territorial draft next February. Each  
team would have four area colleges assigned to its territory and a 
budget of at least $600,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Getting the players will be the easy part,'' Clarkson said.  
``There are players coming out of college every year, late 
developing players who were NFL cuts and players who want to play 
just for the love of the game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 17:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wider Use of Tobacco Money Sought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A growing number of local and national  
coalitions and the U.S. surgeon general are shouldering into the 
tobacco settlement debate, seeking more money from squabbling 
legislatures for antismoking and preventive health campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	The coalitions are offering moral suasion as 46 state  
legislatures separately feud over how much to spend on roads, 
playgrounds or health with the $206 billion they won from the 
tobacco industry last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're saying that the meaning of the settlement should be  
health, not money,'' said Damon Thompson, a spokesman for the 
Department of Health and Human Services. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson and Surgeon General David Satcher spoke Tuesday at a  
U.N. conference on tobacco control and building coalitions 
nationally and globally that include minority communities. The 
forum included students, local and state officials, representatives 
of community organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Canales of the East Harlem Council for Human Services had  
very specific ideas about how to use the settlement monies. New 
York state is due $25 billion from the settlement and Canales 
pointed out that those with HIV/AIDS or who are alcoholics or 
substance abusers also are addicted to cigarettes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should get a higher amount of the money'' because of the  
interconnected problems, Canales said. 
</P>
<P>
	A study last year by the surgeon general, who also serves as an  
HHS assistant secretary, showed rapid increases in smoking by 
minority teenagers. Cigarette smoking is a major cause of death and 
disease among blacks, Latinos, American Indian/Alaska Native and 
Asian American/Pacific Islanders. Black men have death rates from 
cancer 50 percent higher than white men. 
</P>
<P>
	Satcher called the increases among minority teens ``the first  
steps of a potentially tragic reversal for the health of American 
minorities,'' in issuing the department's first-ever study of 
tobacco and health focusing on ethnic and minority communities. 
</P>
<P>
	Satcher vowed then to fight. On Tuesday, Satcher was just as  
emphatic in denouncing tobacco advertising that targets minority 
groups and children in general. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm upset. I'm very upset by the marketing to children, all  
our children ... to addicting tobacco,'' Satcher said. Children 
using tobacco grow up to ``suffer unnecessary diseases, suffer 
unnecessary pain and death,'' Satcher said, adding that fighting 
tobacco is harder than fighting infectious diseases. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tobacco is a greater foe because infectious diseases don't  
have lobbying efforts, infectious diseases don't have marketing 
efforts. They don't spread their infections through vending 
machines,'' he said, adding that children and minorities are not 
the only targets of tobacco marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pattern is to prey upon the poor and undereducated,''  
Satcher said. ``That's the sad part.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Williams, a tobacco industry spokesman, rejected Satcher's  
statements comparing the tobacco industry with infectious diseases 
as ``a bit silly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a very cynical view,'' Williams said. ``You continue to  
hear that firebrand kind of rhetoric'' but not what the industry is 
doing in 1999, including tearing down billboard advertising and 
allocating $1.4 billion over 10 years for antismoking education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 05:45:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woodstock Organizers Book Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME, N.Y. (AP) -- With a temporary permit in hand, Woodstock '99  
organizers have booked four more groups to their musical lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	Added to the lineup for the three-day festival this summer are  
Wyclef Jean and the Refugee Allstars, multi-platinum selling 
Canadian rockers Our Lady Peace, British soul and funk sensation 
Jamiroquai and former Grateful Dead drummer Mickey Hart and his 
Planet Drum band. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, 35 acts have been signed to perform at the 30th  
anniversary event, which will be held July 23-25 at the former 
Griffiss Air Force Base. Among the other groups scheduled to 
perform so far are The Dave Matthews Band, Jewel, Metallica, Alanis 
Morissette, Counting Crows and Sheryl Crow. 
</P>
<P>
	Individual Woodstock tickets go on sale for $150 nationwide on  
Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
