<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eagles Release RB Charlie Garner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Running back Charlie Garner was released  
Tuesday after five seasons with the Philadelphia Eagles on the eve 
of their second mini-camp under coach Andy Reid. 
</P>
<P>
	Garner, a second-round draft choice in 1994, rushed for 2,261  
yards and 17 touchdowns in 495 carries. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Garner battled ankle and rib injuries to play in just  
10 games, rushing for 381 yards and four touchdowns on 96 carries 
while catching 19 passes for 110 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Garner had been expected to replace Ricky Watters as the Eagles'  
primary running back in 1998 after Watters signed with the Seattle 
Seahawks as a free agent. Garner, an unrestricted free agent 
himself, re-signed with the Eagles for a reported $6 million over 
four years. 
</P>
<P>
	Garner made an impressive entrance to the NFL. After missing the  
first three games of his rookie year with a rib injury, Garner 
blitzed San Francisco for 111 yards and two touchdowns on 16 
carries. He got 122 yards the next week against Washington, 
becoming only the seventh player in NFL history to run for 100 
yards his first two games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
