<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed generally lower  
Tuesday on profit-taking, but the key index in Tokyo rebounded in a 
late rally triggered by foreign investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 22.90  
points, or 0.14 percent, to close at 16,697.11. On Monday, the 
index lost 177.37 points, or 1.05 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices recouped early losses as foreign and individual investors  
stayed bullish on the Japanese market. A tumble in hi-tech issues, 
triggered by a sell-off of technology shares in New York, had kept 
Tokyo stocks lower for most of the session. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, the technology-laden Nasdaq Composite Index lost  
138.43 points Monday, falling to 2,345.61, for its second-steepest 
drop ever. The Dow Jones industrial average fell after five 
straight sessions of record highs, slipping 53.36 points, or 0.5 
percent, to 10,440.53. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 118.04 yen in the late  
afternoon, down 0.12 yen from late Monday in Tokyo but above its 
late New York level of 117.58 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices in Hong Kong slumped as investors took profits  
following three straight sessions of sharp gains. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, fell 356.66 points, or 2.8 percent, closing at 
12,409.78. On Monday, the index had gained 276.14 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The profit-taking was expected after the index rose nearly 8  
percent over the past three sessions, brokers said. 
</P>
<P>
	They said investors largely discounted a government land auction  
on Tuesday, which fetched relatively good prices. The land auction 
was the first since the Hong Kong government froze land sales nine 
months ago following a plunge in property prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian shares also plunged on profit-taking, with the main  
index falling more than 4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said Monday's explosion at the Istiqlal Grand Mosque in  
Jakarta, following months of religious violence between Muslims and 
Christians in parts of Indonesia, made investors jittery. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jakarta Stock Exchange's Composite Index fell 4.3 percent,  
or 22.177 points, to 485.970 points. On Monday, the index had 
surged 6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares prices closed mostly lower on profit-taking.  
The Straits Times Index fell 1.8 percent, or 32.83 points, to 
1,809.48. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed little changed. The market's key  
Weighted Stock Price rose 4.56 points, or 0.1 percent, to 7,627.74. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed lower as the local  
market took a breather after four straight session gains. The 
NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 20.77 points, or 0.9 percent, to 
2,192.04. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Profit-taking took some steam out of Philippine shares,  
but advances made by selected blue-chip stocks pushed up the main 
index for a 13th straight day. The Philippine Stock Exchange index 
of 30 selected companies rose 2.67 points, or 0.1 percent, to 
2,358.65. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian shares closed lower, ending a run of record  
finishes as investors sold blue chips. The All Ordinaries Index 
closed at 3,090.1, down 23.00 points, or 0.7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed higher in reaction to plans by  
heavily indebted Daewoo Group to sell off its shipbuilding and 
other key businesses. The Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 
3.84 points, or 0.5 percent, to 770.43. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares closed mixed. The benchmark  
Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip stocks, rose 6.11 
points or 0.99 percent, to 621.53. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai stock prices closed lower following a two-day  
rally. The SET Index fell 6.08 points, or 1.5 percent, to 406.11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
