<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baby Bells, Sprint Profits Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Currency problems spoiled an otherwise strong quarter for  
BellSouth, but profits grew better than 15 percent at other major 
telephone companies in the first three months of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Ameritech led the profit gains with a nearly 20 percent  
improvement from year-ago levels, while its Baby Bell merger 
partner SBC Communications posted a 15 percent increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprint, the No. 3 long-distance provider, reported a 16 percent  
profit gain, but its PCS Group wireless business suffered a 
wider-than-expected loss. 
</P>
<P>
	BellSouth's net profit fell 45 percent as the currency crisis in  
Brazil overshadowed a robust showing in digital and Internet 
services. 

</P>
<P>
                        *SBC Communications    	
</P>
<P>
	The San Antonio-based provider of local calling service in the  
Western and Southwest earned slightly more than $1.1 billion, or 56 
cents per share, in the first quarter, boosted by growth in its 
core and wireless businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	In the same period last year, SBC earned $970 million, or 49  
cents per share, excluding a one-time gain from a change in 
accounting methods. 
</P>
<P>
	First-quarter revenues increased 6.7 percent to $7.3 billion  
compared with a year ago, fueled by the addition of nearly 300,000 
new wireless subscribers and strong demand for Internet access and 
premium phone services like Caller ID. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest results were right in line with the projections of  
most analysts surveyed by First Call. In Tuesday's trading on the 
New York Stock Exchange, SBC's shares rose $1.68 3/4 to $54.62 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	SBC said it expects to complete its planned acquisition of  
Ameritech, still awaiting FCC approval nearly a year after the deal 
was announced, by the middle of 1999. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Ameritech    	
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago-based provider of local phone service in the Midwest  
earned $732 million, or 66 cents per share, in the first quarter 
amid strong contributions from online services and the company's 
European investments. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding a one-time gain of $27 million from the adoption of  
new accounting standards, Ameritech earned $705 million, or 63 
cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	That was slightly better than most Wall Street forecasts and up  
19.5 percent from the $590 million, or 53 cents a share, in 
operating income Ameritech recorded in the first quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues rose 7.8 percent from year-ago levels to $4.46 billion,  
driven by a 40 percent jump in data services such as high-speed 
Internet connections. Revenues from premium telephone services rose 
17 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tuesday's trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Ameritech's  
shares rose $2.43 3/4 to $64.56 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
                            *BellSouth    	
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta-based provider of local phone service in the  
Southeast posted first-quarter income of $615 million, or 32 cents 
a share, including a charge of $280 million to reflect the plunging 
value of the Brazilian currency. 
</P>
<P>
	But excluding currency factors, the company enjoyed a strong  
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues rose 10.1 percent to $6 billion, bolstered by a 30  
percent jump in digital and data services business. 
</P>
<P>
	And without the currency-related charge, BellSouth's per-share  
earnings of 46 cents were slightly better than Wall Street 
projections and year-ago levels. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first quarter of 1998, BellSouth earned $892 million, or  
45 cents per share, including a one-time gain of $96 million from 
the sale of a business. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tuesday's trading on the New York Stock Exchange, BellSouth's  
shares fell 50 cents to $41.37 1/2. 

</P>
<P>
 *Sprint Corp.    	
</P>
<P>
	The Kansas City, Mo.-based long-distance company earned $406  
million, or 93 cents per share, in the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts surveyed by First Call had been expecting a per-share  
profit of 90 cents from Sprint, which in the same period last year 
earned $352 million or 80 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	First-quarter revenues rose 7 percent to $4.2 billion, led by a  
9 percent increase in long distance business 
</P>
<P>
	But the company's new wireless PCS Group, reflected by a  
separate tracking stock created last November, quadrupled its 
first-quarter loss to $625 million, or $1.46 per share. 
</P>
<P>
	In the same period last year PCS lost $145 million, or 97 cents  
per share, in the first quarter a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	The wider-than-expected loss overshadowed a quarter of stellar  
growth for PCS. Revenues nearly tripled to $604.2 million as 
763,000 new customers signed on during the quarter, rising the PCS 
subscriber total to 3.35 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tuesday's trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Sprint's  
shares rose $3.00 to $100.43 3/4, while PCS rose 62 1/2 cents to $47.62 1/2. 


</P>
</TEXT>
