<HEADLINE> Shots Fired at Colorado High School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- At least one gunman opened fire in a  
suburban Denver high school today, scattering students as bullets 
ricocheted off lockers. Witnesses said at least three students were 
injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Davis, a spokesman for the Jefferson County Sheriff's  
Department, said ``we do have injuries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now all I've got is there have been several shots fired,  
some explosions heard and some fire in the school,'' Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
	One student, Jonathon Ladd, said he was leaving a technology  
laboratory when he saw students running amid the gunfire. 
</P>
<P>
	Some witnesses said there were two gunman.  
</P>
<P>
	``They walked down the stairs and they started shooting  
people,'' said a student who gave her name as Janine. ``We didn't 
think it was real and then we saw blood.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said it was two young men, wearing black trench coats.  
</P>
<P>
	``They were shooting people and throwing grenades and stuff. ...  
Me and my friends got to my car and drove off. ... We saw three 
people get shot. They were just shooting. Then something blew up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ambulances and police cars were arriving at the school around  
lunchtime. 
</P>
<P>
	Ladd said he ran to a nearby park to escape the gunfire.  
</P>
<P>
	Columbine High School, opened in 1973, is southwest of Denver in  
the suburb of Littleton. It has an enrollment of about 1,800. 
</P>
</TEXT>
