<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Met Dusts Off Greek Art for Gallery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Metropolitan Museum of Art reopened its main  
Greek art galleries Tuesday after three years and $75 million worth 
of renovations that transformed the dark and dusty rooms into a 
polished, sun-washed space. 
</P>
<P>
	The galleries, arranged around a wide, 58-foot-high limestone  
hallway with classical columns, were built between 1912 and 1917. 
For years, the vaulted ceiling and its skylights were covered over, 
and the rooms were little more than a dull passageway to the museum 
restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	The rooms were closed for three years while workers cleaned and  
cleared the space, revealing the skylights. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're returning it to its original grandeur,'' said Carlos  
Picon, the Met's curator of Greek and Roman art. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, light streams down onto 1,900-year-old marble statues.  
Finely painted red-and-black terra cotta vases and carved reliefs 
that once marked Greek graves are also among the works on display. 
Many were restored after decades in the Met's attic. 
</P>
<P>
	In one larger-than-life piece, a wounded Amazon warrior stands  
with a hand atop her tilted head and a mournful look on her elegant 
face. Nearby are a slender male athlete and a woman draped in wraps 
so finely carved the stone falls like cloth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am overwhelmed,'' said Jeannette Dean, 81, one of the  
opening-day visitors. ``I'm at the point of tears. One visit is not 
enough. I'll have to come here many times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Six smaller rooms flank the main gallery, and curators have  
filled them with restored works from the fourth, fifth and sixth 
centuries B.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, pottery was grouped with pottery and sculpture with  
sculpture. Now works of many types are displayed together in 
chronological order, taking viewers from the early days of Greek 
democracy through Athens' flourishing as a political and cultural 
center to its loss of power around the time of Alexander the 
Great's death in 323 B.C. 
</P>
<P>
	``It places Greek art, the very birth of Western civilization at  
the very center of the Metropolitan,'' said Philippe de Montebello, 
the museum's director. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 14:55:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ETrade Earnings Exceed Forecasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Outpacing the rapid growth of the online trading  
industry, ETrade Group topped forecasts Tuesday for the first three 
months of 1999, showing robust gains in revenues and new customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding a one-time gain of $20 million from an investment,  
ETrade lost $14.3 million, or 12 cents per share, in its second 
quarter ended March 31. 
</P>
<P>
	While the second-largest Internet broker earned $4.5 million, or  
5 cents per share in the same period last year, the loss was 
smaller than the roughly 17 cents per share that analysts surveyed 
by First Call expected the company to lose. 
</P>
<P>
	ETrade's shares soared 21 percent after Tuesday morning's  
report, closing $16 higher at $89.81 1/4 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
The stock had plunged 50 percent over the past week amid a barrage 
of profit-taking among Web-broker shares. 
</P>
<P>
	The company reported second-quarter revenues of $126.7 million,  
up 44 percent from the final three months of 1999 and more than 
double its revenue tally in the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	ETrade said it added 233,000 new accounts during the latest  
quarter, an increase of 77 percent over the prior quarter's 
customer growth and more new accounts than the company added in all 
of 1998. As of March 31, the company had slightly more than 900,000 
accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	ETrade handled 4.3 million trades in the latest quarter, an  
increase of 55 percent from the final three months of 1999. By 
contrast, the overall industry's trading volume rose between 30 
percent and 35 percent during the first three months of 1999, 
according to a preliminary estimate by Credit Suisse First Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Notably, the accelerating growth came during a quarter that saw  
Web brokers suffer repeated slowdowns and outages as investors 
overwhelmed their online systems. 
</P>
<P>
	ETrade, based in Palo Alto, Calif., said it expects to continue  
to lose money in the near future due to aggressive spending on 
marketing, technology upgrades and customer service. 
</P>
<P>
	``We took strong positive action during the quarter to build our  
technology infrastructure and in our efforts to ensure that our 
customers have access to high-quality service and support,'' said 
Christos M. Cotsakos, chairman and chief executive of ETrade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
