<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Declares No-Fly Zone Over D.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- NATO is coming to Washington and bringing with  
it its own no-fly zone. 
</P>
<P>
	The military alliance will observe its 50th anniversary in  
Washington this weekend under cover of an expanded zone around the 
city and its monuments where flights are banned. 
</P>
<P>
	Aircraft already are forbidden in Prohibited Area 56, a swath  
that runs from the Capitol west over the Mall to the Lincoln 
Monument. The zone also extends over the White House and northwest 
to the vice president's residence at the U.S. Naval Observatory. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting Friday, unless authorized by air traffic controllers,  
pilots will not be allowed to fly below 18,000 feet within a 
10-nautical-mile radius of Ronald Reagan Washington National 
Airport, on the edge of the Potomac River, and Andrews Air Force 
Base in suburban Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	The effect will be a ban on low-level flights within a radius  
covering the Capital Beltway region and points to the southeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Sightseeing helicopters also will be banned within seven  
nautical miles of Reagan National. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the restrictions apply to commercial flights into Reagan  
National or diplomatic or military flights into Andrews, the home 
of Air Force One. Limitations remain in effect until Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	This weekend's celebration will bring together as many as 42  
heads of state. Security in Washington will be very tight, with 
streets closed and access to one section limited to those with 
Secret Service credentials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
