<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tech Stocks Recover; Dow Up 8.02 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices ended mostly higher on Tuesday as  
technology stocks recovered from Monday's rout but industrial 
companies, also changing course, fell amid profit-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average rose 8.02 to 10,448.55 after  
fluctuating between positive and negative territory throughout the 
session. The Dow lost 53 points Monday, ending a five-day streak of 
new closing highs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 16.69 to 1,306.17. The Nasdaq  
composite index, which is heavily weighted with technology stocks, 
rose 64.03 to 2,409.64, regaining nearly half the 138 points, or 
5.6 percent, it lost on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Many high-profile technology stocks that took big hits Monday  
recovered Tuesday. Internet shares were back in favor, including 
Amazon.com, up 13 1/16 to 172; and AOL, up 12 13/16 to 128 11/16. 
The shares of online traders rose sharply, with Schwab Corp. shares 
gaining 4 3/4 to 106 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Other computer-related stocks also advanced, including Dell, up  
2 3/4 at 38 3/16, Intel, up 1 1/16 at 56 9/16, and Cisco, up 1 9/16 at 
101 9/16. 
</P>
<P>
	But shares of companies that are sensitive to changes in the  
economy, such as manufacturers, ran aground after moving sharply 
higher last week. One of the biggest decliners among the Dow stocks 
was Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing, which fell 2 5/8 to 81 5/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Drug stocks that fell hard Monday rebounded on positive earnings  
reports. Merck, a Dow component, advanced 2 1/8 to 75 1/4. Retailers, 
which also had big losses Monday, were back in the plus column, 
with Wal-Mart, another Dow stock, up 2 7/8 to 47 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	``What you're seeing today is a classic bounce after an  
absolutely horrendous day yesterday,'' said Charles Pradilla, chief 
investment strategist at SG Cowen Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	The difference in this week's action, Pradilla said, has been  
its speed and ferocity. ``The incredible viciousness of this 
rotation is unlike any I've seen since I've been doing this, which 
is more than 30 years. It's like catching a moving bus -- in the 
teeth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the close of trading today, Microsoft reported  
first-quarter earnings of 38 cents a share, handily beating 
analysts' estimated 32 cents. Some analysts believed the report 
might keep the recovery in technology stocks going on Wednesday. 
Microsoft shares ended 2 1/8 higher at 83 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues had a small 6-to-5 lead on advancers on the New  
York Stock Exchange. Consolidated volume was heavy at 1.12 billion 
shares but off slightly from Monday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 4.96 to 620.84, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 1.87 to 736.98. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies rose 2.93 to 415.34. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.14 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	European markets were sharply lower. Germany's DAX index closed  
down 2.56 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 fell 0.71 percent, and 
France's CAC-40 skidded down 2.88 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
