<DOCNO> APW19990420.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 14:35:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MD-11 Wiring Inspections Ordered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- MD-11 aircraft must undergo emergency wiring  
inspections after airline mechanics found a loose wire, signs of 
electrical sparking and a burnt insulation blanket in the cargo 
hold of one airplane. 
</P>
<P>
	An emergency airworthiness directive, issued by the Federal  
Aviation Administration late Friday but made public Tuesday, is the 
latest in a series of inspections and emergency repairs ordered in 
the aftermath of last September's crash of Swissair Flight 111. 
</P>
<P>
	That investigation is focusing on wiring in the cockpit and  
entertainment systems of the Swissair plane, also a Boeing MD-11, 
and investigators do not believe the latest discovery explains that 
crash. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York-to-Geneva flight plunged into the ocean off Nova  
Scotia, 16 minutes after the pilots reported smoke in the cockpit. 
All 229 aboard were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, mechanics have paid close attention to all wiring on  
the planes. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, the FAA said: ``While performing routine  
maintenance on an MD-11, mechanics found evidence of wire chafing 
in the cargo loader control unit and burnt insulation. They also 
discovered that a wiring harness support bracket and clamp that 
supports a wire bundle may not have been installed on the 
aircraft.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Operators of the MD-11 were required to perform inspections,  
verify the installation of the bracket and clamp and repair any 
damaged wires within five days. Findings must be reported to the 
FAA within 10 days after completion of the inspections. 
</P>
<P>
	The airworthiness directive applies to MD-11s with a 72-inch  
cargo door. There are 45 such U.S.-registered airplanes and 89 
worldwide. Operators include American Airlines, Delta Air Lines, 
World Airways, Federal Express Corporation, and The Boeing Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The estimated cost to inspect the U.S. fleet is $8,100, or $180  
per aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, the FAA gave airlines two months to inspect MD-11s  
for wiring and insulation problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The order followed a letter from the National Transportation  
Safety Board, which also is investigating the Swissair crash, that 
noted signs of heat damage and electrical arcing found by Canadian 
investigators in an overhead cockpit panel and the avionics circuit 
bay of the crashed plane. 
</P>
<P>
	In December, the FAA ordered a one-time inspection of MD-11s to  
detect problems such as nicks, fraying or chafing above the left 
and right front passenger doors. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, the agency also ordered airlines to inspect  
lighting dimmer switches in the MD-11 cockpit. A month earlier, the 
FAA announced it had begun work on an order requiring the eventual 
replacement of insulation aboard the entire U.S. commercial 
aircraft fleet. Those recommendations are due shortly. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Swissair agreed in October to discontinue use of an  
advanced in-flight entertainment system on its MD-11s and some 
Boeing 747s as a safeguard against electrical problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week a Korean Air MD-11 crashed shortly after takeoff from  
Shanghai, China. The cause remains under investigation. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
