<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Economic Growth Seen Slowing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Massive stimulus spending by the government  
helped China grow a robust 8.3 percent in the first three months of 
this year, but its economy won't be able to sustain that pace, a 
state economist said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	With Chinese consumers and private companies reluctant to spend,  
growth will probably slow down in the second half of 1999 as public 
funds dry up, said Zheng Xinli, an economist with the State 
Development Planning Commission, the agency that guides government 
spending plans. 
</P>
<P>
	China's gross domestic product -- the sum of all goods and  
services produced within its borders -- will probably grow at about 
7 percent for the entire year, below last year's rate of 7.8 
percent but in line with government targets, Zheng said. 
</P>
<P>
	China's GDP totaled $205 billion (1.7 trillion yuan) in the  
first three months, said the State Statistical Bureau, which 
released its own figures Tuesday that mirrored Zheng's. 
</P>
<P>
	Zheng said the economy won't be able to pick up steam again as  
long as companies hold back on purchases of new factories and 
equipment, Chinese consumers continue to tighten their purse 
strings and exports remain down. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the government was targeting some of its stimulus money  
at spurring consumption by expanding consumer credit and boosting 
the income of poorer groups like farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	China is in the midst of a three-year, $1.2 trillion spending  
program on public works and other fixed assets aimed at fending off 
the ill effects of the Asian financial crisis, reviving the economy 
and creating new jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Zheng said the spending program was working. He pointed to a 30  
percent to 40 percent increase in new investments in key industries 
like telecommunications in the first three months of this year from 
the same quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The influx of public money has helped profits at manufacturing  
companies soar to six times their level in the same three months of 
last year and to the same levels as 1997, before Asia's economic 
crisis hit, Zheng said. 
</P>
<P>
	State-run enterprises also showed a turnaround, earning $115  
million in the first quarter compared with a loss of $664 million 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	But state enterprises still suffer huge inefficiencies that must  
be corrected as China moves from a socialist economy to a 
market-oriented one, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	This restructuring will probably further drag on growth as state  
enterprises keep cutting excess workers, adding to China's millions 
of unemployed. 
</P>
<P>
	Another problem is a drop in exports ever since the start of the  
Asian financial crisis, Zheng said. But signs that the crisis may 
finally be over would give a much needed boost to exports, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another glimmer of hope: Figures released Tuesday by the State  
Statistics Bureau showed a 7.4 percent rise in retail sales in the 
first quarter, a sign that consumers may be returning to stores. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
