<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Takes Tour of New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton had a simple explanation  
for New Yorkers on why she's considering running for office in a 
state where she's never lived. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love New York to start with -- I always have,'' the first  
lady said Monday as she jam-packed eight events around Manhattan 
into a 14-hour tour. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am very interested in a lot of the issues I think will  
continue to be important for New York and America into the next 
century. New York is truly a microcosm of America,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	As for her potential candidacy for the Senate seat being vacated  
next year by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, she would say only, 
``I'm obviously still considering and exploring and am very 
interested.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton began the second day of her New York road trip  
today at the Village Elementary School in Syosset, examining 
African dwarf frogs and plant life with some third-graders. She 
also planned to give a speech on health care and attend a United 
Jewish Appeal fund-raiser. 
</P>
<P>
	She returns to Washington on Wednesday but comes back to New  
York on Thursday with Niagara Falls among her planned stops. 
</P>
<P>
	Her itinerary is considered part of her work as first lady and  
is being paid for by U.S. taxpayers. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not an exploratory trip,'' she said. ``This is a trip  
filled with events and occasions, some of which I agreed to do 
months ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A new poll out Monday from Marist College's Institute for Public  
Opinion indicates that New Yorkers may be cooling to her. The 
telephone poll of 512 registered voters showed her and a likely 
Republican candidate, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, in a 
dead heat. Half of those polled said Mrs. Clinton should not run. 
</P>
<P>
	In a poll just two months ago, Mrs. Clinton led Giuliani, 49  
percent to 38 percent. Each poll had a margin of error of plus or 
minus 4.5 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one said it was going to be a cakewalk,'' said Sen. Charles  
Schumer, D-N.Y., who attended an event with Mrs. Clinton in Central 
Park. ``This is going to be a tough, tough race, but I think as 
people get to know her, she'll do better and better.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
