<DOCNO> APW19990420.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 15:07:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Seeks Support for Diplomacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Seeking a political solution to the Kosovo crisis,  
Russian diplomats conferred with representatives from Islamic 
nations and ex-Soviet states, but there were no signs of progress. 
</P>
<P>
	A number of the countries in Tuesday's talks did not necessarily  
share Russia's opposition to the NATO airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	Viktor Chernomyrdin, Russia's special mediator in the Yugoslav  
crisis, planned to visit the former Soviet states of Georgia, 
Azerbaijan and Ukraine in a bid to build support. 
</P>
<P>
	``The goal of my mission is to look for a peaceful settlement,  
to seek ways out of the Balkan crisis,'' Chernomyrdin said upon 
arrival in Georgia, his first stop. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, Chernomyrdin said his views largely coincided with  
those of Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze, the former Soviet 
foreign minister who had previously announced his own five-point 
plan for ending the conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	``Genuine and all-around settlement of the conflict in  
Yugoslavia cannot be achieved without Russia's active 
participation,'' Shevardnadze said, according to ITAR-Tass. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia, Azerbaijan and Ukraine are all members of NATO's  
Partnership for Peace program. While they have called for a 
peaceful settlement to the Kosovo crisis, they have not issued 
strong condemnations of the bombing campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	All three countries have sought to develop strong ties with the  
West in the post-Soviet era. Their presidents are heading to 
Washington this week for NATO's 50th anniversary celebration. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO has invited Russia to send a delegation to the NATO summit,  
but Secretary of State Madeline Albright said in Washington that it 
was not clear if Russia would participate. Russia has suspended 
cooperation with NATO to protest the air assault on Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov hosted a  
delegation from the Organization of the Islamic Conference, led by 
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi. 
</P>
<P>
	While Russia has sided with Yugoslavia, many Muslim nations feel  
more sympathetic toward ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, who are 
overwhelmingly Muslim. 
</P>
<P>
	The Iranian foreign minister praised Russia's efforts to find a  
peaceful settlement, but said the most important thing was to halt 
``all repressive action'' by the Yugoslav government against the 
Kosovo Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian President Boris Yeltsin last week tapped Chernomyrdin, a  
former prime minister, to serve as his mediator in the Yugoslav 
crisis. So far, Chernomyrdin has not offered any new peace 
proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin reiterated that Russia did not want the Kosovo crisis to  
undermine Russia's ties with Western countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot break off relations with leading world powers,''  
Yeltsin was quoted as saying by his spokesman, Dmitry Yakushkin. 
Yeltsin has ruled out Russian military intervention in the Yugoslav 
conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
