<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Banks Won't Show Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thai banks' earnings for the first  
three months of the year are unlikely to reflect the severity of 
the damage they've suffered from problem loans, analysts said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the quarterly results due out Wednesday will probably  
indicate that few banks have begun earmarking sufficient cash 
reserves against losses from problem loans -- which account for 
almost half of total lending. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because most have not been pressured to boost reserves in  
the first quarter by the crisis hit Southeast Asian country's 
central bank, according to analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	``The majority of Thai banks will take as little provisioning as  
they have to,'' Peter Redhead, head of research at ING Barings in 
Bangkok, told Dow Jones Newswires. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Bank of Thailand rules, commercial banks don't have to  
meet stricter loan-loss reserve requirements until the middle of 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Only Bangkok Bank, the country's largest, and Thai Farmers Bank,  
which have both successfully raised shareholder equity in the 
January to March period, have the capital base to continue 
prudently setting aside cash reserves well above minimum 
requirements, industry watchers say. 
</P>
<P>
	The two banks are likely to post much greater losses than other  
banks as they dip into reserves for bad loan write-offs. But they 
already have met their mid-year funding requirements and continue 
to accumulate funds to shore up their capital bases. 
</P>
<P>
	Other banks might post results which look better than the  
previous quarter -- although still in the red -- due to low 
provisioning and improving operating results. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said a decline in fixed deposit rates late last year,  
which in effect brings down a bank's cost for funds, also will 
begin to show up in better operating results in the first quarter 
of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Three-month fixed rates have fallen to around 5 percent at most  
commercial banks, compared to 8 percent about six months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks that might seem to do be doing better on the basis of  
Wednesday's results but will come under intense pressure to step up 
reserve funding in the second quarter include Thai Military Bank 
and Bank of Ayudhya, said Kavee Chukitkasem, banking analyst at 
Capital Nomura Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	With improved conditions for raising money through equity  
financing, analysts say banks should now provision above 
requirements to free up capital for new lending -- something seen as 
crucial for economic recovery in Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
