<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Reports Atrocities by Serbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Taking advantage of clear weather,  
NATO blasted tanks, military barracks and communications sites 
today as U.S. helicopters and troops headed toward Albania to boost 
the alliance's ability to attack Yugoslav ground forces. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO reported a series of ``disturbing developments'' today in  
the fourth week of allied airstrikes -- reports ``too numerous'' to 
ignore -- of Serb soldiers raping ethnic Albanian women, using tear 
gas to move ethnic Albanians out of homes in Pristina and 
``mixing'' into civilian convoys. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said Serb military and paramilitary  
forces were staging ``a kind of safari operation,'' shelling hills 
where ethnic Albanians fled to flush them out, marching the 
refugees on roads, putting them on trains to the border and then 
closing the border to them. 
</P>
<P>
	Shea said the alliance was investigating reports of ethnic  
Albanians -- hands tied behind their backs -- being used as ``human 
shields in front of tanks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fighting was also reported inside Kosovo between ethnic Albanian  
rebels and Serb forces. 
</P>
<P>
	The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe said 15  
wounded Kosovo Liberation Army fighters were brought to a hospital 
today in the Albanian border town of Bajram Curri, along with the 
bodies of two rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO commanders spoke of new accounts of mass executions,  
including ethnic Albanians flushed from their homes by Serb forces 
firing tear gas, and of ethnic cleansing operations spreading from 
Kosovo into the border villages of Montenegro, Yugoslavia's smaller 
republic. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the grim reports, NATO and its 19 allies intend ``to see  
this through to the end, no matter how long it takes ... until 
President (Slobodan) Milosevic backs down,'' Shea said at the 
briefing in Brussels, Belgium. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright wouldn't go so far as to  
call for Milosevic's removal but said the Yugoslav people would 
``be better served by a democratic government that represents their 
values.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The flood of refugees from Kosovo slowed today, raising fears  
that Yugoslav soldiers were turning away those trying to flee. 
Ninety percent of Kosovo's 2 million people are ethnic Albanian, 
and Yugoslav forces have expelled an estimated 640,000 of them from 
the province since last month. 
</P>
<P>
	British Prime Minister Tony Blair said the NATO airstrikes that  
began March 24 have destroyed 50 percent of Milosevic's best 
fighter planes, the MiG-29s, 25 percent of its MiG-21s and 30 
percent of its Super Galebs, which he said are used in attacks on 
civilians in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana, who met with Blair in  
Brussels, stressed that ``as we destroy and damage Milosevic's 
extensive military machine, we are also taking care of Milosevic's 
victims'' -- the waves of ethnic Albanians he has driven from the 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. refugee agency, meanwhile, declared its camps in  
Macedonia full beyond capacity today, leaving 2,000-3,000 new 
arrivals from Kosovo stuck in a border no man's land. Another 2,000 
to 3,000 Kosovo Albanians successfully made their way over the 
mountains elsewhere in Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 350,000 refugees already have reached Albania, but  
only a few crossed the border today. It was unclear whether 
fighting halted the flow or Serbs blocked it. 
</P>
<P>
	Macedonia's camps hold 46,600 of the 127,200 Kosovo Albanian  
refugees now in the country. As a stopgap, the U.N. refugee agency 
plans to expand refugee airlifts across Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO, Blair said, had minimum, simple demands to end the  
conflict: Milosevic's forces ``get out of Kosovo,'' an 
international military force goes in and people be allowed to 
return to their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	The allies remain united in the battle, Albright said, promising  
to end Milosevic's and his military, paramilitary and police 
forces' ability to ``wage war on its own people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Albright is trying to persuade her fellow foreign ministers to  
cut off shipments of refined oil to Yugoslavia as another way to 
cut into Milosevic's war machine, which launched its Kosovo 
crackdown in February 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Aided by good weather, NATO airpower reportedly targeted at  
least eight areas of Serbia and its Kosovo province, hitting 
particularly hard at Yugoslavia's third-largest city, Nis. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO said it struck six tanks, army barracks in Prizen, oil  
depots and an ammunition plant. It said all its aircraft returned 
to their bases safely. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbian media reported one person was killed and 12 injured when  
NATO missiles slammed into a residential area of Nis, a southern 
industrial city that is the headquarters of Yugoslav forces in 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav state media claimed that almost all sites struck today  
were non-military. In Nis, reports said 10 homes were destroyed, 
and the state-run Tanjug news agency said the country's main 
cigarette factory had been destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong anti-aircraft fire and explosions could be heard from  
Belgrade and Serbian media said the alliance struck a major 
telecommunications relay facility at Prilike. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, Maj. Gen. Charles Wald said 24 Army Apache attack  
helicopters would probably arrive in Albania today. Small numbers 
of U.S. support troops have been arriving in Albania's capital this 
week in advance of the gunships. 
</P>
<P>
	The helicopters are to attack Yugoslav forces in Kosovo in  
conjunction with ground-based multiple rocket launchers. The task 
force will involve 3,000 U.S. troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
