<HEADLINE> Virginia Executes Man for 2 Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- A man who shot his uncle and another man a  
month after he got out of prison was executed by injection Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur Ray Jenkins III, 29, was convicted of capital murder in  
the October 1990 slayings of his uncle, Floyd Jenkins, 72, and Lee 
H. Brinklow, 69. 
</P>
<P>
	``Forgive me for my sins,'' Jenkins said shortly before his  
death, crying out several times as prison officials inserted the 
injection needles into his body. 
</P>
<P>
	Jenkins had been drinking when he went to a house shared by his  
uncle and Brinklow and got into an argument. He took a .22-caliber 
rifle from a bedroom and shot his uncle and Brinklow, then 
repeatedly stabbed the uncle. 
</P>
<P>
	Jenkins' attorneys said he was mentally ill as a result of years  
of physical and sexual abuse and received improper treatment during 
a previous prison stay. 
</P>
<P>
	Having been placed on anti-psychotic medication when he was 13,  
he was sentenced at the age of 16 to seven years in prison for 
burglary and grand larceny. 
</P>
<P>
	Jenkins was released from the jail in 1990 without supervision  
or medication, his lawyers said. He had been out 36 days when he 
committed the two murders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
