<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Groups To Meet Bid Deadline for A's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Two groups of investors plan to meet  
Wednesday's deadline for putting down a $12 million deposit to buy 
the Athletics, a deal that would keep the team in Oakland through 
at least the 2004 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Under an agreement worked out months ago with current team  
owners Steve Schott and Ken Hofmann, public officials have until 
Wednesday to receive bids from investors willing to buy the team 
for $120 million. 
</P>
<P>
	If public officials cannot work out a deal to sell the team,  
Schott and Hofmann will have the right to sell or move the A's. San 
Jose has been mentioned as a city possibly interested in seeking 
the team. 
</P>
<P>
	A's president Mike Crowley said Tuesday that two investor groups  
have expressed interest in bidding for the team, though neither has 
actually asked to see the club's books. 
</P>
<P>
	Another group of investors, the Mandalay Group, received  
pre-approval from major league baseball and did look briefly at the 
club's books, but decided not to bid, Crowley said. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the groups expected to deposit $12 million in escrow by  
the Wednesday deadline includes former A's executive Andy Dolich, 
Hall of Fame second baseman Joe Morgan and Bob Piccinini, the 
chairman of Modesto-based Save Mart Foods, who is providing the 
deposit for the group. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things are going well,'' Dolich said. ``Our position has  
always been that we'll get it done by the close of business on the 
21st, if not sooner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other group expected to bid includes former pitcher Steve  
Stone, now a broadcaster for the Chicago Cubs, and former A's coach 
and New York Yankees general manager Bob Watson. That group's 
deposit will be provided mostly by Arizona banker Lyle Campbell. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of an agreement reached with Schott and Hofmann in  
October that set the sale price at $120 million, the Athletics 
agreed to remain at the Oakland Coliseum for at least three more 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	The A's agreed to stay in Oakland through the end of the 2001  
season, with a right to extend their lease on a year-to-year basis 
through the 2004 season. When Schott and Hofmann bought the A's for 
$85 million in 1995, they signed a nine-year lease at the Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	If either of the investor groups buys the A's, they will be  
required to keep the team in Oakland through at least the end of 
the 2004 season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
