<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Push On for Watercraft Speed Limit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government and the world's leading  
manufacturer of personal watercraft want the industry to limit the 
speed of water scooters to 65 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Bombardier Recreational Products, maker of Sea Doo models, took  
the lead Monday by announcing voluntary compliance with the limit 
on 2000 year models, going on sale early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We challenge the rest of the industry to join us in capping  
top speeds,'' said Henry Lonski, vice president and general manager 
of Sea Doo watercraft. 
</P>
<P>
	Jan Hall, a Sea Doo spokeswoman, said: ``There's been this speed  
war going on for years within the watercraft industry. At some 
point it makes sense to address the issue. There's a real fine line 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard welcomed the initiative. According to its  
records, 4,070 personal watercraft were involved in accidents in 
1997. Of those, there were 84 drownings. 
</P>
<P>
	While no direct correlation has been made to speed, the National  
Transportation Safety Board said last year that most accidents 
involve operators who have little experience riding the powerful 
machines. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal is to provide a balance between fun and safety.  
Speeds in excess of 65 mph upset this delicate balance,'' said a 
statement issued by Capt. Michael Holmes, chief of the Coast 
Guard's Office of Boating Safety. 
</P>
<P>
	Jack O'Dell, a Coast Guard spokesman, acknowledged that 65 mph  
is fast on either land or water, but he said the limit should help. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think people understand: If you fall off a personal  
watercraft at a high rate of speed, it's just like falling off a 
motorcycle,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Personal watercraft look much like a motorcycle on water, with  
handlebars and a seat that riders straddle. The standard piston 
engine is replaced with a jet that sucks in water, spits it out the 
tail and propels the craft through the ocean, up rivers or across 
lakes. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past decade, the machines have boomed in popularity.  
Sales peaked at 205,000 units in 1995, but 130,000 were sold last 
year. About 1.2 million now are in use nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	While sales have fallen recently, top speeds have increased from  
quick to hair-straightening. Kawasaki, which makes the Jet Ski 
model line, sells the Ultra 150, which has a top speed of 68 mph. 
Sea Doo's fastest, the XP, goes 63.5 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall estimated that every 1 mph gain in speed costs a  
manufacturer $1 million in development costs. She said Bombardier 
could make a model to compete with Kawasaki's Ultra 150, but the 
money should be spent on making personal watercraft quieter and 
less polluting. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesmen for Kawasaki and other leading manufacturers did not  
immediately return calls seeking comment on the Bombardier 
proposal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
