<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Sees Bright Signs in Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Economic conditions remain severe throughout Japan,  
but recent public spending measures have begun to spark 
improvement, the Finance Ministry said Wednesday in a report on the 
nation's regional economies. 
</P>
<P>
	The report, based on findings of the ministry's branch offices,  
said that the employment situation remains severe in all regions 
and that capital spending is expected to fall further this year. 
</P>
<P>
	But the ministry added that public works have been greatly  
boosted under a record supplementary budget announced last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Corporate bankruptcies have also dropped in most regions due to  
an emergency credit guarantee program established by the government 
last October, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other bright spots include signs that the slump in corporate  
earnings and industrial activity may be coming to an end, the 
report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The ministry added that in some regions, personal consumption  
has shown signs of bottoming out, although it still remains 
generally sluggish. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
