<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Companies Post Strong Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Pharmaceutical companies on Tuesday reported  
generally strong first-quarter earnings, with Johnson &AMP; Johnson and 
SmithKline Beecham PLC beating Wall Street forecasts. 
</P>
<P>
	Schering-Plough Corp. and American Home Products Corp.'s results  
were in line with expectations. The shares of all four companies 
rose on the reports, reflecting the stock market's ``very high 
confidence in the industry to post earnings,'' said Sergio 
Traversa, analyst with Mehta Partners. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Johnson &AMP; Johnson    	
</P>
<P>
	J&AMP;J's first-quarter profit rose 11.7 percent, driven by strong  
drug and medical device sales. 
</P>
<P>
	New Brunswick, N.J.-based J&AMP;J earned $1.12 billion, or 82 cents  
a share, up from $1 billion, or 73 cents a share, in the same 
period a year ago. Results beat Wall Street's expectations by 2 
cents a share, according to First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales in the first quarter rose 14.8 percent from $5.8 billion  
to $6.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Global drug sales rose 18.4 percent to $2.5 billion, including a  
23 percent jump in the U.S. market. The company said its major 
drugs had strong sales, including Procrit, an anemia drug, 
Risperdal, an antipsychotic medication and Duragesic, a transdermal 
patch for pain. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's medical device division posted an 18.6 percent  
increase in sales to $2.4 billion. J&AMP;J's 1998 purchase of 
orthopedics products maker DePuy spurred much of the growth. J&AMP;J 
also was aided by strong sales of surgical equipment, sutures and 
glucose monitoring devices, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of consumer goods, including Tylenol, rose 5.4 percent to  
$1.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of J&AMP;J rose $6, or 7 percent, to $96.25 in trading on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Schering-Plough Corp.    	
</P>
<P>
	Schering-Plough's first quarter profit rose 20 percent, mainly  
from accelerating sales of Claritin, the world's best-selling 
antihistamine. 
</P>
<P>
	Madison, N.J.-based-Schering-Plough earned $539 million, or 36  
cents a share in the first quarter, up from $450 million in the 
same quarter a year ago. Results matched analysts' expectations, 
according to First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales rose 15 percent from $1.5 billion to $2.2 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Claritin sales comprised about 27 percent of the company's  
sales. Global Claritin sales jumped 29 percent to $565 million, 
including a 33 increase in U.S. sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Combined sales of Intron A and Rebetron Combination Therapy for  
hepatitis C, rose 66 percent to $272 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Schering-Plough rose $1.87 1/2 to $50.37 1/2 on the NYSE.  

</P>
<P>
                    *American Home Products Corp.    	
</P>
<P>
	Excluding a special charge in 1998, American Home Product's  
first quarter profit was flat mostly due to weak sales of 
herbicides. 
</P>
<P>
	Madison, N.J.-based American Home earned $654.9 million or 49  
cents a share in the first quarter, compared to $651.4 million or 
49 cents a share in the same period a year ago. The results matched 
analysts expectations. The 1998 results exclude the $331 million 
sale of the company's medical device business. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales fell 1 percent in the first quarter to $3.4 billion from  
$3.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Agricultural product sales declined 18 percent in the first  
quarter due to lower herbicide sales as wholesalers built 
inventories last year and the company dealt with lower prices for 
soybeans and corn. Agriculture products make up about 15 percent of 
the company's sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Worldwide drug sales declined 1 percent as strong sales of the  
new rheumatoid arthritis drug Enbrel and antidepressant drug 
Effexor could not make up for weaker sales of the heart drug 
Cordarone and oral contraceptives. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of American Home rose $2.56 1/4 to $62.31 1/4 on the NYSE.  

</P>
<P>
                       *SmithKline Beecham PLC    	
</P>
<P>
	SmithKline Beecham PLC's first quarter profit rose 15 percent  
from strong growth of the company's antibiotic and depression and 
anti-smoking drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	London-based SmithKline earned $606 million, or 49 cents per  
share in the first quarter, compared to $526 million, or 43 cents 
per share in the same period a year ago. Analysts surveyed by First 
Call had predicted earnings of 47 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue increased 9 percent for the quarter, from $3.11 billion  
to $3.40 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	SmithKline Beecham's pharmaceutical sales grew 12 percent. The  
growth was fueled by the antibiotic Augmentin, which rose 19 
percent to $484 million, and Paxil/Seroxat, a depression drug 
therapy, which rose 17 percent to $461 million. Vaccine sales rose 
12 percent to $297 million, driven partly by the company's new 
vaccine for Lyme disease. 
</P>
<P>
	On the over-the-counter market, smoking cessation products,  
including Nicorette smoking cessation gum and patch, posted a 68 
percent increase in sales to $183 million. 
</P>
<P>
	SmithKline's American Depositary Receipts rose $3.93 3/4 to $66.68 3/4  
on the NYSE. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
