<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chase, Mellon Banks Post Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Four major U.S. banks posted strong  
first-quarter profits Tuesday, capping a double-digit increase for 
the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Chase Manhattan Bank, Wells Fargo and Mellon Bank all reported  
earnings that topped Wall Street's expectations, while Bank One's 
results matched estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	``The earnings this morning were good,'' said Catherine Murray,  
an analyst with J.P. Morgan. ``Revenue continues to come in higher 
than expected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The large national banks saw an impressive 8 percent profit  
increase over the first quarter last year, and beat estimates by 
about 10 percent, according to First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Regional banks like Mellon posted an average 14 percent gain in  
profits, but the results were just 1 percent higher than estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	``The results are strong, said Brad Ball, an analyst with Credit  
Suisse First Boston. ``Now people are starting to question just how 
sustainable they are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investors don't seem to agree on how long the good times will  
last as bank stocks were mixed in afternoon trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank stocks have had a good run over the past six months, and on  
Tuesday, Citigroup and Mellon both announced stock splits and 
dividend increases. Stock splits increase the number of shares 
outstanding, but decrease their price in order to make them more 
affordable to investors. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Chase Manhattan Corp.    	
</P>
<P>
	Chase Manhattan, the nation's third-largest bank, reported  
profits of $1.17 billion, or $1.32 a share, beating Wall Street's 
estimate of $1.25 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	The results were 11 percent better than the first quarter last  
year, when Chase earned $1.05 billion, or $80 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Operating revenues rose 10 percent to $5.41 billion from $4.92  
billion in the first quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are looking for 1999 to be a record year in our history,''  
said Dina Dublon, chief financial officer for Chase. 
</P>
<P>
	While most consumers probably think of checking and savings  
accounts when they think of Chase, the New York bank actually makes 
more than half its money selling corporate bonds and complicated 
interest rate contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	Chase has a strong business in providing venture capital money,  
private banking for wealthy individuals and loans for medium-size 
companies. Chase's Global Bank, as it is known, earned $844 million 
in the first quarter on revenues of $2.59 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues from trading stocks and bonds and related interest  
income rose 21 percent to $837 million, a new record. 
</P>
<P>
	Expenses were $2.94 billion in the first quarter, an increase of  
12 percent, as the bank continues to update its computer systems 
for the year 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Return on common equity was 20.6 percent, up slightly from 20.3  
percent from the year-ago quarter. Return on assets was 1.24 
percent vs. 1.08 percent. Return on assets is a key measurement of 
profitability, indicating how efficiently a financial institution's 
assets are employed. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the solid results, Chase's stock fell $2 to $83 on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Bank One Corp.    	
</P>
<P>
	Bank One, the country's No. 4 bank, posted earnings of $995  
million, or 88 cents a share, up 6.6 percent from the first quarter 
last year, when the Chicago-based bank earned $933 million, or 78 
cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	The results met Wall Street expectations.  
</P>
<P>
	Bank One's 1999 earnings do not reflect three special items: A  
gain of $249 million gain from its merger with First Chicago NBD 
Corp., and a charge of $204 million for accounting changes and 
integration costs. Additionally, Bank One recorded a $111 million 
gain for the sale of its Electronic Payment Services company. 
</P>
<P>
	Including all one-time charges and gains, Bank One earned $1.15  
billion, or 96 88 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	``We began to see the promised merger expense and revenue  
synergies, which should gain momentum throughout the year,'' John 
B. McCoy, president and chief executive of Bank One, said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues totaled $4.59 billion, up 20 percent from $3.81 in the  
first quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Return on assets was 1.85 percent, up from 1.59 percent in the  
first quarter last year. Return on common equity was 22.9 percent, 
an increase from 20.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank One's stock slipped 25 cents to $59 on the NYSE.  

</P>
<P>
                          *Wells Fargo &AMP; Co.    	
</P>
<P>
	Wells Fargo, the seventh-largest bank in the country, posted  
profits of $884 million, or 53 cents a share, for the first quarter 
of 1999, a healthy 29 percent increase over the year ago period. 
The results topped analysts' estimate by 3 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first quarter last year, the San Francisco-based bank  
earned $684 million, or 41 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues of $3.99 billion were up from $3.73 billion, as more  
customers bought homes and needed mortgages, and the bank's venture 
capital investments started paying off. Wells Fargo merged with 
Norwest Corp. last November. 
</P>
<P>
	Return on average assets was 1.80 percent, up 1.51 percent from  
the year-ago period. Return on average common equity was 17.33 
percent vs. 14.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Wells Fargo's stock rose $1.25 to $42.37 1/2 on the NYSE.  

</P>
<P>
                            *Mellon Bank    	
</P>
<P>
	Mellon, which ranks 18th among the nation's banks, earned $231  
million, or 87 cents a share, compared with $206 million, or 78 
cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	The results beat analyst estimates by 1 penny a share.  
</P>
<P>
	Mellon's first quarter 1999 earnings reflect a $49 million  
after-tax net gain from divestitures and a $26 million after-tax 
charge for the cumulative effect of a change in accounting 
principle. Including those one-time events, Mellon earned $254 
million, or 96 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Total interest revenue was $711 million vs. $694 million a year  
ago, while non-interest revenue was $872 vs. $698 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pittsburgh-based bank also announced an 11 percent increase  
in its quarterly cash dividend to 40 cents a share (pre-split) and 
a two-for-one split of its common stock. 
</P>
<P>
	The dividend will be paid May 17 to shareholders of record April  
30, and the stock will be split will also be distributed May 17 to 
shareholders of record May 3. 
</P>
<P>
	Return on common equity fell slightly to 20.9 percent from 21.6  
percent a year ago. Return on assets also fell to 1.84 percent vs. 
1.89 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Mellon's stock dipped 6 1/4 cents to $70.93 3/4 on the Big Board.  




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
