<DOCNO> APW19990420.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 16:24:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wings' Chelios Known for Intensity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- You only need to ask Chris Chelios who his sports  
hero was growing up to understand his style of play. No one brings 
the intensity of Dick Butkus to the ice like Chelios. 
</P>
<P>
	``He plays every shift like it could be his last,'' said Anaheim  
coach Craig Hartsburg, who coached Chelios with the Blackhawks. 
``He is a warrior.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chelios says it's the way he's played since junior hockey. He  
had been a small center in youth hockey, but was thrown back on 
defense when he moved into junior hockey in Moose Jaw, 
Saskatchewan. He was the only American in the league at the time 
and felt he had something to prove. 
</P>
<P>
	``People challenged you. It was just my way,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	It's been his way ever since.  
</P>
<P>
	Chelios, a three time winner of the Norris Trophy as the NHL's  
top defenseman, is one of the first Americans to dominate in the 
NHL and was the first U.S. born player to captain the Montreal 
Canadiens. 
</P>
<P>
	He plays with a belligerent style, the kind that causes home  
fans to love him and opposing fans to hate him. He gives hard hits 
and is frequently the targets of hits. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been hurting for years so it doesn't matter to me,'' he  
said with a smile. 
</P>
<P>
	He's already won over the Detroit fans who two years ago in the  
playoffs were hanging him in effigy. He said playing in Detroit, 
home of one of the Original Six teams, is a special feeling. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt it in Montreal, I felt it in Chicago and I feel it  
here,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He's fit in quickly with his new teammates and is carrying a  
lighter load. The Blackhawks needed him to play 30 minutes a night, 
running the power play and killing penalties. The Red Wings have 
more depth on defense and don't need him to do everything. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest challenge for Chelios and the Red Wings against the  
Mighty Ducks will be to contain Teemu Selanne and Paul Kariya, who 
finished second and third in the league in scoring. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to stay close to them, not give them much room,''  
Chelios said. ``We've got to put our best game on the ice and make 
them adjust to us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Wings plan on doing that with physical play.  
</P>
<P>
	``Any time you have the opportunity to hit those guys, you have  
to hit them,'' center Kris Draper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wings have to be careful, though. The Ducks have the  
league's best power-play unit with a 25.5 percent success rate, 
compared with 18 percent for the Red Wings. And with two referees 
on the ice, there may be more penalty calls. 
</P>
<P>
	``So we're going to have to be disciplined,'' Chelios said.  
</P>
<P>
	Discipline isn't a word frequently associated with Chelios or  
Ulf Samuelsson, another player with a nasty streak. Putting the two 
of them on the same team creates a unit only a hometown fan can 
love. Especially when some other fans may resent the appearance 
that Red Wings owner Mike Ilitch might be trying to buy his way to 
another Stanley Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who cares?'' forward Darren McCarty asked. ``The commitment  
our ownership has shown is that he is willing to go out and do what 
it takes to win. That's not a bad thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Chelios and Samuelsson, the Wings added forward  
Wendel Clark and goalie Bill Ranford. Since the trade, Detroit is 
9-2-1, has outscored opponents 37-20, has one shutout and has given 
up just one goal in five games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our team really got re-energized and everybody got their jump  
back,'' defenseman Nicklas Lidstrom said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chelios said he knows he'll be nervous before the first playoff  
game Wednesday night. He always is come playoff time. 
</P>
<P>
	He still remembers his first playoff game in 1984 against the  
Boston Bruins. He scored the first goal of the game and the 
Canadiens upset the Bruins before falling to the New York 
Islanders. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years later, he helped lead Montreal to a Stanley Cup. He  
thought it would be the first of many. He went to the finals again 
with the Canadiens in 1989 and with Blackhawks in 1992, but he's 
still looking for his second title. 
</P>
<P>
	The quest for that title is still what drives him.  
</P>
<P>
	``Every time the playoffs come around it's fun,'' he said. ``I'm  
just going to go out and play.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 06:05:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Straw Reportedly Passes Drug Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Darryl Strawberry's future depends on the  
results of his latest drug tests, due to be received by the 
commissioner's office sometime this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Yankees outfielder came through the first test OK,  
according to a published report today. 
</P>
<P>
	The test was given last week, 24 hours before he was arrested in  
Tampa, Fla., for cocaine possession and solicitation. It indicated 
``there was no problem,'' The Record of Hackensack, N.J., reported, 
quoting sources said to be familiar with Strawberry's legal 
predicament. 
</P>
<P>
	Had the results revealed traces of a drug, Strawberry faced at  
least a six-month ban from baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry was tested again during a weekend visit to New York  
when he met with officials of the players association, the 
commissioner's office and doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	Those close to Strawberry were confident that the latest tests  
will be fine as well, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball had been testing the outfielder twice a week as part of  
the aftercare program that followed his 60-day suspension in 1995 
for a positive test for cocaine use. Strawberry has not tested 
positive for illegal drugs since then, the Yankees said last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry, 37, was at the Yankees' training camp as part of its  
extended spring training program. He was still rehabilitating from 
colon cancer surgery in October. 
</P>
<P>
	``As of right now, he is not resuming workouts,'' Cashman said  
Monday. ``From the club's perspective, he's got his legal issues 
and personal issues to deal with. It's best for him at this 
particular moment to deal with that. Baseball is second right 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's unclear if the Yankees have stopped paying Strawberry, who  
is not on their 40-man roster. He has a minor league contract and a 
consulting deal with the team, which together total $2.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	New York has been advancing money to Strawberry and may have  
stopped those advances, one of the sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	No arraignment date has been set for Strawberry, but when he is  
formally charged, he will plead innocent, his attorney said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Entrapment is a pretty wide avenue,'' attorney Joseph  
Ficarrota told The Record from his office in Tampa. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry has said he as only joking with the female undercover  
officer posing as a prostitute. 
</P>
<P>
	Ficarrota will argue that the charges should be dropped since no  
money changed hands between Strawberry and the woman, Strawberry 
was arrested after driving beyond the motel where the woman told 
him to meet here, and there was no tape recording of the 
conversation between the outfielder and the officer. 
</P>
<P>
	If Ficarrota succeeds in getting the solicitation charge  
dropped, he will argue there was no probable cause for the 
subsequent search which police said produced three-tenths of a gram 
of cocaine inside a rolled up $20 bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Without probable cause, the search would be illegal, Ficarrota  
told the newspaper, and its results inadmissable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
