<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colleagues Sue Winner of Fla. Lotto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOBILE, Ala. (AP) -- Tonda Dickerson's days of juggling dishes  
and coffee cups at the Waffle House ended soon after a customer 
rewarded her with a Florida Lotto ticket worth $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	But when she turned in her apron without sharing the jackpot  
with four co-workers, a sizzling dispute ensued. Her four 
co-workers filed suit claiming there had been an agreement to 
divide any winnings equally. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of moving out of her Grand Bay mobile home, the  
28-year-old former waitress was in court Monday testifying there 
was no such agreement to divide lottery winnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Her Waffle House co-workers, however, testified there was a  
share-the-wealth plan and that in conversations around the hot 
grill they often discussed how they would spend the money. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was always stated that if we hit, we split,'' one of the  
four co-workers, Matthew Adams, told the jury. 
</P>
<P>
	Mobile County Circuit Judge Robert Kendall said the jury's  
verdict will be an advisory one, meaning he will make the final 
decision on whether Mrs. Dickerson must share her wealth. 
Deliberations were expected to resume today. 
</P>
<P>
	Edward Seward Jr., the Waffle House customer from Bayou La Batre  
who gave away the lottery tickets, has said he expected the 
restaurant employees to share any winnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Adams said Seward ate breakfast daily at the restaurant and on  
March 7 handed out tickets to five employees as tips. Mrs. 
Dickerson's winning ticket was in an envelope with her name on it. 
</P>
<P>
	Seward, 41, who managed a seafood restaurant until suffering a  
stroke, declined requests for interviews and sat huddled with 
relatives after testifying Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The co-workers' attorney, Steve Clements, said the case was  
about telling the truth and the ``corrupting influence of money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dickerson's lawyer, Dwight Reid, accused the co-workers of  
cooking up a ``nefarious scheme'' to claim part of the money. 
Besides, he said, there was no written contract to divide the 
money, which is required by Alabama law. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute occurred at the one of the national chain's  
restaurants near Interstate 10 in Grand Bay on the Alabama coast. 
The yellow and black, diner-style eateries are famous for pecan 
waffles and hash browns. 
</P>
<P>
	When Mrs. Dickerson went to Tallahassee, Fla., to pick up the  
jackpot, lottery officials refused to pay her because of the 
dispute with co-workers Sandra Deno, Angela Tisdale, Jackie Fairley 
and Adams. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for the other workers had offered to settle. Under the  
proposed agreement, Mrs. Dickerson would receive 30 percent of the 
jackpot, with each of the four other employees receiving a 17.5 
percent share. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dickerson declined, even though she could end up with only  
a 20 percent cut if a jury decides the five should equally split 
the money. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
