<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Polygamy Goes on Trial in Utah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOGAN, Utah (AP) -- A man accused of beating his daughter after  
she ran away from an arranged marriage to his brother goes on trial 
Wednesday in a case that has many calling for a crackdown on Utah 
polygamy. 
</P>
<P>
	John Daniel Kingston, 43, is charged with felony child abuse for  
allegedly beating his 16-year-old daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl, now living in foster care, says her father drove her  
to a family owned farm near the Idaho line in May and whipped her 
for disobeying Daniel Ortell Kingston, who had made her his 15th 
wife. 
</P>
<P>
	But to many, the real defendant in the case is not the father,  
but a way of life in Utah that has survived in the shadows for more 
than a century. 
</P>
<P>
	Though polygamy is banned by the state constitution and  
denounced by the Mormon church, the attorney general's office 
estimates there are 25,000 practitioners in Utah alone. 
</P>
<P>
	And though lawyers for both sides say the trial is not about  
polygamy, the Kingston clan is one of the most prominent polygamous 
groups in Utah, and the issues have become inseparable. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Polygamy) is the very reason this whole thing is coming  
down,'' said Owen Allred, the leader of a separate polygamous clan 
based in Bluffdale. 
</P>
<P>
	``Generally speaking, our people are very peaceful,  
mind-your-own-business people,'' Allred said in a telephone 
interview. But right now, he said, he feels like his way of life is 
on trial. 
</P>
<P>
	No large-scale bigamy cases have been prosecuted since the  
1950s, when agents raided the town of Short Creek on the 
Utah-Arizona line. The incident backfired when the public, enraged 
by images of families being torn apart, protested and the state 
backed off. 
</P>
<P>
	Anti-polygamy groups say prosecutors should attack once more.  
They say the brothers should face bigamy as well the other charges 
-- child abuse against John Kingston and incest charges against 
Daniel Kingston, who is to be tried in June. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're really missing the boat on this one,'' said Carmen  
Thompson, executive director of the advocacy group Tapestry of 
Polygamy, comprised of former polygamous wives. ``When you see 
crimes stemming directly from the polygamy issue, the polygamy 
should be prosecuted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The clan led by patriarch Merlin Kingston goes by the name of  
the ``Latter-day Church of Christ'' and has about 1,000 members. 
The brothers are the sons of the clan's leader, who died in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Though not the largest polygamous group, the Kingstons are the  
most affluent, with assets estimated around $150 million. 
</P>
<P>
	When the issue exploded with charges filed against the Kingston  
last year, Gov. Mike Leavitt -- the great-grandson of polygamists -- 
said he thought the practice might be protected by the First 
Amendment. He soon backed away from that idea. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say it is difficult to prosecute bigamy, the only  
charge associated with plural marriage. Marriages are often 
performed in secret ceremonies, evidence can be skimpy or 
nonexistent, and they don't want to gamble time and resources while 
more pressing crimes demand attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have concentrated and focused on the abuses,'' said Palmer  
DePaulis, chief of staff for Utah Attorney General Janet Graham. 
</P>
<P>
	To that end, the office is trying to educate members of  
polygamous groups, including the children, how to recognize child 
abuse, date rape and domestic violence. There is also a hotline for 
wives of polygamists. 
</P>
<P>
	But others say that approach treats the symptoms, not the  
problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, the underlying problem is the polygamous relationship  
that exists and they ought to be prosecuting that relationship, not 
just the child abuse,'' said Dexter Anderson, a Millard County 
prosecutor. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the Kingston case ``opened the floodgates,'' Thompson said  
her office has fielded hundreds of calls from plural wives looking 
for help. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can tell you that even if the prosecutor doesn't see this as  
a polygamy case, the public does see it as a polygamy case,'' she 
said. ``How long is the abuse going to continue?'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 17:13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Profits Jump 43 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft Corp.'s quarterly profit jumped 43  
percent from a year earlier on strength across its range of 
products, particularly its Office business software and Windows NT 
software for running corporate computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, the world's dominant maker of personal computer  
software, reported Tuesday it earned $1.92 billion, or 35 cents a 
share, in its fiscal third quarter, which ended March 31. That was 
up from a profit of $1.34 billion, or 25 cents a share, in the 
year-ago quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue rose to $4.33 billion from $3.77 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	The profit beat the predictions of analysts surveyed by First  
Call Corp., who had expected 32 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	The financial results were released at the close of markets,  
where Microsoft stock rose $2.12 1/2 a share at $83.12 1/2 on the Nasdaq 
Stock Market amid a strong rebound from Monday's selloff of 
technology and Internet stocks. In after-hours trading, shares of 
Microsoft were trading slightly lower at $82.25. 
</P>
<P>
	Not included in the third-quarter results is $400 million in  
revenue from early sales of Microsoft's new Office 2000 package of 
business software. Microsoft said it would defer that revenue into 
the current quarter. The product starts retail sales on June 10. 
</P>
<P>
	``Financially and operationally it was a very nice quarter, if  
somewhat complicated from an accounting standpoint,'' Greg Maffei, 
chief financial officer, said on a conference call with reporters 
and analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd say it's more of the same in terms of where the growth is  
coming from,'' said Scott McAdams, president of brokerage McAdams 
Wright Ragen in Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, which has no debt and pays no stock dividend, also  
reported a whopping $21.76 billion in cash and short-term 
investments, an increase of 56 percent from the $13.93 billion it 
had on hand last June 30. Long-term investments grew from $4.7 
billion to $7.47 billion in the past nine months. 
</P>
<P>
	The company doesn't have any new plans for its cash stockpile,  
said Carla Lewis, director of investor relations. Microsoft 
typically taps its reserves for research and development, business 
deals and to fund employee stock options. 
</P>
<P>
	Maffei partly tied the company's latest profit to strong demand  
for its server software, and said sales in Asia were rebounding. 
Licenses for SQL Server, its database software for large 
corporations, rose 50 percent from the year-ago quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Software sales to computer manufacturers were up 29 percent from  
last year, and sales of operating system software accounted for a 
bit more than $2 billion of the revenue for the quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's Windows operating system runs the basic functions of  
90 percent of the world's personal computers. The company is 
fighting federal charges that it illegally wields its Windows 
monopoly to stifle competition in the technology industry. 
</P>
<P>
	While some manufacturers have suffered because of stronger  
demand for lower-cost computers, the higher number of machines sold 
benefited Microsoft, Maffei said. 
</P>
<P>
	``While there were jitters during the quarter and after, the PC  
market seems to be fundamentally healthy,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, which typically plays down profit expectations, was  
cautious about growth for the rest of calendar 1999. Microsoft said 
customers were deferring purchases of new software in order to get 
ready for the so-called Y2K bug, in which computers incorrectly 
interpret the year 2000 as the year 1900. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of fiscal 1999, Microsoft reported  
profits of $5.58 billion or $1.02 a share, compared with net income 
of $3.13 billion or 59 cents a share a year earlier. Revenues grew 
to $13.22 billion from $10.49 billion. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 20:52:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colo. Shooting Reopens Old Wounds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Sabrina Steger was already crying when she picked up the phone.  
</P>
<P>
	She had been in tears all afternoon since she first heard about  
Tuesday's shooting at a suburban Colorado high school. A place 
filled with children -- like her 15-year-old daughter, Kayce, who 
was gunned down in December 1997 when another student opened fire 
on a group of students praying in the hallway. 
</P>
<P>
	Sobbing to a reporter, the Paducah, Ky., woman said she relives  
the terrifying scene of her daughter's death every time a new 
shooting happens at another school. Tuesday's attack was at least 
the sixth in the less than 18 months since then. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's Dec. 1, 1997, all over again. How many more times does  
this have to happen?'' sobbed Steger. ``It doesn't get any 
easier.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others in communities across the country that have been  
devastated by school shootings said the latest violence just brings 
to the surface nightmares they have never entirely put behind them. 
</P>
<P>
	``My daughter said a week ago, 'I wonder when it's going to  
happen again,''' said James Strand, who owns the dance hall where 
Andrew Wurst, 15, gunned down middle school teacher John Gillette 
at a graduation dance in Edinboro, Pa., last April 24. 
</P>
<P>
	``She said, 'I think it's just a matter of when and where,'''  
Strand said. ``And she was right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strand, whose wife and four children were at the dance, chased  
Wurst down and held him until police came. The survivors of the 
Columbine High School shooting have hard days ahead, he predicted. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has taken any innocence. It has stripped it from me and it  
has stripped it from my wife and my children,'' he said. ``Now we 
watch everything we do and everywhere we go, and that's the biggest 
loss for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Edinboro residents had been planning a prayer vigil Saturday to  
mark the painful anniversary of the Gillette shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been a very hard week for me. And this is not  
helping,'' Debbie Gillette, the teacher's widow, said of the 
Colorado shooting. ``It makes me sick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell Wright, whose wife, teacher Shannon Wright, was killed  
in March 1998 in Jonesboro, Ark., said he heard about the Colorado 
shootings on his car radio as he was driving on nearly the same 
stretch of road that he was on when he learned his wife had been 
shot. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just instantly think back to what happened in your own  
life last year and you feel for the families and what they're about 
to go through,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Springfield, Ore., Thurston High School principal Larry Bentz  
broadcast news of the Colorado shootings over his school's intercom 
as soon as he learned of it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd rather they hear it from me than from rumors,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	But still reeling from their own school rampage 11 months  
earlier, several students mistakenly thought the nightmare was 
happening again at Thurston. 
</P>
<P>
	``A whole bunch of people started to get scared and stuff. Some  
people started going toward the door thinking it was happening 
here,'' said Thurston student Willie Kumle. 
</P>
<P>
	The Littleton shooting has been a violent reminder to this small  
town of last May's tragedy, when student Kip Kinkel allegedly 
walked into the school's cafeteria and opened fire, killing two 
students and wounding more than 20 others. He is also accused of 
fatally shooting his parents a day earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's creepy really,'' said James Ready, 17, a junior at  
Thurston. ``I honestly thought ours would be the last one, that 
people would have grown up by now.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
