<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Importers Complain About Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A French chef complained that his recipes  
won't taste right without Dijon mustard. A German delicatessen 
operator worried that without German raspberry jam her Linzertortes 
won't be the same. 
</P>
<P>
	For a full day, more than 50 witnesses went before a government  
hearing panel Monday to urge that products they cared about be 
exempted from 100 percent tariffs the Clinton administration is 
threatening to impose on more than $900 million of European 
products in a nasty trade fight involving beef. 
</P>
<P>
	Importers of foie gras, truffles, Belgian chocolates, mineral  
water and a host of other European delicacies all argued they were 
being caught unfairly in a trade war between the world's two 
largest trading partners. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where is the beef in motorcycles?'' asked Edward W. Moreland,  
Washington representative for the American Motorcycle Association. 
He said the group's 234,000 cycle enthusiasts can't understand why 
European motorcycle imports were being threatened in a food fight 
involving beef. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeffrey Buben showed up in his chef's uniform to say he was  
worried that business at Bistro Bis, his new French restaurant in 
Washington, would be hurt without Dijon mustard, a key ingredient 
in many of his restaurant's dishes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dijon mustard is a unique product, and nothing else in the  
United States comes close,'' he told the officials from nine 
government agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	The purpose of the hearing was to gather information the  
administration will use when it pares down the original list of 
more than $900 million in European products to a smaller amount on 
which the punitive tariffs will actually be imposed. 
</P>
<P>
	The prohibitive tariffs are designed to knock European products  
out of the U.S. market in retaliation for Europe's ban on American 
beef from cattle treated with growth hormones. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Trade Organization has ruled in favor of the U.S.  
cattle industry's arguments that the 10-year ban was not justified 
on scientific grounds. American cattle producers on Monday put the 
price of their annual losses at $500 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The products targeted in the beef dispute are in addition to  
$194.2 million in European imports ranging from fancy handbags to 
bed linen that have been subjected to punitive tariffs since March 
3 in a separate fight with the European Union over trade barriers 
imposed on bananas produced by American companies. 
</P>
<P>
	While the beef hearing was under way, U.S. and EU officials were  
meeting in Washington to search for a compromise that will avert 
the beef sanctions from going into effect in June. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky said after the  
talks with Sir Leon Brittan, the EU's top trade official, that the 
United States was willing to consider labeling U.S. beef as coming 
from America, but the American side is resisting EU attempts to 
include language pointing out the use of growth hormones on grounds 
that there is no scientific evidence the hormones are harmful. 
</P>
<P>
	``The key question is whether the EU will respect the clear and  
unambiguous WTO ruling to lift its ban on U.S. meat,'' Barshefsky 
said after the discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	Hildi Fehr, owner of a German delicatessen and restaurant just a  
few blocks from the White House, told the government hearing 
officers she is concerned about the loss of a host of European 
products from Rittersport chocolate and Zweiback toast to various 
European fruit jams and syrups. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Schwartau raspberry jam is very important to me,'' she  
said, calling it a key ingredient in her Linzertortes. ``I have 
tried to use American substitutes ..., but the small jars don't 
have the same intense flavor or consistency as the German raspberry 
jam,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of American breakfast cereals could go up if the  
government keeps oats on the list, because the United States 
imports one-third of the oats it uses, mainly from Canada, Sweden 
and Finland, officials representing American cereal makers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank Capalbo, owner of Capalbo Gift Baskets Inc. of Nutley,  
N.J., said he can't believe his own government is making it so 
difficult for him to decide what Irish food products he can afford 
to include in his catalogue, which must be printed soon for next 
year's Christmas season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
