<HEADLINE> First Union May Go West for Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- First Union Corp. chief executive Ed  
Crutchfield is doing some California dreaming of his own. 
</P>
<P>
	Crutchfield, speaking today at the bank holding company's annual  
shareholders' meeting in Charlotte, hinted he would like to follow 
the lead of crosstown rival BankAmerica Corp. and go west for its 
next major merger. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's clearly a huge banking market on the West Coast,''  
Crutchfield told about 150 people at this morning's meeting at bank 
headquarters. ``Unfortunately, there are few banks left to 
acquire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charlotte-based BankAmerica completed what was the nation's  
largest bank merger when the former NationsBank combined with San 
Francisco-based BankAmerica last year in a stock deal valued at 
$41.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Crutchfield said there are other ways First Union can expand on  
the West Coast, such as purchasing brokerage houses and other 
financial institutions. But he said he would love to buy a big 
bank. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a desire of ours. I wish we were there today,'' he said  
in response to a shareholder's question. ``It's a big desire on my 
part, particularly California, which has 10 percent of the 
country's population. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's on our radar screen and very high,'' Crutchfield said.  
``The question is, how do we do it?'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other news, shareholders elected former White House Chief of  
Staff Erskine Bowles and nine other nominees to the board of 
directors of the nation's sixth-largest bank. Bowles, 53, is a 
general partner with Forstmann Little &AMP; Co. of New York and also 
managing director of Carousel Capital Co. of Charlotte. 
</P>
<P>
	In his remarks, Crutchfield said he was pleased with First  
Union's 1998 financial performance. The company said in January it 
earned $2.89 billion, a 7 percent gain over the $2.7 billion in 
earnings for 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in excellent position to leverage the platform we've  
built,'' he said. ``I must say that 1999 is going to be a 
challenging year. We will focus our efforts on controlling costs 
and gaining new sources of revenue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Crutchfield also said in a interview that he doesn't anticipate  
additional major employment cutbacks. First Union announced last 
month it was cutting 5,850 jobs and leaving two non-core businesses 
as it restructured following the $16.1 billion merger with 
CoreStates Financial Corp. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
