<HEADLINE> Japan Trade Surplus Rises 23 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's trade surplus with the world rose 23  
percent in fiscal 1998 from the previous year for the second 
highest total ever recorded, the government announced Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The merchandise trade surplus, the measure of all goods exported  
by Japan minus those imported, rose 23.1 percent to 14.097 trillion 
yen ($118.46 billion), the Finance Ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
	The figure was the second largest after the 14.402 trillion yen  
($121.02 billion at current exchange rates) recorded in fiscal 
1986. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's trade surplus with the United States rose 24 percent to  
6.687 trillion yen ($56.19 billion) for the fiscal year, the fifth 
largest surplus on record. 
</P>
<P>
	The country's trade surplus for March, the last month of the  
fiscal year, increased 7.5 percent to 1.334 trillion yen ($11.2 
billion) from the same month last year, the ministry said. The 
surplus is figured before adjustment for seasonal factors. 
</P>
<P>
	The March surplus was in line with the average forecast of  
Tokyo-based economists surveyed by Dow Jones Newswires. 
</P>
<P>
	A Japanese Finance Ministry official, speaking on condition of  
anonymity, said that the government believes Japan's trade balance 
with the world is stabilizing. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that despite the 23 percent jump last fiscal year, a  
quarterly breakdown showed that the rate of increase slowed sharply 
in the third and fourth quarters of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The surplus rose 46.3 percent in the first quarter and 42.8  
percent in the second quarter. In the third quarter, it rose 7.8 
percent, and gained just 3.6 percent in the final quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, Japan's trade surplus fell 32.2 percent for the  
first decline in three months and only the second since April 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The ministry official said the narrowing trade balance trend was  
due mainly to continued low levels of exports to the rest of Asia, 
compounded with a fall in export levels to the United States and 
Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's politically sensitive trade surplus with the United  
States also rose in March, jumping 29.1 percent to 570.30 billion 
yen ($4.79 billion), the ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
	For fiscal 1998, Japanese exports to America rose 4.2 percent,  
coming to 15.160 trillion yen ($127.40 billion) -- the second 
largest figure ever. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan has been under heavy pressure from the United States and  
other trading partners to rein in the surplus by bolstering its 
weak economy to spark demand for imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
