<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't Accountability Bill Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government would be required to  
report each year on the costs its numerous regulations impose on 
businesses and government bodies under a bill approved Tuesday by a 
House subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation would increase the federal government's  
accountability and improve the quality of regulatory programs, said 
its sponsors, Reps. Tom Bliley, R-Va., and David McIntosh, R-Ind. 
The GOP has introduced several measures to curb the creation of new 
rules and regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	``As many Americans filed their federal income taxes last week,  
I'm sure many wondered where their hard-earned dollars were 
going,'' Bliley said. ``This bill will help answer that question by 
providing an annual accounting statement of regulations at all 
federal agencies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House Government Reform Committee's panel on national  
economic growth, natural resources and regulators affairs approved 
the bill by voice vote over the objections of some Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Dennis Kucinich, D-Ohio, said the Clinton administration  
has joined labor, environmental, consumer protection and public 
health groups in opposing the bill because it could tie up already 
overburdened government agencies with work that may end up being of 
little value. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure may ``seriously hamper the work of federal  
government agencies which are mandated to protect the public from 
adverse consequences and certain business practices,'' threats to 
the environment and public health and unfair labor practices, 
Kucinich said. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreover, he said, the bill puts too much emphasis on the impact  
of regulations on businesses and other organizations and too little 
on how the regulations affect the people they are designed to 
protect. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would require the Office of Management and Budget to  
compile accounting statements on the costs of federal regulations. 
Accompanying reports would analyze the impact of regulations on the 
private sector, including small businesses, wages, consumer prices 
and economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that the bill will not impose any undue burden on  
OMB since much of the needed information is already available,'' 
McIntosh said. 
</P>
<P>
	The subcommittee approved a Kucinich amendment that would have  
OMB also look at impacts on public health, public safety, the 
environment, consumer protection, equal opportunity and other 
policy goals. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., has introduced similar legislation  
in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 1074.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
