<HEADLINE> eToys To Merge With BabyCenter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Internet toy retailer eToys Inc. announced today  
that it will merge with BabyCenter, Inc., which runs a Web site 
that offers advice to new and expectant mothers. 
</P>
<P>
	Santa Monica, Calif.-based eToys will issue shares of its common  
stock to BabyCenter's stockholders in exchange for their 
outstanding shares of BabyCenter capital stock. 
</P>
<P>
	eToys sells products from more than 500 manufacturers, including  
mass market brands like Mattel and Hasbro, and specialty names like 
Brio and Creativity for Kids. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts told USA Today that eToys hopes the content-heavy site  
of San Francisco-based BabyCenter will drive sales as moms using 
BabyCenter will turn to eToys to buy toys for toddlers. BabyCenter 
sells products and supplies for infants. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal gives eToys another boost with its initial public stock  
offering later this month expected to be one of the most-sought 
after of the year. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
