<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 15:35:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Roba's Boston Win Is An Easy One </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Maybe Fatuma Roba finally will have some  
down-the-stretch competition. Maybe Louise Sauvage will race away 
to an easy victory for a change. 
</P>
<P>
	None of that happened in the past three Boston Marathons in  
which Roba easily won the women's division, or in the past two 
women's wheelchair races when Sauvage edged Jean Driscoll at the 
finish line twice. 
</P>
<P>
	Sauvage and Driscoll were so close in both races that they were  
clocked in the same official time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew she was behind me, but I didn't know how close she was  
until I saw her on the TV later,'' Sauvage, of Australia, said 
Tuesday. ``I like the competition. I like her to be there pushing 
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Next year, Driscoll may not be there. The Champaign, Ill.,  
resident said she hasn't decided if she'll run in the 104th Boston 
Marathon in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to evaluate my season in the fall. I have to see  
whether I have the heart or mental strength to do this again,'' she 
said. In Monday's race, she didn't have the physical strength to 
overtake Sauvage. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of 11,481 racers started the marathon and 11,293 --  
including seven women wheelchair competitors -- finished. Franz 
Nietlispach of Switzerland easily won his fourth men's wheelchair 
race and third in a row. In the men's open division, Joseph Chebet 
became the ninth straight Kenyan champion after finishing second in 
his previous three marathons, one in Boston and two in New York 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	Chebet's time of 2 hours, 9 minutes, 52 seconds was 27 seconds  
faster than runnerup Silvio Guerra of Ecuador. The Sauvage-Driscoll 
battle was much closer. 
</P>
<P>
	Furiously spinning the wheels of her chair with her arms,  
Driscoll worked hard to take over the lead, but Sauvage held her 
off. Both were timed in 1:42:23 over the 26-mile, 385-yard course. 
They were timed in 1998 in 1:41:19. 
</P>
<P>
	``Number 8 has been very elusive,'' seven-time winner Driscoll  
said. ``I think the close losses are why it hurts so much the next 
morning. It's heartbreaking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said she deliberately stayed behind Monday, hoping to race  
past Sauvage near the end, but ``she's a very good sprinter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sauvage also won in 1997, racing by herself for the last four  
miles. If Driscoll's chair hadn't been upended on trolley tracks, 
that race also might have gone down to the wire. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do my best when I have somebody pushing me,'' Sauvage said  
after Monday's race. 
</P>
<P>
	It may not matter how Roba feels about that since no runner has  
been able to push her over the final several miles as she won the 
last three races by 42 seconds, 3:56 and 2:26. Next year, the 
Ethiopian who won the 1996 Olympic gold medal can become the first 
four-time winner of the women's open division since it became an 
official part of the race in 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope to get the same invitation'' to run in the race, Roba  
said, ``and, hopefully, to win the fourth Boston Marathon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She won her third after China's Sun Yingjie pushed a blistering  
pace before being overtaken just past the midpoint and finishing 
11th. Roba and Kenya's Catherine Ndereba ran together for a while 
before Roba surged ahead with about eight miles to go and kept 
stretching her lead. Ndereba came in sixth. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a Chinese girl running ahead of me (but) the only  
one who scared me was the Kenyan girl who was next to me,'' Roba 
said. ``At 25 kilometers (15.53 miles) I knew I was going to win 
the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All she had to do was run more than 10 more miles to make it  
official. She did it so quickly, in 2:23:35, that she was 24th 
overall, the best finish by a woman in the race's history. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I do my training in Ethiopia, I only do my own pace,''  
Roba said. ``So I don't worry about who's ahead of me or who's 
behind me. I always have my own strategy. That's what I'm going to 
continue to do.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
