<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Police: 2 H.S. Shooting Suspects Dead  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Police said two suspects were dead after  
a pair of young gunmen dressed in long, black trench coats opened 
fire in a suburban Denver high school. At least 20 people were 
injured. Police also led a student away from the school in 
handcuffs. ``He's one of the ones who shot at us,'' said another 
student. Officials said an unknown number of injured people 
remained in the school. Police scoured the school as dozens of 
students fled on foot. There were also reports of explosions inside 
Columbine High School. Shortly after the school was stormed by SWAT 
teams., three youths wearing black were stopped by police in a 
field near the school. It was not clear if they were connected to 
the shooting. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Cites Serb Atrocities  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO reported ``disturbing  
developments'' in Kosovo today, including Serb soldiers raping 
ethnic Albanian women, using tear gas to move ethnic Albanians out 
of homes in Pristina and ``mixing'' into civilian convoys. NATO 
spokesman Jamie Shea said Serb military and paramilitary forces 
were staging ``a kind of safari operation,'' shelling hills where 
ethnic Albanians fled to flush them out, marching the refugees on 
roads, putting them on trains to the border and then closing the 
border to them. Shea said the alliance also was investigating 
reports of ethnic Albanians being used as ``human shields in front 
of tanks.'' 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Declares Macedonia Camps Full  
</P>
<P>
	SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) -- The U.N. refugee agency declared its  
camps in Macedonia full beyond capacity today, leaving 2,000 to 
3,000 new arrivals from Kosovo stuck in a border no man's land with 
no food, water or blankets. While the exhausted refugees faced a 
second night of driving wind and rain, those fortunate enough to 
cross the border faced new harassment in Macedonia, which has 
reluctantly taken in refugee throngs. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Profits Jump 43 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft Corp.'s quarterly profit jumped 43  
percent from a year earlier on strength across its range of 
products, particularly its Office business software and Windows NT 
software for running corporate computers. Microsoft reported today 
it earned $1.92 billion, or 35 cents a share in its fiscal third 
quarter, which ended March 31. That was up from a profit of $1.34 
billion, or 25 cents a share, in the year-ago quarter. Revenue rose 
to $4.33 billion from $3.77 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	Everglades Blaze Being Blocked  
</P>
<P>
	IN THE FLORIDA EVERGLADES (AP) -- Smoke rose from the burning  
Everglades today as fire officials said they were close to blocking 
the blaze that had charred more than 130,000 acres. The fire, 
however, was pushing toward the south and west and could cover an 
additional 40,000 acres before it is declared contained, state 
forestry officials said. There was a chance that the state would 
reopen a 60-mile stretch of South Florida's main east-west highway, 
Interstate 75, later today. 

</P>
<P>
	Cigarette Billboards Coming Down  
</P>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- In the Marlboro Man's hometown and across  
the nation, cigarette billboards that were once were a celebrated 
part of the American landscape are coming down this week as part of 
the national settlement with the tobacco industry. In many places, 
the rugged cowboy with the cigarette dangling from the corner of 
his mouth will yield to images of young children delivering 
anti-smoking messages. Under the $206 billion agreement between the 
tobacco industry and 46 states to settle state claims for 
smoking-related health costs, all cigarette billboards must be 
removed by Friday. 

</P>
<P>
	Telecom Italia Supports Merger  
</P>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Telecom Italia SpA's board of directors today agreed  
in principle to a merger with Germany's Deutsche Telekom AG, but 
several major issues still must be resolved. Following a seven-hour 
board meeting, Telecom Italia released a statement saying it 
supports a ``business combination agreement'' under which a new 
company would be set up to combine the two companies. Telecom 
Italia did not disclose any financial details of the deal it 
favored. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Up 8.02; Nasdaq Gains  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks regained ground today after  
yesterday's slip, and the Dow ended the day up 8.02 to 10,448.55 
after yesterday's big loss. On the NYSE, decliners led advancers 
1,673-1,379. The Nasdaq was up 64.12 at 2,409.73. 

</P>
<P>
	Giants' Bonds Out At Least 10 Weeks  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Barry Bonds will be out of the lineup for  
at least 2 1/2 months after surgery today on his throwing arm. The 
All-Star left fielder underwent an operation to repair a triceps 
tendon in his left arm and a bone spur in his elbow. San Francisco 
Giants team physician Dr. Bill Montgomery said Bonds was expected 
to be released from the hospital today and fitted for a brace this 
week. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  

</P>
