<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 14:35:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hank Aaron Reigns as Career HR King </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Like any red-blooded baseball fan, Hank Aaron  
watched in awe last summer as Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa staged a 
seasonlong celebration of his signature hit -- the home run. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never thought anybody would hit 70,'' said Aaron, who never  
hit more than 47 in any one season but finished with a record 755. 
``Seventy. Nobody ever dreamed of 70 when I was hitting my little 
40.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All of Aaron's 40-something seasons -- he reached that total  
eight times and was in the 30s seven other times -- added up to one 
of baseball's most cherished records. 
</P>
<P>
	A quarter-century ago, Aaron's pursuit of Babe Ruth's record of  
714 home runs was accompanied by racial overtones and threats on 
his life and family. 
</P>
<P>
	His run at Ruth was less celebrated than it was acknowledged. At  
the end, there was relief rather than joy about the achievement. 
The scars of that time are buried in the deepest part of his 
psyche, overshadowed by the good times he now enjoys. 
</P>
<P>
	There's a new award carrying his name that will go to baseball's  
best hitter and a slick new photo book reflecting on his life and 
his achievement. President Clinton attended his 65th birthday party 
and invited him to visit the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	The acclaim is coming 25 years after the fact, but Aaron  
understands. 
</P>
<P>
	``Good things come to those who wait,'' he said. ``I had no  
choice but to wait.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aaron watched baseball embrace McGwire and Sosa as they chased  
Roger Maris' single season record of 61 and felt a little jealous. 
</P>
<P>
	``McGwire, every time he hit a homer, he raised his son,'' he  
said, recalling the home plate greeting that became a ritual 
between father and son. ``I was unable to do that. If I had, how 
wonderful it would have been.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aaron's pursuit of Ruth was largely ignored by everyone  
involved, including Aaron. The record sort of crept up on him, but 
that's what happens when you play 23 years and keep hitting 30 and 
40 home runs every season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think of home runs,'' he said. ``I think of other  
things. My stealing percentage was very good. I was able to field 
with anybody. Not one time did I strike out 100 times in a season. 
That's what's required to hit 40 or 45 homers. If I made contact, I 
had a good chance of getting a base hit or hitting it out of the 
park.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And, of course, he did that with regularity, which is what is  
required to catch him. 
</P>
<P>
	Aaron thinks Ken Griffey Jr. has the best shot.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's 29 and he has 350,'' Aaron said. ``If he keeps doing what  
he's doing, he can break it. It will take a ballplayer an awful 
long time having good years to hit 755. I played a long time. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing that can get in the way is if he gets hurt or  
gets complacent. That's the worst thing than can happen. You start 
thinking you're better than you are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aaron's last 40-homer season was 1973, when he finished with  
713, one homer behind Ruth's record. He homered in Cincinnati 
during the Braves' opening series there in 1974 to tie the record 
and then broke it in Atlanta's home opener. 
</P>
<P>
	He hit 20 home runs that season, then returned to Milwaukee with  
the Brewers for two final seasons. There was no farewell tour, no 
chance for baseball to say goodbye. He just walked away from the 
game after the 1976 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went out the same way I came in,'' he said. ``I didn't have  
a celebration. I wouldn't want it any other way. I knew I was going 
to retire. I knew I played as long as I could. There was no 
baseball left in me.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 03:55:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mormon Family Library Reopens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Mormon church President Gordon B.  
Hinckley, speaking at the funeral of a slain church security guard, 
expressed outrage that a mentally ill man was able to buy the 
handgun used to kill two people and wound four others. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking to more than 1,000 mourners Monday at the Westbrook  
Stake Center in West Jordan, Hinckley said there was no answer to 
why Donald Thomas, a 62-year-old grandfather, had to die. 
</P>
<P>
	``This terrible incident becomes a warning to all of  
ever-present danger'' when ``warped minds'' can still easily obtain 
firearms, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hinckley expressed dismay that ``such a person'' was somehow  
permitted to ``arm himself with an automatic weapon to cut down and 
kill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The gunman, Russian immigrant Sergei Babarin, 70, had been  
treated for a mood disorder and reportedly had not been taking his 
medication before walking into the church's Family History Library 
on Thursday with a .22-caliber handgun. 
</P>
<P>
	Babarin opened fire without warning, killing a patron, Patricia  
Irene Frengs, 55, police said. Authorities said he then fired into 
Thomas' chest and wounded four others before being killed in an 
exchange of gunfire with police. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot live and work in a bunker mentality,'' said  
Hinckley, the leader of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day 
Saints. ``This entire episode was gruesome ... and we hope never to 
experience it again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The library reopened Monday for the first time since the  
shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	Hinckley said that he regularly had exchanged morning greetings  
with Thomas, whom he remembered as ``a self-effacing man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He would look down on this vast congregation today and say,  
`How come all this for me?''' Hinckley said, then answered: ``It is 
because of our love and appreciation and respect for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hinckley said the church would make provisions for the continued  
care and support of Thomas' widow, Konadee, who suffers from 
multiple sclerosis and uses a wheelchair. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of people lined up outside the building before it  
opened about a half hour late due to a devotional service for the 
library staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Kempe said he was ``a little apprehensive, but I'm not  
going to stop coming. I'm still going to do it -- because it's 
important to me, and I come every Monday.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
