<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM's Pearce Back After Cancer Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Harry Pearce says his brush with death has  
changed him. 
</P>
<P>
	The vice chairman of General Motors Corp. -- a top candidate to  
replace chairman Jack Smith when he retires -- returned to the 
public spotlight Monday for the first time since undergoing nearly 
a year of treatment for leukemia. 
</P>
<P>
	Pearce conducted a news conference announcing a joint venture  
with Toyota Motor Corp. to do research and development into 
advanced technology vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel absolutely great,'' Pearce said. ``My physicians tell  
me I'm progressing extremely well. And I'm back at work, full 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pearce, 56, was diagnosed last year with leukemia. He underwent  
a stem-cell transplant at the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research 
Center in Seattle and until recently had continued to work from 
home as he recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview that will appear in the May 10 edition of  
Fortune magazine, Pearce says the painful experience of facing the 
possibility of death and the difficult treatment for leukemia 
changed the way he views work and people. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has been a very real transformation in how I think,''  
Pearce said. ``Even people I didn't care for in the past, I find 
myself re-examining and looking for the good, and often finding it. 
This experience focuses your attention on what I would call real 
value. You're less egocentric because you realize in a very direct 
way how the support of others has contributed to your still being 
around. 
</P>
<P>
	``Your relationship with other people -- your family, your  
friends, your fellow employees -- becomes much more important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pearce's position in GM's succession plan was cast in doubt last  
summer when his illness was discovered. But with his leukemia in 
remission and his role at Monday's event, it's clear that Pearce 
has resumed a high-profile role with the world's largest automaker. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortune said the lawyer made it clear he would like to succeed  
Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I owe the corporation is the ability to deliver 100  
percent,'' Pearce told the magazine. ``If I can deliver that, 
leukemia should not be an issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	G. Richard Wagoner Jr., 46, was elevated to president and chief  
operating officer in October and is seen as Pearce's top competitor 
to replace Smith, who recently turned 61. The mandatory retirement 
age at GM is 65, but there has been some speculation that Smith may 
step down sooner. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
