<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 15:35:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Anheuser-Busch Abandons Plastic Idea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Anheuser-Busch Cos. has ended a month-old  
experiment to see how well its beer would sell in plastic bottles. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement Tuesday, the company siad it was suspending the  
tests because of ``limited consumer interest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The test marketing began about the middle of March, with  
Budweiser and Bud Light being sold in 16-ounce plastic bottles in 
convenience stores in Dallas and Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	Anheuser-Busch had viewed the plastic bottles as a potential  
alternative to the traditional aluminum can or glass bottle. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, the nation's No. 2 brewer, started selling beer in  
plastic bottles in some markets in October. 
</P>
<P>
	Beer in plastic bottles has been available in Europe and  
Australia for years. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
