<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Party Seeks India Comeback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- The long-dominant Congress Party was  
confident Tuesday of staging its comeback to power, most likely as 
a minority government with little hope of a long life. 
</P>
<P>
	Party officials said Italian-born Sonia Gandhi would head the  
new administration. But key backers were voicing reservations about 
her, and it was not clear whether she would become prime minister 
or ask a party colleague to take the job. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gandhi, heir to India's foremost political dynasty, is the  
widow of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and daughter-in-law of Prime 
Minister Indira Gandhi, both of whom were assassinated. Indira's 
father was India's first prime minister, Jawaharlal Nehru. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bharatiya Janata Party, which led the government ousted  
Saturday in a vote of confidence, claimed it had enough support to 
block Congress. In that event, a new election would be almost 
certain. 
</P>
<P>
	Activity on forming a government was expected to be suspended  
until after parliament enacts the national budget early Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Arjun Singh, a senior Congress official, said the new  
administration would most likely be a minority government led by 
Sonia Gandhi because it ``would be easier to manage'' than an 
unwieldy coalition of divergent parties. 
</P>
<P>
	Party spokesman Ajit Jogi told The Associated Press on Tuesday  
that Congress would have letters of support from a majority of 
parliament to prove to President K.R. Narayanan it will be able to 
govern. The president must decide which party can form the next 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the president calls us tomorrow evening, we will  
immediately respond with all the letters,'' Jogi said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Congress legislators admitted the government was not likely  
to last the four years until the next scheduled election. Congress, 
which has governed India for 45 of its 51 years as an independent 
nation, can at best hope to garner support from 272 legislators, 
but that razor-edge majority would be difficult to maintain. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are still talking with all the leaders to evolve a  
consensus,'' Mrs. Gandhi said as she left a meeting with veteran 
communist leader Jyoti Basu. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry and business officials were awaiting the passage of the  
budget that pledged to step up the pace of free-market reforms, 
downsize government and raise taxes. The budget was seen as 
investor friendly, and there had been fears it could fall victim to 
politics after Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee was ousted. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock markets tumbled more than 250 points Saturday but revived  
after all political parties agreed to pass the budget unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gandhi has met almost every opposition leader, but most  
were reluctant to commit their support before she had enough 
backers to form a government. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am assuring you that there is no difficulty, no problem in  
forming an alternative government,'' said Arjun Singh. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, State Department spokesman James Rubin said the  
United States hopes the next Indian government will take concrete 
steps on a nuclear arms nonproliferation agreement and improvement 
of relations with neighboring Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said Washington had expressed regret at both India's and  
Pakistan's tests earlier this month of long-range nuclear capable 
missiles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
