<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	H.S. Shooting Death Toll May Be 25  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Two young men dressed in fatigues  
unleashed a barrage of gunfire in a suburban Denver high school 
today in what police say was a suicide mission that may have killed 
25 people. Jefferson County Sheriff John Stone said two suspects 
were found dead inside the library at Columbine High School. 
Students fled in spurts during the afternoon as police tried to 
secure the building. By early evening, officers had yet to remove 
any bodies because of the danger of explosives and the need to 
preserve evidence. FBI agents and police SWAT teams were slowly 
making their way through the building tonight. The dead suspects 
were found with devices that could be bombs, said a sheriff's 
spokesman. 

</P>
<P>
	Colo. Parents Search for Their Kids  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- In the chaotic aftermath of the nation's  
latest deadly school shooting today, students scrambled for safety 
and their parents endured an agonizing wait for news. Crying and 
shaking, some rescued students from Columbine High School were 
taken by bus to an elementary school, where some parents stood on 
fences, straining to try to see their children. Cries of ``There 
she is!'' or ``I don't see her!'' went up as the buses rolled to a 
stop. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovars Used As Human Shields  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO attacks continued today in  
Pristina as the alliance began investigating reports of Serbs using 
ethnic Albanians as human shields. Officials told reporters at NATO 
headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, that the alliance was looking 
into reports of 700 ethnic Albanian boys as young as 14 being used 
either as ``human shields or as blood banks for Serb casualties.'' 
Refugees also said as many as 700 men were used as human shields 
last week near the town of Orahovac. There was no independent 
confirmation of the report. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Going Without Pacific Carrier  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. military, stretched thin following a  
post-Cold War downsizing, is feeling the pinch because of dual 
defense needs in Kosovo and Iraq. No aircraft carrier is currently 
plying the Pacific. Instead, Air Force planes there have gone on 
alert for any trouble. The gap in carrier coverage for the Pacific 
could last until the fall, when the USS Constellation is to arrive, 
defense officials said. The USS Kitty Hawk that was in the Pacific 
was ordered to the Persian Gulf on April 3 to free up the USS 
Theodore Roosevelt to join the NATO airstrikes on Yugoslavia. The 
Roosevelt arrived in the Adriatic Sea on April 5. 

</P>
<P>
	Enforcement of Kid's Online Privacy  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The enforcement of a new law banning companies  
from collecting personal information from children on the Internet 
was detailed today by the government. The Federal Trade 
Commission's proposed rules would require operators of commercial 
Web sites to make ``reasonable efforts'' in most cases to obtain 
consent from parents before asking children under 13 for their 
names, addresses, telephone numbers or other identifying details. 

</P>
<P>
	Health Benefits of Vitamin C Touted  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Government researchers say the recommended daily  
allowance for vitamin C should be doubled or tripled because of 
increasing evidence over the past two decades of its 
cancer-fighting ability. In a paper in tomorrow's Journal of the 
American Medical Association, researchers from the National 
Institutes of Health said the RDA for vitamin C should be raised 
from 60 milligrams to between 100 mg and 200 mg. 

</P>
<P>
	Cigarette Billboards Coming Down  
</P>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Cigarette billboards that were once a  
celebrated part of the American landscape are coming down this week 
as part of the national settlement with the tobacco industry. In 
many places, the rugged Marlboro Man cowboy with the cigarette 
dangling from the corner of his mouth will yield to images of young 
children delivering anti-smoking messages. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Up 8.02; Nasdaq Gains  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks regained ground today after  
yesterday's slip, and the Dow ended the day up 8.02 to 10,448.55 
after yesterday's big loss. On the NYSE, decliners led advancers 
1,673-1,379. The Nasdaq was up 64.03 at 2,409.64. 

</P>
<P>
	Giant's Bonds Out 10 Weeks  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Barry Bonds had surgery on his throwing arm  
today and will be out of the San Francisco Giants' lineup for at 
least 2 1/2 months. The All-Star left fielder underwent an operation 
to repair a triceps tendon in his left arm and a bone spur in his 
elbow. Giants team physician Dr. Bill Montgomery said Bonds was 
expected to be released from the hospital today and fitted for a 
brace this week. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
