<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ney, Sanders Team on Seniors Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In an unusual political alliance, a Republican  
congressman from Ohio teamed Tuesday with one of the most liberal 
members of Congress to propose a significant change in Social 
Security law. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea: link Social Security cost-of-living adjustments, or  
COLAs, to the costs America's elderly actually face. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just think it is one of the most fair ways to be fair to  
senior citizens,'' said Rep. Bob Ney, R-Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	``All that Bob and I are trying to do is bring forth truth in  
COLAs,'' said Rep. Bernie Sanders, I-Vt. 
</P>
<P>
	Social Security benefits are adjusted yearly based on inflation  
as calculated by the Bureau of Labor Statistics. To determine 
inflation, the agency looks at a wide range of things people buy. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders and Ney are trying to convince their colleagues that the  
elderly tend to spend their money on such things as medicine and 
health care, while the COLA formula also considers such things as 
cellular phones and computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Cellular phone and computer prices have been falling, while  
health-care costs have been rising. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most senior citizens in Vermont are trying to pay their  
heating bill or buy the food they need. They do not have cellular 
phones,'' Sanders told a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation they are pushing would use for calculating  
Social Security's COLA an experimental version of the Consumer 
Price Index devised by the Bureau of Labor Statistics. Known as 
CPI-E, it calculated a 1.9 percent elderly cost-of-living increase 
for 1998, compared with 1.3 percent for the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	To an average retirement stipend, that would mean about an extra  
$44 a month. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders and Ney are a sort of political odd couple who usually  
do not agree on how the government should do its work. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, Americans for Democratic Action, a leading liberal  
organization, gave Sanders a perfect 100 percent score in 1998 for 
being completely in synch with its positions. ADA Ney a 15. 
</P>
<P>
	The reverse is true for the American Conservative Union, which  
gave Sanders an 8 and Ney an 80. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill was introduced with the endorsements of dozens of  
senior citizen groups and bipartisan co-sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Steve LaTourette, R-0hio, said he endorsed the bill because  
it makes sense to segregate older people's living costs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The consumer price index is determined largely by snooping  
into consumers' shopping carts, and what's in the cart matters,'' 
said LaTourette. ``Some carts have more Metamucil than Mountain Dew 
and more Geritol than Gummi Bears.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
