<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO's 50th Turning Into War Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- NATO is remaking its 50th anniversary  
celebration into a war council, with Western leaders preparing to 
impose new sanctions such as an oil embargo to force Yugoslavia to 
stop its aggression in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our alliance consensus is rock solid,'' Secretary of State  
Madeleine Albright said Tuesday, ``and NATO operations will 
continue until this crisis ends on just and durable terms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders of more than 40 nations will hold a three-day summit  
starting Friday to mark the success of the alliance formed a 
half-century ago to protect Western Europe against Soviet invasion. 
With that threat removed, the leaders will commit themselves to 
combating new challenges, such as terrorism and the spread of 
weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
<P>
	With presidents and prime ministers from NATO's 19 member  
countries and officials of two dozen countries affiliated with the 
Partnership for Peace, it will be the largest gathering of heads of 
state in Washington's history. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is going to be a working meeting of a military alliance  
in the middle of the conflict,'' said Sandy Berger, President 
Clinton's national security adviser. Russia, angry about NATO 
airstrikes against Serbia, has not said whether it will send a 
representative. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the hope for a free and united Europe ``will not  
succeed unless it embraces a partnership with democratic Russia. 
And it will not succeed unless it is embraced by Russia. That is 
the kind of alliance that must and will emerge from the Washington 
summit.'' He spoke at a ceremony in the East Room as he presented 
the Medal of Freedom, the nation's highest civilian honor, to 
former German Chancellor Helmut Kohl. 
</P>
<P>
	At a White House briefing on the summit, Defense Secretary  
William Cohen said NATO was not reassessing its decision against 
using ground troops in Kosovo. However, he said, ``It could be done 
very quickly'' if the leaders change course. 
</P>
<P>
	The summit will open Friday morning with a three-hour leaders'  
meeting on Kosovo. To demonstrate NATO's resolve, the alliance will 
underscore its insistence on the withdrawal of Serbian troops from 
Kosovo, the return of hundreds of thousands of displaced people and 
the deployment of an international security force, Albright said. 
</P>
<P>
	Berger said the summit would send ``a signal that the military,  
economic and political pressure on Belgrade will intensify'' until 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic accedes to NATO's terms. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will consider new economic measures designed to deny  
Belgrade the ability to wage war on its own people, such as an 
embargo on oil products,'' Albright said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, some allies are said to be reluctant to impose a naval  
blockade. Cohen said NATO officials were discussing how to deny 
Milosevic a resupply of fuel and energy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think all understand that his resupply of fuel has to be  
stopped and we will take measures to achieve that,'' Cohen said. 
``Acting collectively, we will do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen denied that the allies miscalculated how long it would  
take to stop Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had planned for a phased air campaign for however long was  
necessary,'' he said. ``There was never any time limit put on it. 
There was never any limitation saying it will be over by the 
summit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Albright said the allies also will discuss reconstruction aid  
for the Balkans, humanitarian assistance for refugees and 
information about alleged atrocities that will be referred to a war 
crimes tribunal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 14:55:02 </DATE_TIME>
