<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Golf Notes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	One of the most important clubs in Jose Maria Olazabal's bag  
when he won the Masters was so new that MacGregor didn't even have 
time to stamp its name on it. 
</P>
<P>
	Olazabal got a custom-made sand wedge during the BellSouth  
Classic the week before in Atlanta, where he missed the cut. The 
33-year-old Spaniard doesn't like to change equipment, but this was 
different. 
</P>
<P>
	``As soon as I put my hands on it, it went straight in the  
bag,'' Olazabal said during a conference call from Spain. ``I liked 
how it came off the club. I had a lot of control with the ball. And 
I think you know how well I chipped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Olazabal was 4-of-6 in saving par from around the green during  
the Masters. His best save Sunday was on the par-3 12th from the 
back bunker, one of the most daunting shots at Augusta National 
because the green slopes toward Rae's Creek. 
</P>
<P>
	While everyone else in contention left it on the top fringe,  
Olazabal blasted out to within 2 feet to make par. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know you're going to miss greens, so chipping and putting  
is going to be very important,'' he said. ``That sand wedge was 
very important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That sand wedge now has a name. MacGregor plans to call it the  
``Commemorative 1999 Masters'' edition. 
</P>
<P>
	Augusta National asks all of its champions to donate one club  
for its trophy room. Will Olazabal send his sand wedge? 
</P>
<P>
	``No way,'' he said. ``I'm going to keep my hands on this  
one.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CROSS-HANDED LOPEZ:* Nancy Lopez has become obsessed with  
improving her putting. The latest effort is a cross-handed grip. 
</P>
<P>
	Lopez putted her left-hand low for the first time in competition  
Sunday in The Village Charity Classic. She finished last behind 
Helen Alfredsson and Juli Inkster, but felt good about her stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	``My putting was much more solid,'' she said. ``Today was a good  
test.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lopez believes putting is what has kept her from winning the  
past few years. In January, she reviewed videotape of her 1978 
season and noticed she gave her putts a hard, long look before 
pulling the trigger. When she's home in Georgia, she works almost 
exclusively with the flat stick. 
</P>
<P>
	She got the idea to go cross-handed from her husband last week  
when they played Old Waverly, site of the U.S. Women's Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was rolling the ball much more direct and I was not breaking  
down my left wrist,'' Lopez said. ``I did miss some putts, but it's 
just a matter of practicing and gaining confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SPANISH CELEBRATION:* With only three of the top 20 in the  
Greater Greensboro Classic, much of the attention will be in Spain 
this week for two reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Maria Olazabal will be playing for the Peugeot Open for the  
first time since winning the Masters, and Sergio Garcia will be 
making his professional debut. 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia, the 19-year-old British Amateur champion known as ``El  
Nino,'' was the first European to be low amateur at Augusta 
National. While that doesn't guarantee success as a pro, he has a 
lot more going for him than Justin Rose, the English teen-ager who 
turned pro after tying for fourth in the British Open. Rose has not 
made a professional cut in 18 tries. 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia has played 30 professional events in the past six years.  
He made 12 of 13 cuts last year, and has a 37-2 record in match 
play since 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are delighted to welcome Sergio,'' said Ken Schofield,  
executive director of the European tour. ``We've followed his 
progress ever since he made the cut at the Mediterranean Open at 
the age of 14.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LPGA SPONSOR:* The impact of the World Golf Championship may  
have trickled down to the LPGA Tour. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sarazen World Open, usually played after the Tour  
Championship, no longer exists because of the $5 million Stroke 
Play Championship that will be held that same week at Valderrama. 
</P>
<P>
	How does that benefit the LPGA?  
</P>
<P>
	Subaru of America, the title sponsor of the Sarazen Open the  
past two years, signed a two-year deal to become title sponsor of 
the Naples LPGA Memorial in January. It also announced endorsement 
deals with Juli Inkster and Meg Mallon. 
</P>
<P>
	``Subaru has created some very unique partnerships that focus on  
the growing area of women's sports,'' said Subaru president George 
Muller. ``We're extremely excited about the opportunity to develop 
a strong relationship with the LPGA.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So is LPGA commissioner Ty Votaw. Along with Naples, the Boston  
Classic in August is expected to announce a new title sponsorship 
agreement Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DIVOTS:* During the LPGA Championship media day, children from  
the LPGA Urban Youth Program in Wilmington, Del., greeted defending 
champion Se Ri Pak in her native Korean. ... Tiger Woods will make 
his first trip to Taiwan in November as defending champion of the 
Johnnie Walker Classic. Woods won in February in Thailand, beating 
Ernie Els in a playoff. This year's tournament has been pushed to 
Nov. 11-14 and will be the first leg of the 2000 European tour. ... 
Tickets to the Walker Cup at Nairn, Scotland in September are being 
limited to 7,500 per day. ....After another close call in the 
Masters, followed by a letdown in the MCI Classic, Greg Norman is 
taking off the next six weeks. He won't show up again on the PGA 
Tour until the Memorial Tournament, two weeks before the U.S. Open. 
... Mark O'Meara went to Wayne Gretzky's final game and gave him a 
pair of golf shoes. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MONEY MATTERS:* Andrew Magee is 22nd on the money list with  
$585,422. Take out his runner-up finish in the Match Play 
Championship and he has earned $85,422 in eight events. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *STAT OF THE WEEK:* Payne Stewart took only 95 putts last week  
in the MCI Classic, third-lowest in tour history. Kenny Knox had 93 
putts in 1989 and Bob Tway needed only 94 putts in 1986 -- both on 
the small greens of Harbour Town. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FINAL WORD:* ``I haven't finished in the top 10 once in six  
starts, which is unacceptable for someone of my level.'' -- Colin 
Montgomerie, on his play in America this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
