Gold(final) -    $284.40    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Profits Jump 43 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft Corp.'s quarterly profit jumped 43  
percent from a year earlier on strength across its range of 
products, particularly its Office business software and Windows NT 
software for running corporate computers. Microsoft reported it 
earned $1.92 billion, or 35 cents a share in its fiscal third 
quarter, which ended March 31. The results beat Wall Street 
expectations. Revenue rose to $4.33 billion from $3.77 billiion. 
Not included in the third-quarter results is $400 million in 
revenue from early sales of Microsoft's new Office 2000 package of 
business software, which Microsoft said it would defer into the 
current quarter. Microsoft shares rose today 2 1/8 to 83 1/8. Earnings 
were released after the bell. 
</P>
<P>
	Chase, Mellon Banks Post Profits  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Four major U.S. banks posted strong  
first-quarter profits today, capping a double-digit increase for 
the industry. Chase Manhattan Bank, Wells Fargo and Mellon Bank all 
reported earnings that topped Wall Street's expectations, while 
Bank One's results matched estimates. Chase Manhattan Corp, the 
nation's third-largest bank, reported profits of $1.17 billion, 
beating Wall Street's estimate; Bank One Corp., the country's No. 4 
bank, posted earnings of $995 million, up 6.6 percent. Wells Fargo 
&AMP; Co. posted profits of $884 million, a 29 percent jump. Mellon 
Bank earned $231 million, compared with $206 million last year. 
Chase stock was down 2 at 83; Wells Fargo was up 1 1/8 at 42 1/4; Mellon 
was 1/16 lower at 70 15/16; and Bank One was down 7/16 at 58 13/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Drug Companies Post Strong Earnings  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Pharmaceutical companies reported today  
generally strong first-quarter earnings, with Johnson &AMP; Johnson and 
SmithKline Beecham PLC beating Wall Street forecasts. Johnson &AMP; 
Johnson's first-quarter profit rose 11.7 percent, driven by strong 
drug and medical device sales. Schering-Plough Corp.'s first 
quarter profit rose 20 percent, mainly from accelerating sales of 
Claritin, the world's best-selling antihistamine. American Home 
Products Corp.'s first quarter profit was flat mostly due to weak 
sales of herbicides; SmithKline Beecham PLC's first-quarter profit 
rose 15 percent from strong growth of the company's antibiotic and 
depression and anti-smoking drugs. Johnson &AMP; Johnson shares were up 
6 at 96 1/4; Schering-Plough was up 1 7/8 at 50 3/8; and American Home was 
up 2 9/16 at 62 5/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Airlines Report Earnings  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A pilot sickout at American Airlines helped lift  
earnings at competing U.S. carriers in the first quarter, but bad 
winter weather caused scheduling problems that offset some of the 
gains. Earnings at United Airlines parent UAL Corp. fell but still 
beat Wall Street's expectations; Northwest Airlines narrowed its 
losses; America West's earnings inched higher and discount carrier 
Southwest had a 37 percent surge in profits. UAL shares were down 4 
at 79 3/4; Northwest was up 9/16 at 31; America West was down 3/16 at 
20 13/16; and Southwest was down 7/16 at 32 1/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris Shipments Fall  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Philip Morris Cos. Inc.'s underlying profit  
barely improved in the first quarter as cigarette shipments skidded 
following last fall's price hikes. The world's biggest tobacco 
maker held up better than the industry, however, and extended its 
commanding share of the U.S. cigarette market. Its underlying 
income, excluding one-time-only charges, was up 1.4 percent to $2.0 
billion, or 80 cents a share, in the three months ended March 31, 
from $1.93 billion, or 79 cents a share, a year ago. The results 
were slightly ahead of Wall Street expectations. Philip Morris 
stock was up 1 1/8 at 34 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
	Telecom Italia Supports Merger  
</P>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Telecom Italia SpA's board of directors agreed in  
principle to a merger with Germany's Deutsche Telekom AG, but 
several major issues still must be resolved. Following a seven-hour 
board meeting, Telecom Italia released a statement saying it 
supports a ``business combination agreement'' under which a new 
company would be set up to combine the two companies. A combined 
Telecom Italia and Deutsche Telekom would dwarf its competitors in 
Europe and would most likely become the largest merger in history, 
topping the pending $74 billion deal between Exxon Corp. and Mobil 
Corp. 

