discussing plans to join Long-Term Capital Management, the 
Connecticut investment fund that nearly collapsed last summer and 
threatened global financial markets. Corzine, who will leave 
Goldman Sachs after the investment bank goes public next month, 
helped spearhead the consortium of 14 banks that bailed out 
Long-Term Capital Management to the tune of $3.63 billion. 
Long-Term Capital Management has recovered much of its ground over 
the past six months. 

