</P>
<P>
	CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) -- Apple Computer Inc., seeking to  
strengthen its position in the delivery of audio and video files 
over the Internet, has introduced a new version of its QuickTime 
software. QuickTime 4 software, unlike its predecessor QuickTime 3, 
allows for the ``streaming'' of live video and audio events over 
the Internet. Apple's upgrade of QuickTime is seen as a challenge 
to rivals Microsoft Corp. and RealNetworks Inc. QuickTime 4, 
available as a free ``public beta'' version, also includes support 
for the MP3 digital-music format. 

