<HEADLINE> United Technologies Profits Jump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- United Technologies Corp. reported its  
first-quarter profits climbed 18 percent, boosted by growth at its 
Pratt &AMP; Whitney jet engine division and its building businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also announced Tuesday that job cuts are expected in  
the second and third quarter due to restructuring charges related 
to previously-announced plans to sell the UT Automotive division. 
Spokesman Peter Murphy said the company does not yet know how large 
the restructuring charges will be or how many workers will lose 
their jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The plans are being developed now and we won't know the answer  
to that question until they're finished,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Net income for the quarter was $308 million, or $1.25 per share,  
compared with $260 million, or $1.04 per share, in the first 
quarter a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues increased 3 percent to $5.44 billion, up from $5.31  
billion a year ago. The figures exclude the company's automotive 
segment, which has been classified as a discontinued operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Pratt &AMP; Whitney's operating profit increased more than 20  
percent on 9 percent revenue growth, due to higher military engine 
shipments and growth in the overhaul and repair business. The 
results exclude a government contract settlement gain in the first 
quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Carrier air conditioning unit, operating profit increased  
15 percent on 1 percent revenue growth, reflecting contributions 
from recent acquisitions and improved cost controls. The results 
exclude restructuring charges in the first quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	At Otis elevators, operating profit increased 58 percent on a 3  
percent revenue gain. Otis also took significant restructuring 
charges in the first quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Flight Systems unit, operating profit fell 38 percent on  
a 10 percent revenue decline, due to lower helicopter shipments and 
restructuring at the Sikorsky division. 
</P>
<P>
	AT UT Automotive, operating profit declined 4 percent on an 11  
percent increase in revenues. UTC announced last month that it is 
selling UT Automotive to Lear Corp. for $2.3 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of United Technologies fell $3.06 1/4 to $141.93 3/4 in trading  
on the New York Stock Exchange. 


</P>
</TEXT>
