<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sanyo To Cut 6,000 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese electronics maker Sanyo Electric Co. will  
slash 6,000 jobs -- nearly 11 percent of its work force -- over the 
next three years in a major restructuring drive. 
</P>
<P>
	The cuts, which will reduce Sanyo's work force to 49,000 from  
the current 55,000, aim to help the company bring down costs and 
boost profitability amid a slump in the electronics industry, 
spokeswoman Yumiko Yagata said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanyo estimates it posted a consolidated pretax loss of about 15  
billion yen, or $127 million, in fiscal 1998 which ended March 31. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement comes as many major Japanese corporations are  
forced to scuttle traditional business practices like lifetime 
employment in order to cope with Japan's worst recession in 
decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, Hitachi Ltd., Japan's largest machinery  
manufacturer, said it would cut 6,500 jobs by March 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Work force reductions have also been announced recently by  
Mitsubishi Electric Corp., NEC Corp. and Sony Corp., three of 
Japan's biggest electronics companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanyo's jobs cuts will be accomplished mainly by job freezes,  
early retirement and transfers of employees to non-group 
affiliates, Yagata said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
