<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wright Brothers Flight To Be Marked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTON, Ohio (AP) -- John Glenn says there's one word to describe  
what's happened to aviation since the Wright brothers' first flight 
nearly 100 years ago -- ``amazing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Now you can go down and buy a ticket to go anywhere in the  
world and your biggest worries are whether you're going to have a 
window seat and whether the food's going to be hot and suit your 
palate and whether your baggage is going to get lost,'' Glenn said. 
</P>
<P>
	The astronaut and former senator spoke at a ceremony Monday at  
the United States Air Force Museum to begin the countdown to the 
100th anniversary of the first flight. 
</P>
<P>
	Glenn was named secretary general of the 2003 celebration.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is going to be the biggest celebration anywhere in the  
world, I think, of any commemorative type nature in the year 2003 
because the impact that aviation has had on every single nation in 
the world,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilkinson Wright, great nephew of the Wright brothers and family  
spokesman, said it is not too soon to begin planning the 
celebration. He said Dayton residents already are starting to get 
excited. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a very good feeling about it,'' said Wright. ``They're  
beginning to get the idea this is something big and important for 
the Dayton area. For the first time we're going to have a lot of 
highly visible things going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Orville and Wilbur Wright designed and built their cloth and  
wood airplane in Dayton and took it to Kill Devil Hills, N.C., 
because of the area's giant dunes, soft sand and strong wind. 
</P>
<P>
	On Dec. 17, 1903, their 750-pound aircraft carried Wilbur Wright  
aloft for 12 seconds over nearby Kitty Hawk. It was the first time 
in history that a machine lifted a man into the air in full flight 
under its own power. 
</P>
<P>
	``The achievement of their simple yet astonishing goal has  
changed the world and with it our view of ourselves and our 
universe in ways they could not have imagined,'' said Brad Tillson, 
chair of the organizing committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Tillson said the celebration will include a special air show in  
2003 and an annual international arts festival tied, in part, to 
the Wright brothers. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers have said the celebration will cost up to $20 million  
and require the same sort of marketing as that done to draw the 
Olympics to a city. They predict the series of events will draw 3 
million visitors. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
