<HEADLINE> Angels Say There's No Jinx </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- The Anaheim Angels insist centerfielder Jim  
Edmonds isn't the victim of a team jinx, despite evidence to the 
contrary. 
</P>
<P>
	The Angels, who have had a rash of injuries in recent years,  
learned Monday they will be without Edmonds for about four months 
due to a severely injured right (non-throwing) shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Edmonds, who won his second straight Gold Glove last season and  
has averaged nearly 28 homers over the last four years, will 
undergo arthroscopic surgery Thursday to repair a torn labrum. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never get used to it but you learn to deal with it and  
move on,'' outfielder Garret Anderson said. 
</P>
<P>
	With nine players on the disabled list, Angels manager Terry  
Collins said he's no longer surprised when a player is hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I had a theory about why we've been injured so much I'd  
have an idea how to stop it,'' Collins said. ``But I don't, it's 
just been freaky injuries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the start of spring training, shortstop Gary DiSarcina broke  
his left forearm in a fluke accident. He was hit by a fungo bat 
swung by coach George Hendrick. 
</P>
<P>
	DiSarcina, who hit .287 and drove in 56 runs last season, is  
expected to miss the first three or four months of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Later in the spring, pitcher Jason Dickson felt tenderness in  
his right shoulder. It turned out he has a torn labrum and could 
miss the season. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first inning of his first game with the team on April 5,  
Mo Vaughn, who signed an $80 million, six-year contract with the 
Angels last November, sprained his ankle. 
</P>
<P>
	Vaughn is expected to be activated and back in the lineup on  
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no jinx. Things just happen, and I'll be damned if we  
let it become an excuse,'' said Vaughn, who feels the Angels have 
played well despite the injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we played poorly, I would feel worse, but we've kept our  
heads above water,'' Vaughn said. ``Guys have really stepped up and 
filled the gaps where we needed them to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chief among them has been Todd Greene, who has seen his playing  
time increase at DH because of the injuries. Greene has four homers 
and 15 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's doing one hell of job right now, so it's been a plus for  
us,'' said pitcher Jack McDowell, who is recovering from right 
shoulder surgery. ``We have enough talent to get by until people 
get back.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
