<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Montana Pollution Case Settled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREAT FALLS, Mont. (AP) -- A federal judge has approved a $260  
million settlement between the state of Montana and Atlantic 
Richfield Co., ending 16 years of court battles. 
</P>
<P>
	The case involves 100 years of pollution in the Upper Clark Fork  
River Basin from mining and smelter operations. Arco inherited the 
problems in the 1970s, when it acquired the Anaconda Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The 130-mile-long stretch from the headwaters of the Clark Fork  
River has been designated the largest Superfund cleanup site in the 
nation by the Environmental Protection Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is good to finally be at this point,'' said Montana  
Attorney General Joe Mazurek, who helped negotiate the deal struck 
last June. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Paul Hatfield approved the settlement Monday  
by signing two consent decrees. The decrees involve the state and 
federal government, the Confederated Salish and Kootenai Tribes and 
Arco. 
</P>
<P>
	Montana initiated the suit in 1983, seeking $765 million to  
restore the river basin to its condition before settlers began 
digging for gold, silver and copper in Butte. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement includes $215 million plus interest that has been  
accruing since April 1998. Besides state government's sum, the 
settlement includes $18.3 million for the tribes and about $26.7 
million for various federal agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazurek said Arco already has paid the state $30 million,  
including $15 million to cover the state's legal costs. The other 
$15 million payment is the first installment for the cleanup of 
Silver Bow Creek, headwaters of the Clark Fork River. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, the lawsuit secured $80 million for the state to clean  
up the creek. The rest of the state's share, about $118 million 
plus interest, will be put into a trust. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
