<DOCNO> APW19990420.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 16:14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schott Agrees To Sell Share of Reds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Marge Schott agreed Tuesday to sell control of  
the Cincinnati Reds for $67 million, leaving her one step away from 
the end of her tumultuous 15-year reign. 
</P>
<P>
	The other major league owners have to approve the sale to  
Cincinnati financier Carl Lindner and two of the other limited 
partners, a process that usually takes 6-15 months but is expected 
to move quickly, perhaps with a vote as soon as June. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball had ordered her to sell her controlling interest in the  
Reds and end a tenure that included one suspension for inflammatory 
remarks and other disciplinary measures, such as giving up 
day-to-day decision-making. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindner would become the team's controlling partner. Limited  
partners George Strike and William Reik also would be part of the 
new ownership group. 
</P>
<P>
	``Carl Lindner, George Strike and Bill Reik have been excellent  
limited partners in the current partnership,'' NL president Len 
Coleman said. ``I think with their leadership, once the background 
work is done, the fans in Cincinnati will be blessed with a bright 
future for baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the sale is approved, it would mark a dramatic change for the  
Reds. Lindner owns the Great American Insurance Co. and is a 
behind-the-scenes executive like the Reds' owners before Schott, 
who became a limited partner in 1981 and the general partner in 
December 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	His style will be much different than Schott's -- no dogs on the  
field, few interviews with reporters. He plans to keep John Allen 
as managing executive and Jim Bowden as general manager. 
</P>
<P>
	``All great organizations have great ownership and great  
leadership,'' Bowden said. ``Obviously, Mr. Lindner and the limited 
partners have first-class character and run first-class 
organizations. I think it's a great day for Cincinnati Reds 
baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was a built-in pressure on Schott to sell -- her  
partnership agreement expired at the end of 2000, when the limited 
partners were prepared to oust her. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball suspended her for one year in February 1993 and fined  
her $25,000 for language the sport's executive council judged 
``racially and ethnically offensive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She returned early the following April, but after additional  
remarks brought unfavorable attention she agreed in June 1996 to 
give up control of the team's day-to-day operations through 1998. 
Last October, baseball said she would sell the team and not return 
to daily control. 
</P>
<P>
	The three limited partners also sued her last week, contending  
she was ignoring their right to buy the team by matching a $65 
million offer from Larry Dolan, the brother of Cablevision Systems 
Corp.'s chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been a difficult time for Mrs. Schott,'' said her  
lawyer, Frank Kelley. ``To own a major league team and not be able 
to run it has been heart-rending. She did not want to sell her 
interest, which has been such an important part of her life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schott, 70, owns 6 1/2 of the 15 shares in the team's partnership,  
including the shares that make her the general partner. She agreed 
to sell all but one share to Lindner's group. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, in which 36.6 percent of the Reds' shares would change  
hands, values the franchise at about $182 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Although details weren't disclosed, a source familiar with the  
terms said Schott would keep an office in the stadium, a luxury 
suite and a block of lower-level seats. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the terms must be approved by major league baseball,  
which doesn't want Schott keeping a high profile and will probably 
prevent her from having an office. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Schott's tenure, the Reds won a World Series in 1990 but  
later began feeling the effects of her decision to decimate the 
farm system to save money. 
</P>
<P>
	Since she agreed to sell the team last November rather than face  
another suspension from baseball, the club's front office has been 
limited by the uncertainty. Lindner is expected to keep the front 
office intact as the team prepares for a new stadium in 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got confidence in club management, which should make  
things smoother,'' manager Jack McKeon said. ``A big key is his 
confidence in John and Jim. That should help keep continuity there 
and take a burden off everybody's back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lindner couldn't make any changes in the club until he gets  
baseball's approval. Players hope he'll put more money into the 
organization in the short term to speed up the rebuilding. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's still very early in the process,'' Allen said. ``We'll  
have to wait and see if there's any major changes in direction. 
Over the last three years, our focus has turned to player 
development and I wouldn't expect to see a change in that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds went from having the second-largest payroll in the  
National League in 1995 -- their last time in the playoffs -- to the 
fourth-smallest on opening day 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great if the people who take over the team are interested  
in restoring what once was here, such as getting some good players 
in here,'' team captain Barry Larkin said. ``What's important is 
what happens on the field.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
