</P>
<P>
	``I started to push hard, but after 20 miles, I started to get  
blisters on my feet and slowed down,'' said Guerra, who was seeking 
to become the first South American winner since Colombia's Elviro 
Mejia in 1971. 
</P>
<P>
	That just wasn't going to happen.  
</P>
<P>
	Not with Kenyans running, even though one of them, defending  
champion Moses Tanui, dropped out near the 23-mile mark, apparently 
with leg cramps. 
</P>
<P>
	Guerra finished second at 2:10:18 and was followed by two South  
Africans -- Frank Pooe at 2:11:37 and Abner Chipu at 2:12:45. 
Kenya's John Kagwe, who beat Chebet at New York in 1997 and 1998, 
wound up fifth for the second straight year at 2:13:57. The top 
American finisher, Joe LeMay of Danbury, Conn., was 13th in 
2:16:11. 
</P>
<P>
	The only other streak of nine winners from one country came when  
Americans won from 1916 through 1925 with few foreigners in the 
field. There was no individual competition in 1918, only a team 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the Kenyans are dominant.  
</P>
<P>
	``They have the best professional distance runners in the  
world,'' Rodgers said before the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Chebet is one of them.  
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody in the world is trying to catch the Kenyans,''  
Chebet said, ``but they can't.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
