<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Child Health Program Taking Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A $24 billion program to provide health  
insurance for children in working poor families enrolled nearly 1 
million kids during its inaugural year, and government officials 
said Tuesday they expect to more than double that by the end of 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	States expect to cover about 2.5 million of the nation's 11  
million uninsured children by the time the program is fully 
implemented in October 2000, the Department of Health and Human 
Services said. 
</P>
<P>
	That's close to the 2.3 million children estimated by the  
Congressional Budget Office in 1997 when the bill was approved as 
part of a massive budget deal but far short of the 5 million 
children that President Clinton and others hoped the program would 
reach. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, only about 3 million children are eligible for the  
program. But the administration hopes that some of an estimated 4 
million kids who are eligible for Medicaid but not enrolled will be 
found as states sign children up for the new kids' health program. 
</P>
<P>
	When the program was created, the nation had 10 million  
uninsured children. Since then, the number has grown to 11 million, 
and many fear it will grow more as families leave welfare and don't 
realize that children often remain eligible for health coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement Tuesday was the first time the government gave  
actual enrollment numbers for the program, the largest 
administration health initiative to become law, and administration 
officials celebrated their success. 
</P>
<P>
	``Almost 1 million more children in America have insurance,''  
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton announced in a health care speech 
at Hofstra University in Hempstead, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the best things about this job is knowing that we can  
really make a difference in the lives of working families,'' said 
HHS Secretary Donna Shalala. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mrs. Clinton noted that some states have made more progress  
than others in finding children who need insurance and qualify for 
the new program. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of creativity, but there's a long way to go,''  
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The program provides health insurance to children whose families  
are not poor enough to qualify for the traditional Medicaid program 
but cannot afford to buy coverage on their own. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to find these children, the federal government is working  
with the states and private groups to simplify the enrollment 
process for Medicaid and for the new program. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, there were 43 states and U.S. territories operating  
children's health programs. They had their choice between creating 
programs or expanding Medicaid. Last year, about 540,000 children 
were in state programs and 442,000 children were in Medicaid 
expansions. 
</P>
<P>
	The slow start has meant that states spent just $500 million  
last year -- less than one-eighth of the $4.3 billion allocated. And 
in 1999, the Congressional Budget Office projects that states will 
spend just $1 billion of the $4.3 billion available. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Peacock, an HHS spokesman, said the program's slow start  
should come as no surprise. The average program has been in 
operation for only about six months, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the beginning of this very historic, very progressive  
program,'' he said. ``Some states are just beginning to implement 
their programs.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
