<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Goldman Sachs Exec Eyes Hedge Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jon Corzine, co-chairman of Goldman Sachs, is  
discussing plans to join Long-Term Capital Management, the 
Connecticut investment fund that nearly collapsed last summer and 
threatened global financial markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Corzine, who will leave Goldman Sachs after the investment bank  
goes public next month, helped spearhead the consortium of 14 banks 
that bailed out Long-Term Capital Management to the tune of $3.63 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Corzine may try to raise money from other investors to  
repay the loans from the banks, according to a person familiar with 
the plans. All of the discussions are in the early stages and may 
come to naught. 
</P>
<P>
	A call to Corzine's office was not immediately returned.  
</P>
<P>
	The consortium of banks put out a press release Tuesday saying  
they have a ``policy not to comment on market speculation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Long-Term Capital Management, founded by John Meriwether, has  
recovered much of its ground over the past six months. The fund's 
risk has decreased by about half, while returns are up more than 20 
percent. The banks, which include Goldman Sachs, Merrill Lynch and 
J.P. Morgan, are expecting to be repaid in the second half of the 
year. 

</P>
</TEXT>
