<DOCNO> APW19990420.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 08:55:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Many Ignore Closed-End Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- They're holding a 5-percent-off sale at the  
mutual fund store, but not many investors are showing up to shop. 
</P>
<P>
	The markdown can be found in the category of investment  
companies known as closed-end funds, a sort of oddball cousin to 
traditional open-end mutual funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Open-end fund sponsors stand ready at any time to buy and sell  
shares in direct transactions with the public, at a price 
determined by the net asset value of the fund's portfolio. By 
contrast, closed-end funds have a fixed amount of shares that trade 
in the stock market, just like the stocks of the companies in which 
they invest. 
</P>
<P>
	So buyers or sellers at any time may find that the going price  
stands either at premium (above) or discount (below) a fund's net 
asset value per share. This complicates matters, but it also 
sometimes creates interesting opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Closed-end funds seem to be the forgotten stepchild in the  
mutual fund world, a misunderstood investment option that can be 
quite successful,'' say analysts at the fund tracking firm of 
Wiesenberger in Rockville, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	``While nearly 10,000 options exist for investors in open-end  
funds, only about 500 are available in the closed-end fund 
universe,'' Wiesenberger says in a new report on the subject. ``One 
reason investors shy away from the closed-end fund option is the 
presence of the premium or discount.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This extra layer of complexity can narrow or widen at any time.  
At last tally by the research firm of Lipper Inc., the median level 
stood at a 4.8 percent discount (hence the ``5 percent off'' 
characterization). In other words, half of all closed-end funds 
showed discounts of greater than 4.8 percent, and the other half 
were trading at smaller discounts or premiums. 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes, the premium or discount on a given closed-end fund  
seems logical. For instance, most funds concentrating on single 
foreign countries or areas of the globe outside the United States 
have lately traded at substantial discounts, given that foreign 
markets in general have lagged behind Wall Street for the past five 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	A closed-end bond fund may trade consistently at some discount  
to its NAV simply because its expenses cut into the portfolio's 
yield before it is passed along to investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Conversely, a fund may trade at a premium if it owns exotic  
securities that are scarce or not easy to buy directly, especially 
if those securities are considered hot properties. 
</P>
<P>
	But on many occasions, the reasons for a premium or discount may  
be hard to figure out. A mysterious discount tends to put many 
would-be buyers off, no matter how attractive the resulting price, 
simply by creating the impression that the smart money knows 
something bad that just hasn't come to light yet. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiesenberger says its research shows that people brave enough to  
invest regularly in deeply discounted closed-end funds can make 
some good money -- but that the game gets very chancy and volatile 
at times. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if you aren't interested in anything this complicated, it  
pays to be aware of closed-end funds whenever you invest in mutual 
funds. 
</P>
<P>
	For instance, before you buy an open-ended bond fund at NAV, you  
might check to see if there is a closed-end fund with a similar 
portfolio that is trading at a discount big enough to offer you a 
better return (don't forget to factor trading costs into the 
equation). 
</P>
<P>
	That same principle applies in reverse: If you are attracted to  
a closed-end fund that is trading at a premium, ask yourself 
whether a piece of a similar portfolio could be bought at NAV 
through an open-end fund. 
</P>
<P>
	The newsletter Mutual Fund Forecaster in Deerfield Beach, Fla.,  
notes that plans have been filed to bring out a closed-end fund 
specializing in Internet stocks, LCM Internet Growth. 
</P>
<P>
	``If investors clamor to buy these shares, the premium could  
skyrocket,'' says the letter's editor-in-chief, Norman Fosback. 
``If so, we counsel avoiding it. Eventually, we expect to see LCM 
Internet Growth shrink to a discount below NAV. That could create 
an intriguing buying opportunity.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
