<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italian, German Telecoms Near Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Telecom Italia SpA and Germany's Deutsche Telekom  
AG are nearing a megadeal that would create a new global competitor 
to U.S. giants such as AT&AMP;T. 
</P>
<P>
	The move, pairing two former state monopolies, would be subject  
to intense regulatory scrutiny and would undoubtedly present the 
telecommunications companies with political and cultural obstacles. 
</P>
<P>
	A Telecom Italia-Deutsche Telekom combination would dwarf its  
competitors in Europe and would most likely become the largest 
merger in history, topping the pending $74 billion oil industry 
deal between Exxon Corp. and Mobil Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	A Telecom Italia official who spoke on condition of anonymity  
said the two firms' chief executives -- Franco Bernabe and Ron 
Sommer -- were to outline the merger agreement at a news conference 
today in London. 
</P>
<P>
	However, after separate board meetings Monday, the press  
conference was postponed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Telecom Italia official said today the complexity of the  
merger and the number of issues still to be settled led to the 
postponement. Telecom Italia's board will resume discussions later 
in the day, the official said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Financial Times reported today the main problem appeared to  
be over the structure of the merged company, with the German group 
demanding a 56 percent stake. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom spokesman Stephan Althoff on Monday declined to  
comment on reports that the two companies planned to fold their 
stock into a new telecommunications holding company on a 60-40 
percent basis. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian prime minister's office has said that any accord  
must be on an equal footing, underlining fears in Italy of foreign 
ownership of the strategic telecommunications industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom Italia may not be the only partner Deutsche Telecom is  
eyeing. The German business weekly Manager Magazin issued a news 
release Monday saying that Deutsche Telekom is also negotiating a 
takeover of U.S. telecommunications company Sprint Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a report to be published Friday in the magazine,  
Telekom boss Ron Sommer has been negotiating a deal with Sprint 
Corp.'s CEO William Esrey for several weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Althoff dismissed the story as ``just speculation.''  
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom has a market capitalization of about $117  
billion while Telecom Italia is at about $77 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Italian Premier Massimo D'Alema said Monday that any merger  
between Telecom Italia and Deutsche Telekom would require a 
privatization of the German company. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot imagine that a privatized Telecom Italia may merge  
with a company whose main shareholder is the German state,'' 
D'Alema told reporters. Deutsche Telecom is 72 percent-owned by the 
German government. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian government owns 3.4 percent of Telecom Italia, but  
it has veto power over the acquisition of more than 3 percent of 
the shares of the telecommunications company. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti has offered $12.31 a share for Telecom Italia. Olivetti  
plans to proceed with its tender offer despite the other merger 
talks, company spokesman Ugo Panerai said Monday. Olivetti has 
already filed a prospectus with the Italian regulatory body Consob. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
