<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Auto Franchises Spend $5.3B for Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The nation's franchised auto dealers bought a  
record $5.3 billion worth of advertising last year, a 4 percent 
increase over 1997 spending, the National Automobile Dealers 
Association reports. 
</P>
<P>
	More than half of that amount, $2.7 billion, went to newspapers.  
Radio and television each got less than $1 billion in local 
advertising, while direct mail outlets received $876 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Spending on other forms of advertising increased more than 77  
percent, primarily because of the increased attention to Internet 
ads, the association said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The association represents 19,500 franchised new-vehicle  
dealers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
