<DOCNO> APW19990420.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 16:14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers Try To Win Without Lindros </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Now taking the ice for the Stanley Cup  
playoffs: A team disguised as the Philadelphia Flyers. 
</P>
<P>
	Without Eric Lindros, it's hard to think of the Flyers any other  
way. 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers head into a first-round series against the Toronto  
Maple Leafs in the unfamiliar role of underdog. The reason for that 
is easy to pinpoint: Lindros is out with a collapsed lung, and his 
chances of playing again this season are slim. 
</P>
<P>
	Without him, the Flyers finished with a 3-1-1 record in their  
last five regular-season games to capture the fifth playoff seeding 
in the Eastern Conference. They still believe they have a chance 
against Toronto, a team they dominated in the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, they just don't seem like the Flyers without No. 88.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're only missing one guy now,'' forward Keith Jones said.  
``We can't make any excuses. It's laid on the table for us, our 
lines are set and I think we're all comfortable with what we have 
to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers, who begin the series in Toronto Thursday night, got  
a rare dose of good news on the injury front this week. Forward 
Mark Recchi, feared out for the first round with another head 
injury, was cleared to play against the Maple Leafs. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors determined that Recchi's most recent bout with headaches  
and dizziness was caused by migraines, not another concussion. 
Recchi returned to practice Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt fine out there,'' said Recchi, limited to eight games  
since the Flyers acquired him from Montreal to bolster their 
offense for the playoffs. ``Hopefully it won't happen again. But if 
I do get the numbness, I'll probably have to sit out that game. 
Obviously I'll be all right. I'll be able to bounce back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers were 3-1 against the Leafs this season, but that was  
with Lindros in the lineup. Philadelphia won the most recent 
meeting, 3-1 at Toronto as Lindros scored his 40th and, as it 
turned out, last goal of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros was injured in the same April 1 game at Nashville in  
which Recchi suffered his second head injury in three weeks. About 
12 pounds lighter from his ordeal, Lindros showed up at a couple of 
practices this week, but was unable to do anything more strenuous 
than glide around the ice. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our jobs have always been the same, whether he (Lindros) is in  
there or isn't in there,'' Rod Brind'Amour said. ``You still have 
to go out there and execute and do all the things right to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Recchi is likely to play on the Flyers' revamped top line with  
Brind'Amour and John LeClair. He doesn't plan to use his head for 
worrying. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to be an effective player in the playoffs if I  
play passive,'' Recchi said. ``I have to go out there and create 
things. Getting hit is part of the game and I can't worry about 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The series provides an intriguing matchup of goaltenders. With  
Curtis Joseph available last summer, the Flyers signed the older 
(35 vs. 32) and cheaper ($3.5 million vs. $6 million) John 
Vanbiesbrouck. Joseph signed with Toronto, getting the biggest 
contract among free-agent goalies. 
</P>
<P>
	The Beezer's 2.18 goals-against average was better than Joseph's  
2.56. Now, Vanbiesbrouck gets to prove that he was the better 
choice, not a second option. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is it a `Cujo against John' kind of thing?'' Vanbiesbrouck  
said. ``I don't think it is. There's more to this. We've got some 
great players, they've got some great players. There's going to be 
some magnificent play. Toronto's going to be a high-spirited, 
high-flying team.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
