<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM Boss' Pay Declines After Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. chairman Jack Smith was paid  
$3.2 million in salary, bonus and dividends last year, a 27 percent 
drop that partly reflected the automaker's strike-damaged financial 
performance. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Smith cashed in previously granted stock options  
worth $3.9 million, got another $1.6 million in stock under a 
long-term executive incentive plan, and was given an estimated $3.7 
million worth of stock options that he can exercise over the next 
decade. 
</P>
<P>
	The compensation figures for Smith and four other top GM  
executives are included in GM's annual proxy statement filed 
Tuesday with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, who also holds the title of chief executive, got a total  
compensation package worth an estimated $12.4 million, up 12 
percent from $11 million in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	By comparison, Alex Trotman, who retired Jan. 1 as chairman,  
president and CEO of Ford Motor Co., received a total compensation 
package worth $73 million last year, of which $14.9 million was in 
salary, bonus and dividends. Trotman's pay was inflated by the 
$30.1 million in stock options he exercised and $24.1 million worth 
of stock he received under Ford's long-term incentive plan. 
</P>
<P>
	The compensation totals can vary widely year to year based on  
the amount of previously granted stock options the executive 
decides to cash in and the extent to which the company's financial 
performance affects long-term incentive plan payouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Compensation for Smith and Trotman is determined in large part  
by formulas that consider how each automaker met financial and 
management goals for the year and, in the case of stock options, 
over several years. Last year, GM earned $3 billion, down 53 
percent from the $6.3 billion it earned in 1997. Ford's operating 
earnings increased 10 percent last year to $6.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith's $1.08 million bonus was down 56 percent from the $2.45  
million he received in 1997. But at the start of 1998, Smith was 
granted a raise in his salary to $1.95 million from the $1.75 
million he received the previous year. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
