<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Finish Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures rose sharply Tuesday  
on the Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts for rains that could delay 
spring plantings. 
</P>
<P>
        Corn and soybeans found the most support on continuing rains  
the Midwest, which have increasingly stalled fieldwork and could lead 
to smaller acreage planted and lower yields if the wet weather pattern 
holds. 
</P>
<P>
        Corn futures also were boosted after Russia announced it would  
buy 250,000 metric tons of U.S. corn, a purchase many linked to Clinton 
administration donations to that financially troubled country. 
</P>
<P>
        Soybeans also were supported by a lack of farmer selling out  
of Brazil and the United States, which boosted cash market prices. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat futures rose after the U.S. Agriculture Department reported  
Monday that winter wheat crop conditions had declined, although most 
of the gains came largely on the strength of the corn and soybean markets. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat for July delivery rose 5 3/4 cents to $2.69 a bushel;  
May corn rose 3 1/2 cents to $2.24 a bushel; May oats rose 3 1/4 cents 
to $1.24 a bushel; May soybeans rose 7 1/2 cents to $4.95 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
        Beef and lean hog futures rose strongly on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange as higher cash market prices signaled renewed domestic demand 
from slaughterhouses. Pork bellies retreated. 
</P>
<P>
        June live cattle rose .80 cent to 63.70 cents a pound; May  
feeder cattle rose .32 cent to 71.62 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
rose .75 cent to 55.97 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell .47 cent 
to 55.45 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
