<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Iowa 47' Families Mark Explosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORFOLK, Va. (AP) -- A former USS Iowa commander has criticized  
the Navy for not apologizing to relatives of the 47 sailors killed 
in an explosion on the battleship. 
</P>
<P>
	Retired Capt. Larry Seaquist said at a ceremony Monday marking  
the disaster's 10th anniversary that the Navy, which initially 
blamed one of the dead sailors for the blast, misled families about 
the nature of its investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	That made it difficult for relatives and shipmates of the dead  
men to come to grips with the tragedy because they feel 
``tarnished,'' Seaquist said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would have been very nice if the leadership of the Navy  
would have been here to say something simple to you, like `We 
apologize,''' Seaquist said in a speech at the Norfolk Naval Base 
ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the Iowa's skipper a year before the explosion.  
</P>
<P>
	Seaquist said afterward that he's mystified the Navy would  
``continue to miss the opportunity to do the right thing for the 
families and the crew.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Norfolk Naval Base spokesman Cmdr. Mike Andrews said, ``What  
Capt. Seaquist says is his opinion; that's his right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Andrews noted that Adm. Frank B. Kelso III, then the chief of  
naval operations, publicly apologized in 1991 to the family of 
Clayton Hartwig. Kelso said there was no proof to the Navy's 
initial claim that Hartwig, despondent over a homosexual affair, 
deliberately detonated gunpowder, killing himself and 46 shipmates. 
</P>
<P>
	Hartwig's sister, Kathy Hartwig-Kubicina of Cleveland, said she  
and other Iowa families were grateful to Seaquist for his remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	``All we've ever asked for is somebody to stick up for us,''  
Mrs. Hartwig-Kubicina said. The family's $12 million defamation 
suit against the Navy is pending in federal court in Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	The World War II-era warship was conducting exercises in the  
Caribbean on April 19, 1989, when an explosion ripped through a 
turret with 16-inch guns. 
</P>
<P>
	About 300 veterans and relatives of the victims attended  
Monday's ceremony at Iowa Point on the Navy base, the Iowa's home 
port until the ship was decommissioned in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Family members read poetry and bits of Scripture and talked  
about the men they lost. The names of all 47 crewmen were read 
aloud, and a bell was rung after each name. That was followed by a 
21-gun salute and the playing of taps as family members sobbed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
