<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airlines Report Improved Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A pilot sickout at American Airlines helped lift earnings at  
competing U.S. carriers in the first quarter, but bad winter 
weather caused scheduling problems that offset some of the gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings at United Airlines parent UAL Corp. fell but still beat  
Wall Street's expectations; Northwest Airlines narrowed its losses; 
America West's earnings inched higher and discount carrier 
Southwest had a 37 percent surge in profits. 

</P>
<P>
                             *UAL Corp.    	
</P>
<P>
	The parent company of United Airlines reported a decline in  
first-quarter earnings Tuesday as winter storms in January grounded 
planes. But the earnings still surpassed Wall Street expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Net income for the three months ended March 31 fell 14 percent  
to $187 million, or $1.54 a share, from $218 million, or $1.68 a 
share, the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings easily surpassed Wall Street expectations of $1.39  
a share, according to a survey of analysts by First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues rose 2.6 percent to $4.16 billion from $4.06 billion as  
the carrier filled more planes, especially in March. The carrier 
also benefited from an American Airlines pilots' sickout in 
February that drove passengers to competing carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Elk Grove Village, Ill.-based carrier reported its traffic  
in the Asian region improved on a year-over-year basis, reflecting 
some recovery in that region's economy. It was the first 
improvement since September 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite higher tickets costs instituted by most of the major  
carriers, United reported the amount of revenue it received from 
flying one passenger one mile fell 1.8 percent to 12.54 cents from 
12.77 cents as it paid higher costs to workers to improve on-time 
performance and higher salaries as a result of recent wage 
negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline said it was on track in the second quarter to match  
record earnings made in that year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the earnings beat expectations, UAL's stock fell $4  
or 4.8 percent to $79.75 on the New York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                      *Northwest Airlines Corp.    	
</P>
<P>
	Continued fallout from a 1998 pilot strike and other labor  
problems cost Northwest Airlines $90 million in the first quarter, 
resulting in a net loss of $46 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss for the three months ended March 31, which amounted to  
58 cents a share, compared with income of $71 million, or 66 cents 
a share, in the same period in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The figures do not reflect a one-time gain of $18 million from  
sale of securities. Including the gain, the quarterly loss was $29 
million, or 36 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest's per-share loss was smaller than the 75 cents  
expected by analysts, according to a survey by First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue fell 6 percent to $2.28 billion, from $2.43 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	``While we are dissatisfied with any loss, we are pleased with  
the pace of our recovery from last year's disruptions,'' said John 
Dasburg, president and chief executive. ``We expect to be 
profitable in the remaining three quarters of the year and for the 
full year of 1999.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to labor problems, severe weather in January and  
March also hurt Northwest's bottom line. 
</P>
<P>
	Eagan, Minn.-based Northwest still has not reached contract  
agreements with its largest labor groups, representing flight 
attendants, ground workers and mechanics. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's stock rose 56 1/4 cents or 1.8 percent to $31 on the  
Nasdaq Stock Market. 

</P>
<P>
 *America West Holdings Corp.    	
</P>
<P>
	The parent of America West Airlines reported a 3 percent gain in  
first-quarter profits Tuesday despite a March feud with flight 
attendants that took the company to the brink of a strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Phoenix-based America West, which also owns a vacation travel  
business, The Leisure Co., earned $26 million in the first three 
months of the year, up slightly from $25 million a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Thanks largely to a share repurchase program, per-share earnings  
posted a larger gain, increasing to 63 cents from 53 cents. The 
per-share earnings surpassed Wall Street expectations of 61 cents a 
share. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues rose 7.5 percent to $520 million from $483 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Late last month, America West officials said the impact of a  
threatened flight attendants strike was substantially offset by the 
pilots' sickout at American Airlines. The 10-day sickout led to 
increased bookings at America West and other airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	America West, which has hubs in Phoenix, Las Vegas and Columbus,  
Ohio, narrowly averted a strike by reaching a contract agreement 
with its flight attendants' union just hours after the flight 
attendants could have walked off the job. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's stock fell 18 3/4 cents to $20.81 1/4 on the New York  
Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Southwest Airlines Co.    	
</P>
<P>
	Southwest Airlines reported its first-quarter profit rose 37  
percent, led by strong passenger demand and lower jet fuel prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas-based discount carrier earned $95.8 million, or 27  
cents per share, in the three months ended March 31. That compared 
to $70 million, or 20 cents a share, in the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues rose 14 percent to $1.08 billion from $943 million.  
</P>
<P>
	The airline expects strong growth again in the second quarter,  
during which it will begin service to its 54th city, Raleigh, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's stock fell 43 3/4 cents to $32.06 1/4 on the New York  
Stock Exchange. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
