<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Israelis Remember War Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) --Traffic stopped and Israelis stepped out of  
their cars on streets and highways Tuesday to remember soldiers 
fallen in battle and countrymen killed in terror attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Sirens sounded across the country at 11 a.m., signaling the  
start of two minutes of silence on a day of mourning for fallen 
loved ones. 
</P>
<P>
	Flags flew at half-staff, and radio and television stations  
broadcast mournful songs and interviews with the families of men 
and women who lost their lives during compulsory military service. 
</P>
<P>
	``We come here to unite and remember,'' Prime Minister Benjamin  
Netanyahu said during a ceremony at Mt. Herzl National Cemetery in 
Jerusalem. 
</P>
<P>
	``No nation can assure its security, existence, or future if it  
does not have the inner preparedness to pay the heavy price in the 
struggle for national existence,'' Netanyahu said, wearing a black 
skullcap. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands left roses and carnations on Mt. Herzl's pink  
limestone graves, gleaming in brilliant sunshine. An elderly woman 
draped in a shawl stooped over a grave, sobbing. 
</P>
<P>
	Across town at the Cinematheque cafe, a young woman dressed in  
bright summer colors set down her orange juice and stood to gaze 
across the valley of Gehenna at the Old City walls -- the site of 
fierce battles in the 1967 and 1948 wars. She wept. 
</P>
<P>
	The mourning was marred by scuffles in the ultra-Orthodox  
Jerusalem neighborhood of Mea Shearim, where signs had been posted 
instructing residents to make a point of conducting their business 
throughout the siren. 
</P>
<P>
	The ultra-Orthodox regard such public displays as heathen icons  
and believe that mourning must come through the recitation of 
psalms and the study of religious texts. 
</P>
<P>
	Other ultra-Orthodox Jews stood at attention out of respect for  
secular Israelis, who constitute the bulk of military conscripts. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Israel remembers over 20,000 soldiers and fighters  
killed in battle since the start of Zionist settlement at the turn 
of the century. 
</P>
<P>
	The day was also marked in Macedonia at a field hospital set up  
by the Israeli army to attend to refugees from the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	The mood shifted abruptly in Israel at sundown Tuesday, when  
Israelis ushered in the country's 51st Independence Day with 
barbecues, parties and air shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip are barred from  
entering Israel over the two-day holiday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
