<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	25 May Be Dead in Colorado Shooting  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Two young men dressed in fatigues and  
black trench coats walked into a suburban Denver high school today 
and began the bloodiest U.S. school shooting in recent years, an 
incident police are calling a ``suicide mission.'' The gunmen, who 
authorities say may have killed 25 people, were found dead in the 
library at Columbine High School. Several students said the killers 
were gunning for minorities and athletes. The gunmen -- both juniors 
at Columbine -- were found dead of self-inflicted gunshot wounds, 
with what appeared to be bombs around their bodies, a sheriff's 
spokesman said. Authorities also said explosives were found in two 
cars in the school parking lot and bomb squad officers were 
disarming them. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton: 'Wake Up' to School Violence  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton, in the wake of the school  
shooting at a suburban Denver high school, called on the nation to 
``wake up'' to school violence. Out of respect for Colorado's 
grief, Clinton canceled a political trip tomorrow to Texas. He said 
a team of counselors has been mobilized and will head to Littleton, 
Colo., where the death toll -- which police estimated at 25 -- was 
still being confirmed. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Attacks Continue in Yugoslavia  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- U.S. helicopters and troops were  
headed toward Albania tonight in a new military phase aimed at 
boosting the NATO alliance's ability to attack Yugoslav ground 
forces and stop their campaign to rid Kosovo of its ethnic Albanian 
majority. NATO launched daylight attacks today and continued them 
after dark across Yugoslavia and accused Serb forces of flushing 
out ethnic Albanians hiding in the province's hills. Yugoslav media 
reported pre-dawn attacks Wednesday in several areas of central 
Serbia, including Novi Sad and the town of Valjevo, where six 
missiles struck a factory, triggering a huge fire. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Military Pressed for Resources  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The dual military needs in both Yugoslavia and  
Iraq are putting the pinch on the U.S. military, leaving no U.S. 
aircraft carrier in the Pacific Ocean. Instead, Air Force planes 
there have gone on alert. The gap in carrier coverage for the 
Pacific could last until the fall, when the USS Constellation is to 
arrive, defense officials said. The USS Kitty Hawk that was in the 
Pacific was ordered to the Persian Gulf on April 3 to free up the 
USS Theodore Roosevelt to join the NATO airstrikes on Yugoslavia. 
The Roosevelt arrived in the Adriatic Sea on April 5. 

</P>
<P>
	Tribes Seek Tougher Grave Law  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Thousands of Indian remains and sacred  
artifacts haven't been returned to tribes because of delays by 
museums and loopholes in a federal grave-protection law, a Senate 
committee was told today. Some 14,000 human remains out of 200,000 
identified nationally have been returned to tribes under the 1990 
law, the committee said, and many of the remains that haven't been 
returned can't be identified by tribe. But tribal leaders told the 
Senate Indian Affairs Committee the law is too narrowly written. 

</P>
<P>
	Malaysia Seeking Out Killer Virus  
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Malaysia has begun killing dogs  
and plans to test ``every species imaginable'' to curb a rare form 
of viral encephalitis that has claimed about 100 lives, officials 
said today. A dozen victims have died of Japanese encephalitis and 
more than 90 most recently from a new virus named Nipah for the 
village where its first victim died. Despite claims that the 
outbreak appeared to be over, officials said today that stray dogs 
had contracted the Nipah virus. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Profits Jump 43 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft Corp.'s quarterly profit jumped 43  
percent from a year earlier on strength across its range of 
products, particularly its Office business software and Windows NT 
software for running corporate computers. Microsoft, the world's 
dominant maker of personal computer software, reported today it 
earned $1.92 billion, or 35 cents a share, in its fiscal third 
quarter, which ended March 31. That was up from a profit of $1.34 
billion, or 25 cents a share, in the year-ago quarter. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Open Lower  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks edged lower Wednesday on renewed  
concerns about the pace of Japan's economic recovery. The Nikkei 
fell 67.30 points to 16,629.81. In New York, the Dow ended up 8.02 
to 10,448.55. The Nasdaq finished up 64.03 to 2,409.64. 

</P>
<P>
	Games Postponed After Colo. Shooting  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The shooting at Columbine High School in suburban  
Littleton prompted the Denver Nuggets to postpone their game 
tonight, and the Colorado Rockies did the same. And the 
Montreal-Colorado baseball game will be made up as part of a split 
doubleheader when the Expos return to Colorado for a three-games 
series Aug. 13-15. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  

</P>
</TEXT>
