<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Straw Reportedly Passes Drug Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Darryl Strawberry's future depends on the  
results of his latest drug tests, due to be received by the 
commissioner's office sometime this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Yankees outfielder came through the first test OK,  
according to a published report today. 
</P>
<P>
	The test was given last week, 24 hours before he was arrested in  
Tampa, Fla., for cocaine possession and solicitation. It indicated 
``there was no problem,'' The Record of Hackensack, N.J., reported, 
quoting sources said to be familiar with Strawberry's legal 
predicament. 
</P>
<P>
	Had the results revealed traces of a drug, Strawberry faced at  
least a six-month ban from baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry was tested again during a weekend visit to New York  
when he met with officials of the players association, the 
commissioner's office and doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	Those close to Strawberry were confident that the latest tests  
will be fine as well, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball had been testing the outfielder twice a week as part of  
the aftercare program that followed his 60-day suspension in 1995 
for a positive test for cocaine use. Strawberry has not tested 
positive for illegal drugs since then, the Yankees said last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry, 37, was at the Yankees' training camp as part of its  
extended spring training program. He was still rehabilitating from 
colon cancer surgery in October. 
</P>
<P>
	``As of right now, he is not resuming workouts,'' Cashman said  
Monday. ``From the club's perspective, he's got his legal issues 
and personal issues to deal with. It's best for him at this 
particular moment to deal with that. Baseball is second right 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's unclear if the Yankees have stopped paying Strawberry, who  
is not on their 40-man roster. He has a minor league contract and a 
consulting deal with the team, which together total $2.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	New York has been advancing money to Strawberry and may have  
stopped those advances, one of the sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	No arraignment date has been set for Strawberry, but when he is  
formally charged, he will plead innocent, his attorney said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Entrapment is a pretty wide avenue,'' attorney Joseph  
Ficarrota told The Record from his office in Tampa. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry has said he as only joking with the female undercover  
officer posing as a prostitute. 
</P>
<P>
	Ficarrota will argue that the charges should be dropped since no  
money changed hands between Strawberry and the woman, Strawberry 
was arrested after driving beyond the motel where the woman told 
him to meet here, and there was no tape recording of the 
conversation between the outfielder and the officer. 
</P>
<P>
	If Ficarrota succeeds in getting the solicitation charge  
dropped, he will argue there was no probable cause for the 
subsequent search which police said produced three-tenths of a gram 
of cocaine inside a rolled up $20 bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Without probable cause, the search would be illegal, Ficarrota  
told the newspaper, and its results inadmissable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
