<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Escaped Suspect Turns Himself In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- A man whose testimony helped put two  
innocent men in prison for murder turned himself in Tuesday, one 
week from the day he escaped from a work detail after learning he 
was now a suspect in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Glen Gore walked away from a prison work crew April 14, one day  
before the two men he helped put behind bars were released. 
</P>
<P>
	The men, Ron Williamson, 46, and Dennis Fritz, 49, were cleared  
after DNA evidence showed they were not the men who strangled and 
assaulted a 21-year-old woman, a crime for which they were 
convicted in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	The men spent 12 years in prison. Williamson was on death row;  
Fritz was sentenced to life in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, 38, returned to the Lexington Correctional Center on  
Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say Gore is the prime suspect in a reopened  
investigation into the crime. No charges have been filed against 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	DNA results were compared to a databank of DNA samples from  
state inmates, and the results matched a DNA profile of Gore, who 
was serving time for burglary, kidnapping and shooting with intent 
to injure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
