<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Proposes Surplus Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans brought legislation to the Senate  
floor Tuesday that would make it difficult to spend anticipated 
Social Security surpluses on anything but shoring up the retirement 
program or reducing the national debt. The White House threatened 
to veto the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders say strict new rules are needed to stop  
lawmakers from spending government surpluses that come from Social 
Security's payroll taxes, as opposed to income taxes, in coming 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``The goal here is to lock this money up,'' said Senate Majority  
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. ``We want to make it as difficult as 
possible to breach that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate began debating the proposed restrictions Tuesday, but  
objections from Democrats -- including a veto threat from the 
Clinton administration -- are expected to hold up any votes until at 
least later this week. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton's advisers at the White House Office of  
Management and Budget said in a statement Tuesday that the GOP 
measure would too tightly restrict the government's day-to-day cash 
flow, especially in the event of ``any unanticipated slowdown in 
the economy.'' Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin first raised that 
concern last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota said the  
Republican measure ``doesn't commit a nickel'' of income tax 
surpluses that Democrats want for Medicare, the health insurance 
program for the elderly. Republicans instead want expected income 
tax surpluses for tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, the administration's statement said ``the  
legislation is flawed because it ... fails to ensure that the 
surplus is used to protect the payment of benefits to Social 
Security beneficiaries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton wants to try to give Social Security a tangible claim on  
the economic growth that would be expected to result from a lower 
national debt: IOUs giving the program a claim on income-tax 
dollars after baby boomers retire. He also has called for 
government investment of some of Social Security's cash reserves in 
the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans say Clinton's IOUs would be just paper promises that  
would have to be made good by taxpayers or borrowing in the future, 
and the stock market investments would bring private financial 
markets under undue government influence. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders have yet to endorse any specific alternative for  
using the surpluses to benefit Social Security, but in both the 
House and Senate they are encouraging the development of plans by 
other influential Republican lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means  
Committee, is close to unveiling one such plan that would use the 
Social Security tax surpluses to finance new personal accounts 
workers could invest in the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	Those familiar with Archer's plan say the investment returns  
workers earned would be substituted, on an individual basis, for 
traditional Social Security benefits, probably at something close 
to a dollar-for-dollar exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Republican Sens. Judd Gregg of New Hampshire and Rick  
Santorum of Pennsylvania, whom Lott has picked to head a GOP task 
force, are collaborating with moderate Democrats on a plan 
combining similar personal accounts with upfront trimming of Social 
Security benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Unless Democrats and Republicans can resolve their considerable  
differences and enact Social Security changes, however, the 
Republican bill that reached the Senate floor Tuesday would wall 
off Social Security surpluses for the next 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would require that the surpluses be used to pay off  
the government's debt to private bondholders. To ensure that 
happens, it would periodically lower the statutory limit on that 
public debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Breaching the declining debt limit would require agreement by 60  
senators -- more than a majority. The main exception would be for 
money used to enact Social Security reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Other exceptions would include national defense emergencies --  
such as the current conflict in Yugoslavia -- and a recession that 
held economic growth to less than 1 percent for at least six 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	House Republican leaders say they will bring similar legislation  
to the floor soon. A nonbinding version passed Congress as part of 
the GOP budget resolution last week, but actually putting the new 
spending restrictions into effect would require a change in law and 
Clinton's signature. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
