<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amgen Profits Soar 31 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Amgen's first-quarter earnings soared 31  
percent, easily surpassing Wall Street estimates, on the strength 
of the biotechnology firm's Epogen anemia-fighting drug. 
</P>
<P>
	Amgen stock rose 13 percent Tuesday even before the profit  
report was released after the close of trading on the Nasdaq stock 
market. Shares of Amgen rose $8.06 to $69 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	The company earned $247 million, or 46 cents per share, up from  
$187 million, or 35 cents per share, in the same period a year ago. 
Results beat Wall Street estimates by 2 cents, according to First 
Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales rose 21 percent to $688 million from $567 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Epogen, Amgen's top product that treats anemia in dialysis  
patients, posted a 30 percent increase in sales to $395 million to 
$304 million. Sales of Neupogen, which stimulates the growth of 
white blood cells in cancer patients, rose 10 percent to $287 
million from $261 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it has made progress in testing its  
next-generation anemia drug called NESP. Amgen expect to start 
advanced human testing of the drug in dialysis patients by the end 
of the year. 

</P>
</TEXT>
