<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Celtics' Battie Faces Assault Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Tony Battie of the Celtics is facing charges of  
dragging a police officer behind his car after the officer told him 
to move it. 
</P>
<P>
	Battie's arraignment was postponed to Wednesday in Boston  
Municipal Court as the court grappled with a busy schedule 
following the Patriots' Day weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Battie was arrested around 2:20 a.m. Saturday in front of the  
Cosmopolitan Club, Boston police spokeswoman Sgt. Detective Margot 
Hill said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said he was asked several times by an officer to move his  
car, but Battie refused. 
</P>
<P>
	Battie also was said to have refused the officer's request for  
proper identification and tried to drive off when the officer 
attempted to arrest him, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The officer's arm was caught in the driver's window, Hill said,  
and the officer was forced to pull out his service revolver before 
Battie stopped the car. 
</P>
<P>
	Battie faces a charge of assault and battery with a dangerous  
weapon (the car), and a charge of refusing to identify himself to 
an officer, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Celtics general manager Chris Wallace would not comment on the  
incident. Battie scored four points in Boston's 120-104 loss to 
Indiana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
