<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Mrs. Clinton Addresses Health Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton called for changes  
in the nation's medical insurance system on Tuesday at the same 
time she acknowledged her failed 1993 effort to reform health care. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to try that again, rest assured,'' she said in a  
speech at Hofstra University, adding: ``I come from the school of 
smaller steps now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton spoke on day two of her road trip to New York,  
where she is considering running for the U.S. Senate seat of Sen. 
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, who is retiring. 
</P>
<P>
	She called for a patient's bill of rights to force health  
insurers to provide access to specialists; enhanced privacy 
regarding medical records; tax breaks to encourage small businesses 
to provide health insurance for employees; and support for 
President Clinton's proposal to shore up Medicare with part of the 
federal budget surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Mrs. Clinton said nothing about her political plans,  
several others were talkative on the subject. 
</P>
<P>
	Judith Hope, chairwoman of the state's Democratic Party, said  
the first lady is giving her potential candidacy ``very serious 
consideration ... She continues to look like a candidate, sound 
like a candidate while doing the valid work of a first lady.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton began Tuesday at the Village Elementary School in  
Syosset, where she watched third-graders observing tiny live frogs 
swimming in tanks. 
</P>
<P>
	She laughed when she was told that another first lady -- Eleanor  
Roosevelt -- visited the Long Island school 41 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm used to following Mrs. Roosevelt,'' she said. ``I don't  
know that I've ever been anywhere in the world, literally, that she 
hadn't been first.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
