<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Family of Killed Schoolgirl Settles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- The parents of a girl killed when she  
caught the drawstring of her jacket on a school bus handrail have 
settled their $30 million lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrea Chen, 14, was getting off her school bus on Feb. 8, 1996,  
when one end of the drawstring around the bottom of her parka 
slipped between the handrail and the wall of the stairway leading 
down from the bus. 
</P>
<P>
	Though regulations say a school bus cannot leave until departing  
children are 15 feet away, the bus drove off. The parka was still 
attached to the handrail and Andrea was dragged beneath the bus and 
crushed by its back wheels. 
</P>
<P>
	The terms of the settlement were not disclosed but the parents'  
lawyer, Donald Silverman, said, ``It's an extraordinary amount for 
the wrongful death of a child.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement came Monday, after a jury had been selected for  
the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverman said Michael and Sin-Chai Chen were recovering money  
from the bus company, Advance Transit Co., as well as from an 
insurer for the company and for driver Eugenio Cordero. Advance 
Transit did not return calls for comment. There was no telephone 
listing for Cordero. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 11:06:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Allies Urged on Economic War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Clinton administration officials said today  
they will use this week's NATO summit to push for allied agreement 
on economic sanctions including an oil embargo to deny Yugoslavia 
the ability to wage war in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO allies remain ``rock solid'' behind the goal of the  
month-old airstrikes to continue the campaign until the Serb 
military halts attacks on ethnic Albanians in the Serbian province, 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright declared. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will prevail here. We are not putting a time limit on it,''  
Albright said at a White House news conference with President 
Clinton's foreign policy team. ``There is a sense of determination 
and unity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the three-day 50th anniversary summit, which begins Friday,  
U.S. leaders will urge NATO allies to ``consider new economic 
measures designed to deny Belgrade the ability to wage war against 
its own people,'' Albright said. 
</P>
<P>
	Specifically, she said the administration would like to see an  
oil embargo to prevent supplies from reaching Yugoslav ports. NATO 
airstrikes have destroyed 100 percent of Yugoslavia's oil-refining 
capacity and have hit supplies as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Although NATO leaders haven't yet embraced the proposal,  
Albright said she has talked to allied foreign ministers who are 
beginning to ``see the problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defense Secretary William Cohen said he believed an oil supply  
clampdown would occur. ``We think it's important that all sources 
of resupply of fuel and energy be eliminated. How that is to be 
achieved is a matter of discussion,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether the Clinton administration is pushing for removal  
of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, Albright said the Serbs 
would be better off with a democratic leader, but airstrikes aren't 
meant to get rid of Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have said that President Milosevic is responsible for the  
ethnic cleansing and all the depredations that are taking place,'' 
Albright said. ``But that is not the goal.'' Instead, it is ``get 
the Serb forces out of Kosovo and the refugees back into Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president's national security adviser, Sandy Berger, said  
NATO summit leaders may discuss the matter of sending group troops 
to Yugoslavia, an idea that has been repeatedly rejected by the 
allies and the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, he said, NATO wants to keep up the air campaign and he  
doesn't expect that to change. ``The consensus is to stay the 
course,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent days, Albright has been beseeching her fellow foreign  
ministers to approve a cutoff in shipments of refined oil to 
Yugoslavia, possibly with at-sea intercepts of vessels, and 
soliciting cooperation from Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	In a parallel move, American diplomats are appealing to  
governments in Europe and elsewhere to withhold any oil shipments 
to Yugoslavia, according to a senior U.S. official speaking Monday 
on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	France has registered doubts about interdiction of oil shipments  
in the absence of a declaration of war against Yugoslavia, while 
the Greek government would prefer that the Clinton administration 
work through the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The French foreign ministry said Monday it supported ``the quick  
adoption of a common stand'' on restricting oil supplies to 
Yugoslavia, but that the European Union and the Balkans nations 
should be asked to take on the task of finding a formula. 
</P>
<P>
	Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis, calling on U.N.  
Secretary-General Kofi Annan in New York, sought to shift the focus 
of NATO's efforts. He said the United Nations should take the lead 
in devising a political framework to end the bombing and to permit 
ethnic Albanian refugees to return to their homes in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	With Annan bound for Moscow, Albright telephoned Foreign  
Minister Igor Ivanov in a bid for at least Russian acquiescence to 
the U.S. proposal and for continued withholding of technology and 
intelligence to Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	President Boris Yeltsin has ruled out Russian intervention in  
the Balkans conflict. But he urged Clinton on the telephone Monday 
to call off the airstrikes and revert to diplomacy as the path to a 
settlement in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin still has not indicated whether he plans to attend the  
NATO summit meeting here next weekend that will dwell on Kosovo 
instead of celebrating the 50th anniversary of the founding of the 
anti-Soviet alliance as originally planned. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, though, the NATO alliance remains essentially united on  
the air campaign, which began March 24, and Russia has not crossed 
the line between sympathy for the Serbs and actively supporting 
them, administration officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright is hoping to sell the idea of an oil cutoff to the  
allies with the argument that it is the logical follow-up to the 
devastating bombardment of Yugoslav refineries. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important to try to prevent them from pursuing other  
means to fuel this evil war machine,'' State Department spokesman 
James P. Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shying away from calling the cutoff a blockade, Rubin said: ``An  
example of a way to go about this is a regime of some kind of 
visiting and searching ships, which would enable one to distinguish 
between products that would fuel the Yugoslav war machine and other 
kinds of products.'' He said he didn't know which countries were 
shipping refined oil to Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
