<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> People Might Feel the Cost of War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Top congressional Republicans acknowledged  
Tuesday that the multibillion-dollar costs of the clash with 
Yugoslavia and an accompanying military buildup will come from 
Social Security surpluses, and might affect the size of the party's 
proposed tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
	A day after President Clinton asked Congress for $6.05 billion  
for the Balkans conflict, Republican House and Senate leaders said 
the first votes on the measure could come next week. But the 
leaders seemed to disagree over how insistent they should be about 
adding more defense funds. 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, said it is ``our  
first moral obligation'' to strengthen a Pentagon left overburdened 
worldwide by the Clinton administration. He used no figure, but 
said Monday that a $10 billion measure would be ``insufficient.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe the perception of us being stretched too thin is for  
any number of places around the world an invitation, a provocation, 
to make a strike and see if we can get away with it,'' Armey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reflecting the sentiment in his more moderate chamber, Senate  
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said the GOP should use ``as 
much restraint as we can'' and limit the bill to single-digit 
billions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	He said a measure costing $15 billion to $18 billion, as some  
House conservatives have said they want, does not have ``any 
realistic chance'' of being enacted. Citing shortages of ships, 
ammunition and personnel, Rep. Duncan Hunter, R-Calif., chairman of 
the House Armed Services military procurement subcommittee, said he 
believed the bill should run ``well beyond $20 billion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a limit to how much you can sensibly spend in a period  
of time,'' Lott said. ``You run the risk if you make it too big it 
collapses in a puddle, and that creates problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armey and Lott also disagreed over whether language should be  
included boosting military pay and pensions. Lott said it should, 
but Armey suggested that should be considered later because it 
wasn't as urgent as paying for the war. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever the price tag, Armey and Lott said they believed the  
money will come from this year's federal budget surplus, which is 
expected to be about $110 billion and comes entirely from Social 
Security surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	That was a significant admission, because in this year's budget  
fight with Clinton, Republicans have promised repeatedly that they 
will use Social Security surpluses only to overhaul the program or 
reduce the national debt. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president has asked for that money, and the American  
people need to understand that it's coming out of Social 
Security,'' Lott told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Armey said separately that if voters see the war's costs  
trimming the national debt reduction that is achieved this year, 
``I think they understand the need, the priorities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armey said defense spending should go up next year, too, and  
finding the money to pay for that would cause Republicans to 
``re-examine our priorities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said that would include a debate over whether money should be  
shifted from domestic to defense spending, and ``whether the tax 
reduction might be less than it might otherwise need to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP-written budget approved by Congress last week calls for  
10-year tax cuts of at least $778 billion, with about $15 billion 
of the cuts coming next year. Fiscal 2000 begins Oct. 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
