<HEADLINE> Japan Phone Co. Cutting 2,000 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's leading international long-distance phone  
service provider will cut 2,000 jobs -- about one-third of its work 
force -- over the next five years as part of a restructuring. 
</P>
<P>
	KDD Corp. President Tadashi Nishimoto announced the widely  
expected move, saying the retrenchment will trim the company's 
payroll to 3,800 employees from 5,800 by early 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	The reductions will be achieved through early retirement and  
attrition, as opposed to layoffs, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Once a protected monopoly, KDD has seen its dominant market  
share slide amid greater competition sparked by recent government 
moves to deregulate Japan's telecommunications industry. 
</P>
<P>
	KDD also plans to streamline its board of directors to 10  
members from 32 and split up its business operations into three 
main units responsible for sales, networks and management. 
</P>
<P>
	Company head Nishimoto said KDD's operating revenues for the  
fiscal year that ended March 31 will probably be slightly lower 
than forecast. But revenues from operations outside of its core 
business will probably be slightly higher than expected, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
