<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Notes 'Disturbing Developments'  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO is reporting ``disturbing  
developments'' -- reports ``too numerous'' to ignore -- of Serb 
soldiers raping ethnic Albanian women and using tear gas to move 
ethnic Albanians out of their homes in Pristina. NATO spokesman 
Jamie Shea said Serb military and paramilitary forces were staging 
``safari-style'' operations, shelling hills where ethnic Albanians 
fled to flush them out, marching the refugees on roads, putting 
them on trains to the border and then closing the border to them. 
Shea told reporters at NATO headquarters that the alliance was 
investigating reports of ethnic Albanians used as ``human shields 
in front of tanks,'' mass executions, and ethnic cleansing 
operations spreading from Kosovo into border villages of 
Montenegro, Yugoslavia's smaller republic. 

</P>
<P>
	$6B Kosovo Request Sparks Battle  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A group of seven senators has proposed that  
President Clinton be given authority to use ``all necessary force'' 
in the Kosovo campaign. Such authority could be used to send ground 
troops to the area. President Clinton has not asked for such 
authority. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., the prime sponsor of the 
``necessary force'' proposal and a presidential candidate, pushed 
the idea as Congress discussed President Clinton's request for $6 
billion to pay for the war in Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	Serb Police Commander Arrested  
</P>
<P>
	ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) -- A police commander suspected of war  
crimes against Croat civilians during the country's conflict with 
rebel minority Serbs has been arrested, a county prosecutor said 
today. Dragisa Cancarevic, an ethnic Serb who served with local 
Serb paramilitary troops in the eastern town Vukovar, was arrested 
late yesterday without offering resistance, prosecutor Biserka 
Treneski said. Minority Serbs rebelled against Croatia's secession 
from the former Yugoslav federation in 1991. 

</P>
<P>
	Bradley Pushes Racial Unity  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Declaring racial unity ``the defining moral  
issue of our time,'' former Sen. Bill Bradley today put the quest 
for societal integration at the center of his campaign to win the 
White House in 2000. Bradley, the sole Democrat thus far to 
challenge Vice President Al Gore for the party's nomination, said 
the problem of race is ``central to our American future.'' His 
remarks were prepared for an appearance today at Cooper Union in 
New York City. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate Votes To Honor Rosa Parks  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate has voted unanimously to award Rosa  
Parks a Congressional Gold Medal four decades after her refusal to 
surrender her bus seat to a white man helped spark the civil rights 
movement. Senators approved the measure 86-0 Monday, and House 
passage was expected today. President Clinton is certain to sign 
the legislation, which would bestow Congress' highest civilian 
award on the 86-year-old civil rights pioneer. 

</P>
<P>
	Gandhi's Party Set To Lead India  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- The Congress Party headed by Sonia  
Gandhi will be ready to form a government by Wednesday, after the 
national budget vote, party officials said today. President K.R. 
Narayanan has made passage of the national budget a priority and 
was not expected to talk to any parties about the next government 
until parliament's lower house passes the spending plan. The 
parliament, which includes lawmakers from 45 parties, was split by 
Saturday's 270-269 vote, which brought the collapse of Prime 
Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee's government. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 19; Nasdaq Up 44  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 1 p.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was down 19.47 at 10,421.06. Decliners on the New York 
Stock Exchange outnumbered advancers 1,694-1,165. The Nasdaq 
composite index was up 44.42 at 2,390.03. 

</P>
<P>
	NHL May Revoke Penguins' Franchise  
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A National Hockey League official said the NHL  
could ask a court for permission to revoke the Pittsburgh Penguins' 
franchise if a plan to pull the team from bankruptcy protection 
isn't adopted soon. Efforts to get the team out of financial 
trouble have stalled, and former Penguins star Mario Lemieux has 
submitted the only financial reorganization plan. Revoking the 
Penguins franchise would be an NHL first. The move would allow the 
sale of player contracts or the entire team to another city under 
the league constitution. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by PRUDENCE HELLER  
</P>
