<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Times Mirror Profits Rise 7.8 Pct. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Times Mirror reported a 7.8 percent increase  
in first quarter earnings Tuesday as the newspaper and magazine 
publisher benefited from circulation growth and higher profits at 
key East Coast newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which publishes the Los Angeles Times and other  
leading newspapers, earned $48.8 million, or 58 cents per share, 
compared to $45.3 million, or 44 cents per share, during the first 
quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues rose 4.5 percent to $746 million from $714 million.  
</P>
<P>
	The improved earnings were supported by double-digit growth in  
operating profit at Newsday and The Baltimore Sun, Times Mirror's 
largest East Coast newspapers in terms of circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	The growth offset a slight decline in operating profit at the  
flagship Los Angeles Times, said Mark H. Willes, chairman, 
president and chief executive officer of Times Mirror and publisher 
of the Times. 
</P>
<P>
	``We also showed steady improvement in both average daily and  
Sunday circulation at our largest newspapers,'' Willes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Times executives announced in December they would eliminate 500  
full-time and part-time jobs as part of a reorganization aimed at 
cutting costs and boosting circulation and ad sales. Willes said 
full savings from the restructuring have not been realized. No 
editorial positions were included in the cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	First quarter revenues from newspaper publishing rose 5.6  
percent to $573.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Times Mirror closed down 25 cents at $61.87 1/2 in  
trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 


</P>
</TEXT>
