<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillip Morris Profits Rise Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Philip Morris Cos. Inc.'s underlying profit  
barely improved in the first quarter as cigarette shipments skidded 
following last fall's price hikes. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's biggest tobacco maker held up better than the  
industry, however, and extended its commanding share of the U.S. 
cigarette market. 
</P>
<P>
	The results were slightly ahead of Wall Street expectations, and  
Philip Morris shares closed up 3 percent, or by $1.12 1/2, at $34.25 
in trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Its underlying income, excluding one-time-only charges, was up  
1.4 percent to $2.0 billion, or 80 cents a share, in the three 
months ended March 31, from $1.93 billion, or 79 cents a share, a 
year ago. That was a penny better than the 79 cents a share average 
expected by analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Including one-time factors, the company's net income was $1.79  
billion, or 73 cents a share, up from $1.38 billion, or 57 cents a 
share, a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Those results were depressed by $287 million in pretax charges  
for early retirement programs in its food and tobacco businesses 
this year and $901 million in pretax charges a year ago for tobacco 
litigation settlements and employee reductions in the tobacco 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue rose 6.1 percent to $19.5 billion from $18.38 billion a  
year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Domestic tobacco profits fell 7.3 percent to $1 billion as its  
cigarette shipments fell 9.6 percent and promotional spending 
increased. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had expected cigarette shipments would tumble in the  
wake of the 45 cent-a-pack price increase that Philip Morris and 
other leading cigarette makers imposed in November to help pay for 
a legal settlement with the states. 
</P>
<P>
	The tobacco makers agreed to pay $206 billion over 25 years to  
settle claims by 46 states over health costs related to treating 
sick smokers. The industry had settled earlier for $40 billion with 
the other four states. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris said the 9.6 percent decline in its cigarette  
shipments to wholesalers and distributors was slightly smaller than 
the industry's 9.7 percent decline. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, its share of the U.S. shipment market rose 0.1  
percentage point to 50.4 percent. Its share of retail cigarette 
sales, as measured by A.C. Nielsen, climbed 1.6 points to 53.7 
percent, Philip Morris said. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts said the price hikes didn't account directly for  
the entire decline in shipments. Part was because wholesalers and 
distributors had stocked up in advance of the price hikes and were 
selling from inventory rather than ordering more from the cigarette 
makers. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin Feldman, analyst for Salomon Smith Barney, said the  
shipment figures were being compared with an especially strong 
first quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Feldman said he was impressed with Philip Morris' ability to  
shield its best-selling Marlboro brand from the full brunt of the 
price fallout. Philip Morris and others have been offering 
discounts on some brands to cushion the impact of the price hike, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Marlboro shipments fell only 4.6 percent and the brand's share  
of the retail market rose 2.2 points to 38.8 percent, the company 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Emanuel Goldman, tobacco analyst for Merrill Lynch, said Philip  
Morris may have been worried people would buy cheaper brands due to 
the price hike. ``That clearly didn't seem to happen. If anything, 
people traded up to Marlboro,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	International tobacco profits rose 0.9 percent even as cigarette  
shipments fell 11.2 percent. Strong results in Western Europe and 
Japan were offset in Eastern Europe and parts of Asia and Latin 
America, 
</P>
<P>
	Profits at Kraft Foods North America rose 5 percent, mainly due  
to lower commodity and manufacturing costs, while international 
food profits rose 5.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Its Miller Brewing Co. posted a 6.3 percent increase in  
operating income due to lower costs and higher income from brewing 
done for rivals like Pabst. 
</P>
<P>
	Domestic shipments were up 0.5 percent despite a 1.2 percent  
decline for the flagship Miller Lite brand. 
</P>
<P>
	A new advertising campaign was launched recently for Miller  
Lite, evoking the ``Tastes Great, Less Filling'' approach of the 
brand's heyday. New leaders were installed at Miller several weeks 
ago. 

</P>
</TEXT>
