<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Compaq Promises To Rebuild </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Just days after Compaq Computer Corp. ousted its  
chief executive, the company purchased a full-page advertisement 
published Tuesday in two newspapers promising customers and 
shareholders it is committed to rebuilding. 
</P>
<P>
	``Compaq became a leader through intense dedication to  
anticipating and exceeding the needs of its market. We are 
committed to re-energizing that dedication ...,'' according to the 
ad in the Houston Chronicle and The Wall Street Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	The advertisement included a letter distributed Sunday to Compaq  
employees announcing the departure of chief executive Eckhard 
Pfeiffer, who had struggled to maintain profits amid plummeting 
personal computer prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine days before Pfeiffer was asked to resign, Compaq announced  
it anticipated earnings of 15 cents per share in the first quarter 
on revenue of $9.4 billion -- $600 million lower than expected. 
First-quarter results are due out Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The employee letter, signed by Compaq chairman Ben Rosen, vows  
to increase efficiency, ``delivering quick responses to business 
demands, promptly meeting the needs of every customer and keeping 
us well ahead of the market at all times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rosen is acting as chief executive officer until a replacement  
for Pfeiffer is found. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfeiffer, meanwhile, says he was asked to leave to mollify Wall  
Street. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you want to appease the financial community, you create a  
shakeup,'' he told the Houston Chronicle in Tuesday editions. 
``That, at least, seems to wipe the page clean and you start from 
there.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
