<HEADLINE> Honeywell Earnings Rise 9 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Honeywell Inc. reported Tuesday its  
first-quarter earnings rose 9 percent on a 3 percent increase in 
sales and continued cost-cutting. 
</P>
<P>
	Honeywell earned $105.4 million, or 83 cents a share, in the  
quarter ended April 4, compared with $96.3 million, or 75 cents a 
share, a year earlier. The results surpassed the 80 cents a share 
expected by Wall Street analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for the Minneapolis-based maker of controls for the home,  
industrial, aviation and space markets rose to $1.99 billion, from 
$1.92 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Home and building controls sales were up 3 percent to $805.7  
million. Sales of space and aviation controls rose 6 percent to 
$581 million. Sales of industrial controls were flat at $583.9 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Honeywell introduced several new products during the quarter,  
including a pulp and paper quality control system, and continued to 
cut costs and make its businesses more efficient. Honeywell said it 
was able to reduce costs significantly by paying other companies to 
make 70,000 circuit card assemblies per year. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Honeywell has said it expected worldwide economic  
conditions to limit core growth this year, the company expects 
continued strong earnings growth into 2000, said Michael 
Bonsignore, chairman and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Honeywell also announced it has signed a $250 million, 10-year  
contract with Chevron Products Co. to install and maintain all 
automation solutions at Chevron's refinery in Richmond, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Honeywell fell $1 to $89.37 1/2 in trading on the New  
York Stock Exchange. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
