<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nazareth Mosque Compromise Gets OK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Christian leaders in Nazareth accepted an  
Israeli compromise today on a dispute over a planned mosque that 
prompted religious tensions in Jesus' hometown. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal calls for a section of the ground outside the  
Church of the Annunciation to be designated for a mosque on 
condition that Muslims agree to remove a protest tent they have 
pitched on the site. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Nazareth's Christian mayor said he accepted the  
proposal. Muslim leaders, however, have rejected the Israeli plan 
and have sued to have the entire area dedicated for a mosque. 
</P>
<P>
	The head of the Islamic Movement in Nazareth, Salman Abu Ahmad,  
said the government offer, though well-intentioned, does not even 
begin to meet the Muslims' demands. ``How can they give us only 13 
percent of what is Wakf (Islamic Trust) property? It's a 
disgrace,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli authorities -- backed by some churches -- plan to build a  
plaza on the site to accommodate an anticipated flood of pilgrims 
during the millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	Tensions over the plan led to an outbreak of violence over  
Easter weekend. Cars were stoned and shops were set on fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The Christians, despite their tentative approval, remain  
skeptical about the Israeli government's motivations. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel goes to the polls in national elections on May 17 and the  
Christians say the Israelis have drawn out the dispute in order 
play the two sides against each other and gain votes from both 
camps in the process. 
</P>
<P>
	``They want to use the incident for political purposes,  
specifically for the elections,'' said Ramzi Hakim, an aide to 
Mayor Ramez Jeraisi. 
</P>
<P>
	He questioned the need for a compromise, saying that Israel --  
which controls the disputed land -- does not need to consult with 
Muslim authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	Roman Catholic tradition holds that the church is where the  
Angel Gabriel told Mary that she would give birth to Jesus. Muslims 
believe that a leading anti-Crusader is buried at the site. 
</P>
<P>
	Now that Bethlehem, the city where tradition has it that Jesus  
was born, has come under Palestinian control, Israel has been eager 
to promote Nazareth as one of its main attractions for pilgrims 
during the millennium year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
