<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybean Futures Rise Sharply  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures rose sharply Tuesday on the Chicago  
Board of Trade amid forecasts for rains that could delay spring 
plantings. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, copper futures fell for the first time in four  
sessions, while energy futures also retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans moved higher on continuing rains in the  
Midwest, which have increasingly stalled fieldwork and could lead 
to smaller acreage planted and lower yields if the wet weather 
pattern holds. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures also were boosted after Russia announced it would  
buy 250,000 metric tons of U.S. corn, a purchase many linked to 
Clinton administration donations to that financially troubled 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans also were supported by a lack of farmer selling out of  
Brazil and the United States, which boosted cash market prices. 
Russia also tendered for 100,000 metric tons of soybeans. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures rose after the U.S. Agriculture Department  
reported Monday that winter wheat crop conditions had declined, 
although most of the gains came largely on the strength of the corn 
and soybean markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 5 3/4 cents to $2.69 a bushel; May  
corn rose 3 1/2 cents to $2.24 a bushel; May oats rose 3 1/4 cents to 
$1.24 a bushel; May soybeans rose 7 1/2 cents to $4.95 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Copper futures fell sharply on the New York Mercantile Exchange,  
retreating for the first time in four sessions, amid profit-taking 
and fears a worldwide surplus will continue to build. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices in recent weeks have been supported by expectations for  
sharp production cutbacks in North America, which could have an 
effect on warehouse supplies monitored by the London Metal Exchange 
that have soared this year. 
</P>
<P>
	William O'Neill, director of futures research at Merrill Lynch,  
said prices likely have reached their bottom amid expectations for 
renewed demand in Asia and Europe for economic weakness in key 
consuming countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Copper is used mainly in construction, plumbing and electronics,  
making its fortunes heavily dependent on industrial demand. 
</P>
<P>
	But some market skeptic believe the Asian recovery will be slow  
and see few signs of better European long-term demand. 
</P>
<P>
	May high-grade copper fell 1.75 cents, or 2.5 percent, to 68.65  
cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy futures retreated on the New York Mercantile Exchange  
amid expectations industry figures this week will show increased 
inventories. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers were anticipating the American Petroleum Institute would  
report crude inventories rose as much as 1 million barrels as 
higher U.S. prices attracted more imports. That, in turn, could 
boost refining into gasoline and heating oil. 
</P>
<P>
	The expiring May crude contract finished down 2 cents at $17.78  
a barrel, while June crude fell 15 cents to $17.48 a barrel. May 
heating oil fell 1.01 cents to 42.69 cents a gallon; May unleaded 
gasoline fell 1.03 cents to 52.41 cents a gallon; May natural gas 
fell 2.5 cents to $2.144 for each 1,000 cubic feet. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 16:14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Polygamy Goes on Trial in Utah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOGAN, Utah (AP) -- A man accused of beating his daughter after  
she ran away from an arranged marriage to his brother goes on trial 
Wednesday in a case that has many calling for a crackdown on Utah 
polygamy. 
</P>
<P>
	John Daniel Kingston, 43, is charged with felony child abuse for  
allegedly beating his 16-year-old daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl, now living in foster care, says her father drove her  
to a family owned farm near the Idaho line in May and whipped her 
for disobeying Daniel Ortell Kingston, who had made her his 15th 
wife. 
</P>
<P>
	But to many, the real defendant in the case is not the father,  
but a way of life in Utah that has survived in the shadows for more 
than a century. 
</P>
<P>
	Though polygamy is banned by the state constitution and  
denounced by the Mormon church, the attorney general's office 
estimates there are 25,000 practitioners in Utah alone. 
</P>
<P>
	And though lawyers for both sides say the trial is not about  
polygamy, the Kingston clan is one of the most prominent polygamous 
groups in Utah, and the issues have become inseparable. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Polygamy) is the very reason this whole thing is coming  
down,'' said Owen Allred, the leader of a separate polygamous clan 
based in Bluffdale. 
</P>
<P>
	``Generally speaking, our people are very peaceful,  
mind-your-own-business people,'' Allred said in a telephone 
interview. But right now, he said, he feels like his way of life is 
on trial. 
</P>
<P>
	No large-scale bigamy cases have been prosecuted since the  
1950s, when agents raided the town of Short Creek on the 
Utah-Arizona line. The incident backfired when the public, enraged 
by images of families being torn apart, protested and the state 
backed off. 
</P>
<P>
	Anti-polygamy groups say prosecutors should attack once more.  
They say the brothers should face bigamy as well the other charges 
-- child abuse against John Kingston and incest charges against 
Daniel Kingston, who is to be tried in June. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're really missing the boat on this one,'' said Carmen  
Thompson, executive director of the advocacy group Tapestry of 
Polygamy, comprised of former polygamous wives. ``When you see 
crimes stemming directly from the polygamy issue, the polygamy 
should be prosecuted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The clan led by patriarch Merlin Kingston goes by the name of  
the ``Latter-day Church of Christ'' and has about 1,000 members. 
The brothers are the sons of the clan's leader, who died in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Though not the largest polygamous group, the Kingstons are the  
most affluent, with assets estimated around $150 million. 
</P>
<P>
	When the issue exploded with charges filed against the Kingston  
last year, Gov. Mike Leavitt -- the great-grandson of polygamists -- 
said he thought the practice might be protected by the First 
Amendment. He soon backed away from that idea. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say it is difficult to prosecute bigamy, the only  
charge associated with plural marriage. Marriages are often 
performed in secret ceremonies, evidence can be skimpy or 
nonexistent, and they don't want to gamble time and resources while 
more pressing crimes demand attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have concentrated and focused on the abuses,'' said Palmer  
DePaulis, chief of staff for Utah Attorney General Janet Graham. 
</P>
<P>
	To that end, the office is trying to educate members of  
polygamous groups, including the children, how to recognize child 
abuse, date rape and domestic violence. There is also a hotline for 
wives of polygamists. 
</P>
<P>
	But others say that approach treats the symptoms, not the  
problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, the underlying problem is the polygamous relationship  
that exists and they ought to be prosecuting that relationship, not 
just the child abuse,'' said Dexter Anderson, a Millard County 
prosecutor. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the Kingston case ``opened the floodgates,'' Thompson said  
her office has fielded hundreds of calls from plural wives looking 
for help. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can tell you that even if the prosecutor doesn't see this as  
a polygamy case, the public does see it as a polygamy case,'' she 
said. ``How long is the abuse going to continue?'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 18:42:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Sentenced in Restaurant Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- An aspiring country singer accused of  
killing seven people in three robberies was sentenced to death 
Tuesday for the murders of two restaurant workers. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury took three hours to sentence Paul Reid in the deaths of  
Captain D's manager Steve Hampton, 25, and worker Sarah Jackson, 
16. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid was convicted last week for the February 1997 slayings in  
which he stole $7,500. He still faces two trials on charges he 
killed five workers at two other restaurants in Nashville and 
Clarksville. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers claimed Reid, 41, deserved to live because he is  
mentally ill and brain-damaged. Prosecutors described him as a 
calculated, cold-blooded murderer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Show him the same mercy he showed Steve and Sarah. Absolutely  
none,'' prosecutor Roger Moore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid was paroled in 1990 after serving about eight years of a  
20-year sentence in Texas for robbing a steak house in suburban 
Houston. He hoped to be a country singer, and drifted between 
Texas, Oklahoma and Tennessee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 16:14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Officials Mull School Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Metal detectors and surveillance cameras went  
up in the hallways. Idle threats went past the principal's office 
to the police station. Special events like proms and graduations 
were postponed. 
</P>
<P>
	In the year since a spate of school shootings, many principals  
and superintendents -- worried their students would copycat 
nationally reported incidents -- have cracked down on security. 
Congress and states have backed their efforts with money. 
</P>
<P>
	But as another violent school tragedy unfolded Tuesday,  
officials asked whether any school can protect against deadly 
shootings like those Tuesday in a Denver suburb. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's one of the great mysteries -- how do you identify a  
student who is going to act out?'' asked Barbara Wheeler, school 
board member in Downers Grove, Ill., and former president of the 
National School Boards Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Schools nationwide have taken steps such as installing metal  
detectors and surveillance cameras, tracking idle threats and 
profiling students with a potential for violence. At the slightest 
sign of trouble, principals and superintendents have responded: 
</P>
<P>
	-- A high school student in Starkville, Miss., was arrested in  
February and faces criminal charges for having a gun on school 
property. 
</P>
<P>
	-- An eighth-grader in Clarion County, Pa.,, who had a gun and  
repeated a threat to kill teachers was arrested at Union High 
School after a fellow student told his mother of threats. 
</P>
<P>
	-- A ninth-grade girl in Virginia was suspended when she wrote a  
note to a fellow student expressing anger about her teacher giving 
her a D, and the teacher took it as a physical threat. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials must walk a fine line between youthful boasting and  
joking and serious intentions, said June Arnette, associate 
director of the National School Safety Center in Westlake Village, 
Calif. But such talk shouldn't be ignored, said Arnette, whose 
private group now trains 100 schools a year to set up security 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Schools are being more proactive,'' said Arnette.  
</P>
<P>
	One of the most widely used safety measures, she said, is an  
anonymous tip service. Students can phone in or drop in a secured 
box any tip, such as a student with a gun. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not clear what policies were followed at Columbine High  
School in the middle-class suburb of Littleton, Colo., where gunmen 
-- believed to be fellow students -- opened fire Tuesday. Deborah 
Fallon, a spokeswoman for the Colorado Education Association, said 
the state's 176 districts set their own policies. 
</P>
<P>
	As the 1997-98 year showed, violence can even erupt at schools  
that seem safe to teachers and parents. 
</P>
<P>
	In March of last year, two boys in Jonesboro, Ark., opened fire  
on a crowd of students at their middle school, killing four 
classmates and a teacher. Students also were accused of fatal 
shootings in Springfield, Ore., West Paducah, Ky., and Pearl, Miss. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, a high school sophomore in Notus, Idaho, was  
accused of firing a shotgun in a school hallway, but no one was 
hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	Most school districts haven't faced legal action for not  
preventing crimes, but they have been held liable for violating 
students' rights when imposing penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet schools have not backed off developing policies because of  
the threat of lawsuits, said William Modzeleski, the Education 
Department's safe schools chief. They have been working with 
attorneys to develop fair policies. 
</P>
<P>
	In the long-run, educators argue that schools must address  
mental health. 
</P>
<P>
	Movies and television programs that glorify violence teach  
children to resort to violence, said Kevin P. Dwyer, of the 
National Association for School Psychologists in Bethesda, Md. He 
also blamed access to guns. Colorado requires handgun permits, and 
bans the possession or use of a gun by minors. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not something you can do with a metal detector,'' Dwyer  
said. ``We as a community have to teach kids to stop and think and 
respect one another.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal officials still say schools are safe. In 1996, theft  
accounted for 62 percent of crimes against students at school. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is the perception that schools are terribly  
crime-ridden. The perception is unfounded,'' Modzeleski said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
