<DOCNO> APW19990420.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 23:33:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schott Agrees To Sell Share of Reds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Marge Schott's tumultuous 15-year run as the  
Cincinnati Reds owner is coming to a close. 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with a lawsuit by the team's limited partners and pressure  
from baseball to sell, Schott agreed Tuesday to let Cincinnati 
financier Carl Lindner and two others buy most of her shares for 
$67 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Schott will retain one share and a few perks -- provided baseball  
goes along -- but won't have any say over how the club is run or any 
platform for her views. 
</P>
<P>
	After one full-fledged suspension for inflammatory remarks and  
two other disciplinary actions by baseball, the 70-year-old auto 
dealer with a fondness for dogs will no longer be synonymous with 
Cincinnati baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	``She wants the people of Cincinnati and baseball fans  
everywhere to know that she's grateful and loves them one and 
all,'' said her attorney, Frank Kelley. ``She hopes to still have 
time to encourage youngsters to appreciate baseball. She will 
always be a fan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It usually takes baseball's owners six to 15 months to approve a  
team sale, but the Reds' deal is expected to move quickly, perhaps 
with a vote as soon as June. Baseball's approval is the final step 
in the process. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindner and current limited partners George Strike and William  
Reik would buy 5 1/2 of Schott's 6 1/2 shares, including the two 
controlling shares. There are 15 shares under the current 
partnership. 
</P>
<P>
	``Carl Lindner, George Strike and Bill Reik have been excellent  
limited partners in the current partnership,'' NL president Len 
Coleman said. ``I think with their leadership, once the background 
work is done, the fans in Cincinnati will be blessed with a bright 
future for baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schott's sale agreement allows her to keep an office in the  
stadium, a luxury suite and a group of lower-level seats at games, 
according to a source familiar with the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	However, baseball can negate the perks and is likely to at least  
deny her an office at the stadium. Baseball owners want to keep her 
in the background when the team changes hands. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball suspended her for one year in February 1993 and fined  
her $25,000 for language deemed ``racially and ethnically 
offensive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She returned early the following April, but made more  
inflammatory remarks and agreed in June 1996 to give up control of 
the team's day-to-day operations through 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Last October, she agreed to extend the arrangement while she  
tries to sell the team rather than face another suspension for 
allegedly using the names of Reds employees on falsified sales 
records at one of her car dealerships. 
</P>
<P>
	Managing executive John Allen, who has been running the team in  
place of Schott, will remain in charge and Jim Bowden will continue 
as the general manager under the new regime. 
</P>
<P>
	Although players hope that Lindner will pump more money into the  
franchise as it rebuilds towards the opening of a new stadium in 
2003, baseball's approval must come first. 
</P>
<P>
	``Until the change of control is approved by major league  
baseball, I expect we'll operate under the same plan as we have for 
the last three years,'' Allen said. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be a major difference in ownership style. Lindner,  
who owns the Great American Insurance Co., rarely gives interviews 
and prefers to stay in the background, a sharp contrast to Schott's 
love for the spotlight. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindner is expected to remain a behind-the-scenes owner, much  
like the Reds owners who preceded Schott. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that's been his style,'' Bowden said.  
</P>
<P>
	Lindner didn't attend the Reds' 3-2 loss to the New York Mets on  
Tuesday night. Neither did Schott, who usually attends home games 
and sits right behind the Reds' dugout for the last few innings. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been a difficult time for Mrs. Schott,'' her lawyer  
said. ``To own a major league team and not be able to run it has 
been heart-rending. She did not want to sell her interest, which 
has been such an important part of her life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She bought control of the team on Dec. 21, 1984, and became  
chief executive officer the following July. The Reds won the World 
Series in 1990 with a team developed through the farm system, but 
her cutbacks in scouting and the minor leagues began taking a toll. 
</P>
<P>
	Forced to spend on free agents, the Reds' payroll ballooned to  
the second-highest in the National League in 1995, the last time 
they reached the playoffs. The club has failed to contend the last 
three years with reduced payrolls and an unproductive farm system. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great if the people who take over the team are interested  
in restoring what once was here, such as getting some good players 
in here,'' team captain Barry Larkin said. ``What's important is 
what happens on the field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was inevitable that Schott would sell. The team's partnership  
agreement expired at the end of 2000 and the limited partners -- who 
often fought Schott and challenged her in court -- were ready to 
oust her at that time. 
</P>
<P>
	She agreed in February to sell for $65 million to a group headed  
by Larry Dolan, the brother of Cablevision Systems Corp.'s 
chairman. Lindner and the two limited partners then exercised their 
right under the ownership agreement to match the offer and take 
control of the Reds. 
</P>
<P>
	Schott had one last controversy left. She rejected the matching  
offer and tried to sell to her cousin, Steve Schott, for $67 
million. The three limited partners sued Schott and got a court 
order last Friday blocking her deal with her cousin. 
</P>
<P>
	Four days later, she gave up the fight and sold.  
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, Mr. Lindner and the limited partners have  
first-class character and run first-class organizations,'' Bowden 
said. ``I think it's a great day for Cincinnati Reds baseball.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
