<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brit Retailer, Grocery Chain Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP)-- British retailer Kingfisher PLC and grocery chain  
ASDA Group PLC are merging in a deal that values ASDA at about 5.85 
billion pounds, or $9.44 billion, and would create one of Europe's 
leading retailing groups. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company would have sales of more than 17 billion  
pounds, or $27.4 billion, and interests ranging from supermarkets 
to electrical goods shops. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies rejected speculation that the merger was a  
defensive measure against possible European expansion by the 
world's biggest retailer, Wal-Mart Stores Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``The idea that this is a way of keeping out Wal-Mart has never  
cropped up,'' ASDA boss Allan Leighton said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger would involve an exchange of 4.42 Kingfisher shares  
for each share of ASDA. Kingfisher would hold 66.3 percent of the 
combined group, with ASDA holding the remaining 33.7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal would give ASDA shareholders a premium of 12.2 percent  
for ASDA shares. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies expect the merger would eventually create annual  
savings of at least 100 million pounds, or $161 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The merged companies would also be better positioned to  
accelerate expansion in European and other overseas locations, the 
companies said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kingfisher owns the Woolworth and Superdrug chains and a  
do-it-yourself hardware business called B&AMP;Q. 
</P>
<P>
	Kingfisher Chief Executive Sir Geoffrey Mulcahy will hold the  
same role in the merged group. Leighton will be deputy group chief 
executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts have suggested that the merger may be a way of  
defending the market shares of both companies ahead of a possible 
expansion in Europe by Wal-Mart, which is based in Bentonville, 
Ark. 

</P>
</TEXT>
