<DOCNO> APW19990420.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 08:05:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Direct Pay Plan Can Simplify Things </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Q: Just about every monthly bill that comes in the mail offers  
an option for direct payment. Is it risky to let my phone company 
or credit card issuer take money directly from my bank account? 

</P>
<P>
	A: Merchants that offer direct payment -- aka automatic bill  
payment, direct debit and autopayment -- don't actually have direct 
access to your account. 
</P>
<P>
	The payments are handled in the same way as direct deposit for  
paychecks and Social Security checks, using an electronic network 
operated by the Federal Reserve and three private payment 
processors, including Visa USA. 
</P>
<P>
	The network, which is called the Automated Clearing House,  
currently handles electronic transactions among 20,000 financial 
institutions and 500,000 companies. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a 1998 Fed survey, 37 percent of American  
households use direct payment options for their bills. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, there were 1.2 billion direct payment transactions  
worth $678 billion, an 18 percent increase from the previous year, 
according to the National Automated Clearing House Association, a 
not-for-profit industry group that sets rules for the ACH network. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the strong growth, less that 5 percent of all bills are  
paid through the network, says Louis Fuertes, a product manager for 
Chase Manhattan. He notes that 64 billion checks are written 
annually in this country. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Europe, (direct) payment is the norm,'' says Fuertes. ``The  
thought of writing a check in a number of European countries is 
seen as a quaint concept.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although the process is called direct payment, that doesn't mean  
your cable television company or mortgage company has direct access 
to your account and your finances. For each transaction, the vendor 
sends billing information to its own bank, which sends it to your 
bank through the ACH network. 
</P>
<P>
	``The vendor has your authority to debit your account, but it's  
not like an electronic hand that goes into your account,'' says 
NACHA spokesman Michael Herd. ``We don't know of a single case of a 
direct payment or direct deposit being lost or stolen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed survey found that 87 percent of those using direct  
payment said they were extremely satisfied or very satisfied with 
the service. 
</P>
<P>
	Direct payment may not be the best choice for people who live on  
a very tight budget and don't keep a close eye on their account 
balance. 
</P>
<P>
	But direct payment plans can simplify life. There's no  
check-writing, no cost for stamps, no payments lost or delayed in 
the mail, no risk of forgery or theft, and no late-payment fees. 
</P>
<P>
	And for those worried about privacy, direct payment actually may  
be superior to checks, which according to Herd, pass through as 
many as 12 hands from the time they leave your home. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, if there is a discrepancy, direct payments leave a  
clear electronic trail that's easy to trace. 
</P>
<P>
	If there is a dispute, consumers need not be left holding the  
bag while it's being resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	When a complaint is registered within 60 days of the debit, Fed  
regulations require the consumer's money be returned while any 
investigation is conducted, says Mary O'Toole, a product manager 
for Chase. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
