<DOCNO> APW19990420.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 13:45:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Game Asks 'Loaded Questions' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The questions are personal, hypothetical,  
devil-may-care -- designed to amuse, provoke and titillate. Don't 
expect to furrow your brow, tilt your head back and gaze skyward 
for the answer. 
</P>
<P>
	Trivial Pursuit, this is not.  
</P>
<P>
	The creator of Loaded Questions says there are no wrong answers  
to the questions he poses. No wrong answer? 
</P>
<P>
	``If you were forced to kill one person living today, at your  
discretion, who would it be?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Where Trivial Pursuit comes up with brain teasers -- What country  
calls its organized crime the Yakuza? What mile-wide break in the 
Zambezi River has been dubbed ``smoke that thunders''? -- Loaded 
Questions often has no brainers. 
</P>
<P>
	Like this probing question: What is the longest you've gone  
without taking a shower? 
</P>
<P>
	Loaded Questions encourages players to give personal answers to  
more than 500 questions posed in a Trivial Pursuit-type setup. (The 
Yakuza are found in Japan; Victoria Falls is the smoke that 
thunders.) 
</P>
<P>
	In less than two years, more than 50,000 copies of Loaded  
Questions have been sold nationwide, and its creator, Eric Poses, 
has just finished production on another game. 
</P>
<P>
	Poses never planned on creating board games for a living. Until  
a few years ago, he didn't really know what he wanted to do. ``I've 
had a lot of wacky ideas that never materialized into anything,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But in 1996, while waiting for a girlfriend at Miami  
International Airport, Poses said he was thinking about what they 
would talk about. A question popped into his mind: ``If you became 
president of the United States, what would be the first measure you 
would enact while in office?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The relationship didn't last, but the question did. And it  
inspired the now 25-year-old Emory University graduate to create 
Loaded Questions. 
</P>
<P>
	A person rolls the die, then reads a card corresponding to the  
topic that they land on. Players secretly write down answers to the 
question, and the roller must guess who wrote which answer, 
advancing through the board with each correct guess. The player who 
advances to the end wins. 
</P>
<P>
	The questions are divided into four color-coded categories --  
hypothetical, anything goes, no brainers and personals. They range 
from ``If you were invisible, where would you go?'' to ``If you 
could change one thing about the way you look, what would it be?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think most people like to talk about themselves, and the  
game allows that,'' Poses said. ``People don't feel stupid playing 
the game. You definitely know the answer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Poses said he didn't include any questions about sex or drugs  
because he wanted it to be a game that families could play 
together. 
</P>
<P>
	Cheryl Stern, president of The Game Keeper, a nationwide chain  
of game stores, said she played Loaded Questions with nine other 
people before deciding to put it in her stores. 
</P>
<P>
	``We loved it,'' she said. ``We decided immediately that it  
should go in our stores. The questions are interesting and you can 
learn about people really quickly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than 1,150 stores across the country, including Toys R Us,  
carry copies of the game, which has a suggested retail of $25, 
although some sell it for less. After production costs, Poses 
clears about $5 a game. 
</P>
<P>
	The game industry is tough to break into because of the hundreds  
of new games developed every year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would consider him a great success,'' said Rick Loomis,  
president of the Game Manufacturer's Association based in 
Scottsdale, Ariz. ``He's one in 100, maybe one in 1,000'' to sell 
so many games in such a short time. 
</P>
<P>
	Poses formed his own company, All Things Equal, Inc., and  
initially printed 5,000 games at a cost of about $45,000 -- his 
parents helped with about two-thirds of that amount. His company 
has had sales of about $600,000 so far, and he has since paid them 
back. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Poses had a good idea for a game, he backed it up with  
hard work. He researched his game by studying other question-based 
board games. He also referred to a color harmony book that helped 
him decide on a blue board with orange, purple, yellow and blue 
spaces. 
</P>
<P>
	In April 1997, he took to the road in his Honda Accord for a  
13,000-mile, four-month, 32-city tour. In each town, he went 
door-to-door to small toy stores to peddle his game, and contacted 
the local media hoping for some free press. He sat down with 
reporters in 12 cities. 
</P>
<P>
	All the while, Poses was calling Toys R Us representatives. He  
finally was able to sit down with a board member, and the chain 
picked up his game in December 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was always confident of the product,'' Poses said. ``It was  
just the matter of getting a break.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Poses has already come up with 300 more questions for a second  
edition of the game, which he expects to release in a few years. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, he is promoting his newest game, Group Photo, a  
children's card game that is part gin rummy, part Concentration. 
About 10,000 copies were printed on the first run of that game, of 
which he sold about 1,500 copies and donated 6,500 to 30 chapters 
of Make A Wish Foundation and to children's hospitals throughout 
the country. He recently finished a second production run on Group 
Photo. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with his continued success in the gaming industry, Poses is  
still a one-man operation working out of his apartment on South 
Beach in Miami Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd love to sell 100,000 games,'' he said. ``At the pace I'm  
going now, I think it's possible.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990420.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 18:11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Red Wings Begin Quest for Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	There's a reason Detroit is known as ``Hockeytown'' -- an  
illustrious history that includes nine Stanley Cups and such 
players as Gordie Howe and Terry Sawchuk. 
</P>
<P>
	One thing the Red Wings have yet to accomplish: winning three  
straight championships. 
</P>
<P>
	They'll begin that mission when they open the playoffs on  
Wednesday night against the Anaheim Mighty Ducks in one of four 
first-round games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're deeper than we ever have been in past years in every  
position,'' goaltender Chris Osgood said. ``(But) if you don't play 
well, you're going to get knocked out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other first-round games on Wednesday, it's Edmonton at  
Dallas, San Jose at Colorado and Buffalo at Ottawa. The playoffs 
continue on Thursday with Pittsburgh at New Jersey, Philadelphia at 
Toronto, Boston at Carolina and St. Louis at Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings won't have an easy time getting back to the  
finals. Two of the best teams in the NHL are in the Western 
Conference -- the league-leading Dallas Stars and Colorado 
Avalanche, who had a great second half. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at every (team) out there in the West, it's going  
to be a battle,'' defenseman Larry Murphy said. ``You can't take 
anything for granted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings' first-round opponents present a major obstacle.  
The Mighty Ducks feature two 100-point scorers on their top line, 
league-leading scorer Teemu Selanne and Paul Kariya. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to slow them down,'' center Kris Draper said. ``Our  
job is to go out and play as physical on those guys as we can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nor are the Stars taking the Oilers for granted -- particularly  
after what happened two years ago when Edmonton knocked them out of 
the playoffs in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	``We learned a lot from that thing that happened two years  
ago,'' Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``We know not to overlook 
anybody. We learned our lesson.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides, finishing with the best record in the NHL guarantees  
nothing. Ask the Red Wings, who won a record 62 games in the 
1995-96 season, yet were knocked out of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 30 years since expansion, less than half the teams that  
had the highest point total in the regular season managed to win 
the Cup. The last was the New York Rangers in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being the No. 1 seed is a burden you have to accept,''  
Hitchcock said. ``You know that going in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Dominik Hasek playing for Buffalo and Ron Tugnutt for  
Ottawa, goals figure to be rare in the Sabres-Senators series. 
Hasek is generally considered to be the best goalie in the league, 
and Tugnutt had the best goals-against average. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've played a lot against Dominik Hasek,'' Senators forward  
Shawn McEachern said. ``We aren't expecting any high-scoring 
games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The teams played five times this season, resulting in four ties  
and a 3-2 overtime victory for Ottawa. 
</P>
<P>
	The Avalanche took the season series over San Jose 3-1, and have  
been on a tear in the second half after starting slowly. They 
finished the season with a 9-2-1 record, while the Sharks won only 
one of their last five games (1-3-1). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
