<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Rebounding From Poor Day / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, with technology stocks  
showing signs of recovery from Monday's rout but blue chips losing 
more ground. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 34.93 at 10,405.60 after having fallen 53 points on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq composite index was up 32.02 at 2,377.63 after  
plunging 5.6 percent Monday amid a sharp selloff in 
Internet-related shares. 
</P>
<P>
	High-profile technology stocks that took big hits Monday were  
mostly higher. Microsoft led the Nasdaq trading in volume and was 
up 1 33/64 at 82 33/64. Dell, Intel and Cisco were all higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet shares, which were pounded sharply lower on Monday,  
were recovering too, with Amazon.com up 9 1/16 at 168. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think the tech group will stay down. This is just a  
normal pause to refresh,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, chief market 
strategist, A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc., St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Belski, chief investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP;  
Co., in Kansas City, Mo., said he was encouraged at signs of gentle 
recovery in tech stocks after Monday's debacle. Investors embarked 
on the day expecting a recovery in tech shares, so they placed some 
bets in that stock sector. 
</P>
<P>
	``When tech stocks cratered yesterday, investors in general had  
someplace else to go,'' Belski said. ``While the vim and vigor is 
not present on this upside bounce that was there in other 
recoveries in the tech sector, it's good that people have 
alternatives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While technology stocks recovered, industrial shares, which have  
been popular purchases for more than a week, were lower today. One 
of the biggest decliners was United Technologies, which fell 4 1/4 to 
140 3/4 despite reporting better-than-expected earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Ricky Harrington, a technical analyst at Wachovia Securities in  
Charlotte, N.C., said attributed some of the blue-chip decline to 
profit taking. 
</P>
<P>
	``But there is also a little bit of apprehension out there,'' he  
said. ``The fall in technology stocks over the last few sessions 
has created caution elsewhere in the market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are in a transition period and no one is sure what is  
coming next,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by 4-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 477 million shares, 
down from 462 million shares on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 10.94 at 1,300.42, the  
NYSE composite index was up 3.55 at 619.43, and the Amex composite 
index was unchanged at 735.11. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
