<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 12:15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Shots Fired at Colorado High School  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Two young men dressed in long, black  
trench coats opened fire in a suburban Denver high school today, 
scattering students as gunshots ricocheted off lockers, witnesses 
said. At least three students were injured. There were also reports 
of explosions in the school, which was ringed by ambulances and 
police officers at lunchtime. The location of the gunmen was not 
immediately known. ``We found out that our physics teacher was shot 
in the cafeteria,'' said Kaley Boyle, a junior at Columbine. ``One 
kid got shot in the library. We heard the gunshots and we were 
running.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Allies Urged on Economic War  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Clinton administration officials said today  
they will use this week's NATO summit to push for allied agreement 
on economic sanctions including an oil embargo to deny Yugoslavia 
the ability to wage war in Kosovo. NATO allies remain ``rock 
solid'' behind the goal of the month-old airstrikes to continue the 
campaign until the Serb military halts attacks on ethnic Albanians 
in the Serbian province, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright 
declared at a White House news conference with President Clinton's 
foreign policy team. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Notes 'Disturbing Developments'  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO is reporting ``disturbing  
developments'' -- reports ``too numerous'' to ignore -- of Serb 
soldiers raping ethnic Albanian women and using tear gas to move 
ethnic Albanians out of their homes in Pristina. NATO spokesman 
Jamie Shea said Serb military and paramilitary forces were staging 
``safari-style'' operations, shelling hills where ethnic Albanians 
fled to flush them out, marching the refugees on roads, putting 
them on trains to the border and then closing the border to them. 
Shea told reporters at NATO headquarters that the alliance was 
investigating reports of ethnic Albanians used as ``human shields 
in front of tanks,'' mass executions, and ethnic cleansing 
operations spreading from Kosovo into border villages of 
Montenegro, Yugoslavia's smaller republic. 

</P>
<P>
	IMF Hopeful About Economic Crisis  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The International Monetary Fund reported today  
that ``significant positive developments'' in the world economy 
this year raise hopes that the worst may be over for a financial 
crisis that pushed one-third of the globe into recession. In its 
latest ``World Economic Outlook,'' the IMF insisted there are still 
plenty of threats around. But for the first time since the crisis 
erupted, it was able to revise its previous growth forecast 
slightly upward. The IMF said it believes the global economy will 
expand by 2.3 percent this year, just 0.1 percentage point higher 
than a forecast it made four months ago. 

</P>
<P>
	Queen Elizabeth Visits South Korea  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Queen Elizabeth II dined with South  
Korea's top executives and visited firms with British ties in a 
tour today aimed at improving business links between South Korea 
and Britain. About 30 British executives are accompanying the queen 
and her husband, Prince Philip, on the first visit to Korea by a 
British monarch. The emphasis was on increasing South Korean 
investment in Britain, currently totaling $1.5 billion, and 
promoting British goods. South Korea is Britain's 15th largest 
export market. 

</P>
<P>
	Waitress Must Share $10M Lottery  
</P>
<P>
	MOBILE, Ala. (AP) -- A former waitress who was given a Florida  
lottery ticket worth $10 million as a tip must share her winnings 
with four Waffle House co-workers, a jury said today. Circuit Judge 
Robert Kendall adopted the jury's advisory verdict and gave 
attorneys several days to tell him how they would divide the money 
among the five people. There was no immediate word on any appeal. 
Tonda Dickerson, who will have to share the $10 million, rushed out 
of the courtroom without comment. Mrs. Dickerson's Waffle House 
co-workers had testified that there was a share-the-wealth plan and 
that in conversations around the hot grill they often discussed how 
they would spend the money. 

</P>
