<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 15:25:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trainer Charlie Whittingham Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Charlie Whittingham, one of the greatest  
trainers in thoroughbred racing and twice a winner of the Kentucky 
Derby, died Tuesday of leukemia. He was 86. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-time Eclipse Award winner was taken from his home in  
Sierra Madre by ambulance to Saint Luke Medical Center in Pasadena 
at 6:30 a.m. He died about 8:30 a.m., said his wife, Peggy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a birthday party for him last week. And he was able to  
go to the races on Sunday, when he had two horses running,'' Mrs. 
Whittingham said. ``The doctor told me that sometimes when you get 
an infection like leukemia, the system just can't fight it. He was 
having trouble breathing this morning and I called the Sierra Madre 
ambulance people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A crusty ex-Marine with a quick wit and sharp tongue,  
Whittingham had a 62-year career as a trainer. He prepared more 
than 2,500 winners, with two of the biggest being Derby winners 
Ferdinand (1986) and Sunday Silence (1989). Ferdinand made him, at 
73, the oldest trainer to win the Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	He was oldest again at 76 when Patrick Valenzuela rode Sunday  
Silence, who also won the 1989 Preakness. Sunday Silence was a 
distant second to Easy Goer in the Belmont Stakes, bidding for 
racing's Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	After two of his colts were Kentucky Derby disappointments in  
the 1950s, Whittingham decided to stay away from the race until he 
had a chance to win. That absence lasted 26 years. 
</P>
<P>
	He returned to Churchill Downs with Ferdinand, ridden by Bill  
Shoemaker, jockey for Whittingham on more than 200 stakes 
victories. Riding Ferdinand at 54, he became the Kentucky Derby's 
oldest winning rider. 
</P>
<P>
	``He liked the way I handled the horses and got the run out of  
them, didn't abuse them or override them. And I liked the way he 
trained 'em,'' Shoemaker said Tuesday. ``We had a good chemistry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shoemaker recalled that Whittingham brought him to see Ferdinand  
as a 2-year-old, before the horse had been raced. 
</P>
<P>
	``He took me around to his stall and there was a big chestnut  
beautiful colt in the stall and he said, `We're going to have some 
fun with this horse. I think that we'll probably win the Derby with 
him.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Whittingham seemed to get the most out of horses, said  
Shoemaker, who became a trainer himself after retiring as the 
jockey with the most career victories. 
</P>
<P>
	Whittingham's son and fellow trainer, Michael, took over most of  
the direction of the Whittingham barn in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	Until this week, Whittingham was out working with horses every  
morning, and for decades he was at the track by about 4 a.m. daily, 
Shoemaker said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess he'd been around horses all his life and through trial  
and error you learn how to deal with them and get through to them 
and think like they do and get the most out of them,'' Shoemaker 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Born April 13, 1913, in San Diego, Whittingham was inducted into  
racing's Hall of Fame in 1974. He was the leading trainer in career 
victories at both Santa Anita and Hollywood Park. 
</P>
<P>
	He won thoroughbred racing Eclipse Awards as top trainer in  
1971, 1982 and 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Other champions trained by Whittingham included: Porterhouse,  
champion 2-year-old, 1953; sprinter Ack Ack, Horse of the Year, 
1971; filly Turkish Trousers, champion 3-year-old, 1971; Cougar, 
turf champion, 1972; Perrault, turf champion, 1982; Estrapade, 
female turf champion, 1986; Miss Alleged, female turf champion, 
1991, and Flawlessly, female turf champion, 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	He held the national earnings title seven times, from 1970-73,  
1975, and 1981-82. His top earnings year was 1989 -- $11.4 million. 
More than 20 of the horses he trained had career earnings over $1 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	He was also the leading career trainer at Santa Anita and  
Hollywood Park. On Feb. 9, 1987, he became one of only five 
trainers to win four races in a day at Santa Anita. 
</P>
<P>
	His training career began in the 1930s but was interrupted by  
World War II. He saw action with the Marine Corps at Guadalcanal, 
and contracted malaria, 
</P>
<P>
	In 1946, Whittingham went to work as an assistant to trainer  
Horatio Luro in New York. Two years later, he split with Luro and 
went on his own. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the owners whose horses were trained by Whittingham is  
Burt Bacharach, the composer-singer of numerous hit songs. 
</P>
<P>
	One day Bacharach didn't like the way one of his horses ran, and  
he asked Whittingham if the animal needed to be wormed. 
</P>
<P>
	Whittingham's reply, Jay Hovdey wrote in the 1993 book,  
``Whittingham: The Story of Thoroughbred Racing Legend,'' was 
itself legendary: 
</P>
<P>
	``Burt, I haven't heard too many hit songs coming out of your  
piano lately. Maybe you need to get that piano wormed.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
