<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NHL May Back Lemieux Ownership Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The NHL is expected to back Mario Lemieux's  
ownership bid for the bankrupt Pittsburgh Penguins and hinted it 
could revoke the team's franchise if he does not gain control. 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL plans to file legal documents Friday supporting the  
Lemieux group and offering to work with him to get the Penguins out 
of bankruptcy, league and legal sources close to the proceedings 
told The Associated Press. The NHL wants the matter settled by June 
at the latest, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	The league is eager for a new owner -- Lemieux -- and a  
reorganization plan to be in place by then so budgets for the 
1999-2000 season can be made, players can be signed and season 
tickets can be sold. 
</P>
<P>
	For that reason, the league is discouraging Florida investment  
banker Chip Gesner from submitting a bid, one that might further 
slow the process, the sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people could buy the Penguins, but one person can  
save them: Mario Lemieux,'' Penguins spokesman Tom McMillan said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Bernard Markovitz has scheduled a  
hearing on Lemieux's takeover bid for April 30. Markovitz has no 
obligation to follow the NHL's advice and choose the Lemieux group, 
but the league does have some leverage. 
</P>
<P>
	If the NHL does not agree with the choice of owners, it could  
reject the judge's recommendation and revoke the franchise, 
essentially making it worthless. 
</P>
<P>
	William Daly, the NHL's vice president for legal affairs, said  
the revocation of the franchise is an unwanted but valid way for 
the league to settle the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the NHL constitution, the Penguins' players then could be  
distributed throughout the league or the franchise could be awarded 
to a new city. 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL has not set a firm date to resolve the Penguins'  
situation, but the next step could be to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anything that sets a deadline ... is positive to keeping the  
Penguins in Pittsburgh,'' McMillan said. ``We've been in bankruptcy 
since October and time is of the essence. In the NHL, next season 
begins in June. We have to make decisions about payroll and the 
budget and about signing players. And we've got to sell tickets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since Lemieux retired after the 1996-97 season and the Penguins'  
financial situation worsened, the team's season-ticket base has 
dropped from 12,000 to 8,300. By contrast, expansion franchises 
must guarantee season-ticket sales of 12,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't have another disastrous season ticket-selling  
season,'' McMillan said. ``If Mario's group gets in there, there 
are a lot of things that could be done right away to sell 
tickets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest hangup to reorganizing the Penguins' finances is the  
lack of a new lease with Spectacor Management Group, which operates 
the Civic Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite playing in the NHL's oldest arena, the Penguins' pay the  
steepest annual rent, an estimated $6 million to $7 million that is 
blamed for much of the team's financial problems. The lease was 
renegotiated several times under co-owner Howard Baldwin to supply 
cash needed to keep the team going. 
</P>
<P>
	Privately, the Lemieux group is hopeful that the threat of the  
Penguins folding or being relocated will be enough to spur city and 
county officials into pressuring SMG to renegotiate. However, 
lawyers for Lemieux and co-owner Roger Marino said the lease talks 
have gone nowhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Regardless, Lemieux remains optimistic he will become the first  
former player in the history of modern major pro sports in the 
United States to buy his former team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand that Wayne (Gretzky) might want to someday,''  
Lemieux said. ``Maybe we could go at it someday as owners the way 
we did as players.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
