<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 01:53:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fires May Burn 40,000 More Acres </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- An erratic 130,000-acre wildfire that has roared  
through the Everglades could devour another 40,000 acres before it 
is contained, officials warned. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters were monitoring the blaze early today while hoping  
that barriers created with controlled burns would stop its 
progress. 
</P>
<P>
	Late Monday, the flames reached the Miccosukee Indian  
Reservation, threatening several hunting camps and shacks, said 
John Fish of the state Division of Forestry. No injuries were 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Just to the north, the blaze was about two miles east of the Big  
Cypress Seminole Indian Reservation. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, smoke from the fire blanketed Interstate 75 -- south  
Florida's main east-west highway -- and forced authorities to keep 
about 60 miles of it closed. The road, known as Alligator Alley, 
could be closed for days, said Florida Highway Patrol Lt. Greg 
Edwards. 
</P>
<P>
	In communities immediately east of the fire -- about 25 miles  
northwest of Miami -- people with asthma, bronchitis and emphysema 
were urged to stay indoors if possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials expected erratic winds and dry weather to remain in  
the coming days, making new fires quick to start and difficult to 
fight. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire began in the eastern Everglades late last week,  
possibly ignited by heat from a vehicle's catalytic converter. 
Aided by swirling winds, it quickly became the largest of at least 
2,515 fires that have burned in Florida this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Emergency Management Agency announced Monday that it  
was adding the Everglades fire and another blaze in the Panhandle 
to a list of fires chosen for fire suppression assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement brought to six the number of Florida fires  
recently approved for this type of federal aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
