<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 14:45:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Multiple Golf Titles Hard To Win  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Greg Norman walked up the 18th fairway with the Masters champion  
for the second time in four years. If Davis Love III had birdied 
the two reachable par-5s on the back nine of Augusta National, 
perhaps he could have worn the green jacket. 
</P>
<P>
	A week later in the MCI Classic, Payne Stewart was in a familiar  
role -- complimenting someone else's final round and offering 
congratulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Three players, two weeks, one common denominator.  
</P>
<P>
	Winning is the best way to measure success, and all three have  
had their share. Together, they have won 42 tour events and five 
majors. 
</P>
<P>
	But as golf has become deeper in talent and multiple wins have  
become a rarity, there is rarely enough appreciation for 
consistently being in the hunt. 
</P>
<P>
	Of active players with at least 10 years' experience on the PGA  
Tour, no one has done that as well as these three. 
</P>
<P>
	For Stewart, who lost the MCI Classic in a playoff to Glen Day,  
it was the 25th time in his career that he has finished second. 
</P>
<P>
	Norman finished third at Augusta, but he's no stranger to second  
place. Among active players, only Tom Watson has as many runner-up 
finishes (31) on the PGA Tour. Eight of Norman's seconds have come 
in the majors, and he's the only player to lose all four majors in 
a playoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Love was the Masters runner-up for the second time in five  
years. He has finished second 14 times in his career, three of them 
this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm disappointed I didn't win,'' Love said. ``But I'm pleased  
to have played another Masters and to have a chance to get nervous 
on the weekend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is no substitute for winning. Day made that clear when he  
choked back tears after his first PGA Tour victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, anything less is too often perceived as failure.  
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, Tiger Woods won once, was second twice and third  
twice. He had more top 10s than anyone (13), but was hounded by 
questions about his ``slump.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Duval can appreciate the feeling. He was the ultimate PGA  
Tour bridesmaid for nearly three years -- seven times a runner-up 
from 1995 until he finished the 1997 season with three straight 
victories. He took a lead into the final round five times without 
winning during those ``lean'' years, and never once considered 
himself a failure. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was being criticized for not having won,'' Duval said at the  
beginning of the year, before his 59 or the four wins that pushed 
his count to 11. ``It's kind of like if you don't win, you're a 
bum. What about kids who are coming up who don't have as much 
talent as some other people? They gave their heart, busted their 
tail, finished third, had a great golf tournament. That's not 
failing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duval then pointed to the year-by-year listing in the PGA Tour  
media guide that shows number of victories, second- and third-place 
finishes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The next stat they show is top 10s,'' he said. ``Why is that?  
Because top 10 is a good week out here. It's good playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	How good?  
</P>
<P>
	Consider the following statistical review, in which 10 points  
were awarded for a victory, five points for second, three points 
for third and one point for a top 10. An additional 10 points were 
given for each major. 
</P>
<P>
	The total points were then divided by the number of years on  
tour, and yielded the following results: 
</P>
<P>
	--Watson, who turns 50 in September, averaged 31.4 points per  
season and was the highest ranked among active players on the 
strength of his 34 victories, eight majors and 31 second-place 
finishes. 
</P>
<P>
	--Norman, who joined the tour in 1983, was second at 29.9 points.  
While Norman has won 18 times and has only two majors, he has 
matched Watson's total of runner-up finishes in only 17 years on 
tour. 
</P>
<P>
	--Stewart was third at 24.1 points per year. Along with 10  
victories (two majors) and 25 seconds, Stewart has finished third 
20 times. Only Watson and Tom Kite have more seconds and thirds 
combined. 
</P>
<P>
	--Love has been so good for so long that it's hard to believe he  
just turned 35. With 13 wins and 14 seconds, he was fourth at 23.9. 
</P>
<P>
	Duval and Woods were both around 40, although neither has been  
on tour longer than five years. Ernie Els was at 24.5 points in his 
sixth year on tour. 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Nicklaus clocked in at 42.1, which accounts for every year  
through 1998. While his record of 18 professional majors might 
never be broken, it should be noted that Nicklaus finished second 
19 times in the majors alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
