<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 23:42:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Wants Boost for Broadcasters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- The nation's top airwaves regulator wants to  
give broadcasters greater flexibility to own more TV and radio 
stations, ensuring that the public continues to have diverse 
sources for news and entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	``My challenge this year is for you to join with me in crafting  
commonsense ownership rule relief,'' Bill Kennard, chairman of the 
Federal Communications Commission, told broadcasters Tuesday at the 
industry's annual convention. 
</P>
<P>
	The broadcast industry has been at odds with the FCC over how to  
ease rules that limit the number of local TV and radio stations 
that a single company can control. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadcasters say they need regulatory relief to better compete  
against cable TV, satellite TV, the Internet and other media and 
entertainment providers, which aren't subject to the same ownership 
restrictions. Owning more local TV and radio stations in the same 
market would produce business efficiencies that would allow 
broadcasters to offer new programs and services, they argue. 
</P>
<P>
	But deregulation opponents say allowing companies to own more  
local stations would threaten editorial diversity. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennard acknowledged that in today's marketplace broadcast  
owners need ``flexibility'' to seize on opportunities and ``be a 
player in the information age,'' 
</P>
<P>
	While FCC officials have said they want to produce a final plan  
on new ownership rules in a couple of months, Kennard didn't 
specify what such a plan would do or whether it would resemble a 
proposal offered by commission staff last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The staff proposal would make it easier for some broadcasters to  
own more media properties, but also would require others to divest 
some stations. Many broadcasters and key Republican lawmakers in 
Congress opposed the plan, saying it doesn't give broadcasters 
enough regulatory relief. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., chairman of the Senate Commerce  
Committee and presidential contender, said he plans to hold 
hearings next month on broadcast ownership and on ways to increase 
minority ownership of the airwaves. McCain, who supports giving 
broadcasters freedom from ownership rules, made his remarks in a 
taped speech Tuesday beamed into the convention by satellite. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain also said he intends to offer legislation to bolster  
airwaves ownership by revising the now-defunct ``tax certificate,'' 
which gave a tax break to broadcasters who sold stations to 
minorities. Congress repealed that provision several years ago, 
citing abuses. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1996 telecommunications law eased some ownership restrictions  
but required the commission to consider changing, or even 
eliminating, other limits because of competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Those rules prohibit a single company from owning more than one  
local TV station in a given market or from owning a TV station and 
a radio station in the same market unless the FCC grants a waiver. 
</P>
<P>
	The major broadcast networks, meanwhile, want the FCC to  
eliminate or loosen a rule limiting them to owning stations that 
reach no more than 35 percent of all TV viewers in an area-- 
something their affiliates oppose. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some say we should just eliminate all of these rules, just  
sweep them away, get rid of everything,'' Kennard said. ``I don't 
think that's the right answer, frankly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another crucial matter for broadcasters is whether the FCC will  
continue to let companies enter into local marketing agreements 
that allows one TV station to operate another TV station in the 
same market, but not own it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
